<HEADLINE> Int'l Environmental Meeting Begins In Bangladesh </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, September 14 (Xinhua) -- Environmental Journalists,
activists and experts from some 30 countries gathering in Comilla,
about 200 km southeast of Dhaka began a four-day conference
Tuesday focusing on a wide range of conservation concerns.
</P>
<P>
The theme of the conference, being held under the joint
auspices of the Asia-Pacific Forum of Environmental Journalists
(AFEJ), Commonwealth Environmental Journalists Association (CEJA)
and Forum of Environmental Journalists of Bangladesh (FEJB), is
"Water and Environment: Role of the media."
</P>
<P>
AZM Enayetullah Khan, a veteran Bangladeshi journalist and
Editor-in-Chief of the weekly Holiday, said media in Bangladesh
has been highlighting the environmental issues not only for
purpose of dissemination of information, but also as an active
agent in awareness.
</P>
<P>
But he added that the media also has a significant rule in
highlighting the civic concerns of the flood action plan
pertaining to the local population and their voiced needs.
</P>
<P>
Mahfuz Anam, who won the Green Pen Award 1999, said one of the
challenges of present-day newsmen is creating awareness about
environmental issues.
</P>
<P>
Anam, Editor of The Daily Star of Bangladesh, noted that the
media can play a great rule in protecting the country's
environment, adding that the newsmen will have to change their
mindset to perform their social responsibilities. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
