<DOCNO> XIE19990915.0007 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Feature: U.N. Bell Rings for World Peace </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, September 14 (Xinhua) -- The autumn morning
sunlights are caressing the Peace Bell Pavilion in the complex of
the United Nations headquarters in New York. Standing in the
breeze on the front lawn, 10 boys and girls are playing violin for
peace and friendship.
</P>
<P>
The blue U.N. flag and national colors of 185 member states are
flying high against the white clouds and blue sky in the sunny
morning of the 1999 International Peace Day, which falls on
September 14. The audience, representing different cultures and
varying countries, applauded the performance.
</P>
<P>
U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan rang the Peace Bell at 10:00
a.m. EST, and the bell sang in a universal language -- peace for
the world, peace for mankind.
</P>
<P>
"Each year, as we ring the Peace Bell, we reflect on the
meaning of peace and reaffirm our commitment to work in
partnership with others in pursuit of this universal objective,"
Annan said at the brief ceremony.
</P>
<P>
"Today the ringing of the Peace Bell coincides with the
launching by UNESCO (the United Nations Educational, Scientific
and Cultural Organization) of the International Year for the
Culture of Peace," he said.
</P>
<P>
"Why a culture of peace?" he said. "Because war, violence
poverty and prejudice are the daily experience of millions upon
millions of people throughout the world."
</P>
<P>
"Over the years, we have come to realize that it is not enough
to send peacekeeping forces to separate warring parties," he
said. "It is not enough to engage in peace-building efforts, after
armed conflicts have taken place. It is not enough to conduct
preventive diplomacy."
</P>
<P>
"All of this is essential work, but we must also act at a
deeper level. We need, in short, a culture of peace," he said.
"Let us all join in working for a culture of peace," and "let the
message of this Peace Bell be heard far and wide today and
throughout the year."
</P>
<P>
The Peace Bell rang one day after the 53rd General Assembly
session adopted a resolution on "the Declaration and Program of
Action on a Culture of Peace," which says, "A culture of peace is
a set of values, attitudes, traditions and modes of behavior and
ways of life."
</P>
<P>
The president of the Security Council, Arnold Peter van Walsum
of the Netherlands, also delivered a speech at the ceremony.
"Finding peaceful solutions to conflicts is not something that
comes naturally," he said. "In a large number of countries, for a
large number of people, peace is not the norm. War and destruction
are all these people have ever known."
</P>
<P>
"Peace for them is only a word," he said. "Their reality is
violence, injustice, violations of human rights. They have no idea
that peace feels, looks and sounds like."
</P>
<P>
For this year, peace becomes much more precious for the world
after the United States led NATO in the 78-day air strikes on
Yugoslavia, a sovereign member of the U.N. family.
</P>
<P>
Under the Charter, the U.N. Security Council has the primary
responsibility for the maintenance of peace and security in the
world at large. However, NATO, without the authorization of the
Security Council, waged the unilateral air strikes on the Balkan
country, undermining the principle of the Charter and the
authority of the 15-nation Council.
</P>
<P>
The violin players are of the Chinese, Japanese, Spanish and
Korean origins, with the youngest of them at the age of six. The
youngest player is only six. That is, she is 10 years junior of
the oldest in the musical group.
</P>
<P>
The ring of the Peace Bell also coincides with the opening of
the 54th General Assembly session, during which 39 heads of state
and 25 heads of government, among others, are expected to take the
floor at the general debate, slated for September 20, to voice
their various stance on what role the U.N. will play in the next
century. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
