<HEADLINE> Poll: Most Quebecers Opposed to Separation Referendum </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, September 14 (Xinhua) -- The latest poll shows that 68.2
percent of the surveyed 1,014 Quebecers are opposed to a third
separation oriented referendum, Canada's National Post daily reported
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Citing the results released Monday by the polling firm Sondagen,
the newspaper also said that 59 percent of the respondents surveyed
between August 27 and September 8 hold that Lucien Bouchard, the
Quebec premier, will fail to assemble what he termed as "winning
conditions" for the next referendum.
</P>
<P>
Bouchard was reported to prepare for the referendum by the end of
his government's mandate, which could go until November 2003, but with
a promise not to hold one without "winning conditions."
</P>
<P>
Canadian Prime Minister Jean Chretien Monday said he was ready for
the referendum just hours before flying to Japan to join Bouchard and
other Canadian provincial premiers on a week-long trade mission.
</P>
<P>
"I hope that they will listen to the people of Quebec and not
have a referendum," the prime minister said, adding that "for me,
I will be ready," the newspaper quoted him as saying. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
