<HEADLINE> Simitis, Clerides Discuss Cyprus Problem </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, September 14 (Xinhua) -- Greek Prime Minister Costas
Simitis discussed here Tuesday with visiting Cypriot President
Glafcos Clerides the latest developments in efforts to settle the
protracted Cyprus problem.
</P>
<P>
The two men also examined defense cooperation between the two
countries in the framework of the joint defense pact.
</P>
<P>
Both sides reached a consensus that the Greek Cypriot side,
which is ready for talks with the aim of seeking a solution to the
Cyprus issue, wanted to restart its dialogue with the Turkish
Cypriots without preconditions in the framework of the U.N.
decisions.
</P>
<P>
Speaking after their talks, Simitis said that Greece and the
international community placed great weight on the position to be
taken by the Turkish side, expecting it to show that it respected
the international community and its decisions.
</P>
<P>
He noted that this element would play a definitive role in
ensuring Turkey's accession towards the European Union (EU).
</P>
<P>
On his part, Clerides, who arrived here Monday, said that his
talks with Simitis resulted in unanimous conclusions as to how to
deal with the issue of beginning and duration of the talks on the
Cyprus issue.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has been divided into the Greek Cypriots-controlled
south and the Turkish Cypriots-dominated north since 1974 when
Turkish troops invaded and occupied the northern third of the
island in the wake of a failed coup seeking union with Athens.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
