<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-14 16:29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israel, PNA Discuss "Safe Passage" Issue </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, September 14 (Xinhua) -- Israeli-Palestinan Joint
Committee on Safe Passage on Tuesday committed to strike a deal on
the opening of the "safe passage" linking the Gaza Strip and West
Bank by the end of this month.
</P>
<P>
In a meeting held in Tel Aviv Tuesday afternoon, the committee
discussed in detail about the opening of the safe passage linking
Gaza and Hebron, but members from the two sides are still at odds
over some relevant issues such as car registrations, Israel's
stoppage of suspects and security inspection by the Israeli
security forces, Israel Radio said.
</P>
<P>
The Radio quoted Israeli officials as saying that the
committee could solve all those differences soon and the safe
passage could be opened by next month as stipulated by the Sharm
El Sheikh peace deal.
</P>
<P>
The peace deal, which was signed by Palestinian leader Yasser
Arafat and Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak last Sunday in Egypt,
stipulates the safe passage linking Gaza and Hebron should be
opened by October 1.
</P>
<P>
Hebron is a Palestinian-controlled city in the south of the
West Bank. About 130,000 Palestinians are living in the city.
</P>
<P>
Under the peace deal, Israel and Palestine launched their
final-status talks at Erez checkpoint Monday evening. The deal
asks the two sides to reach a statement of principles on
final-status talks in five months and a final-status accord by
September 13, 2000.
</P>
<P>
During the final-status talks, the two sides have to solve
such most thorny issues as the status of Jerusalem, borders, the
future of the Jewish settlements on the occupied land in the West
Bank and Gaza Strip and the fate of over 3 million Palestinian
refugees as stipulated by the Oslo Accord signed six years ago.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
