<HEADLINE> Cyprus, US Sign Extradition Treaty </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, September 14 (Xinhua) -- Cyprus and the U.S. signed
here Tuesday a new extradition treaty and initialled a Mutual
Legal Assistance Treaty (MLAT).
</P>
<P>
The two treaties were signed by Cyprus Justice and Public
Order Minister Nicos Koshis and U.S. Ambassador to Cyprus Donald
Bandler, the Cyprus News Agency (CNA) reported.
</P>
<P>
For years, Cyprus and the U.S. have been applying a treaty of
extradition which was concluded in 1931 between the U.K. and the
U.S. and then extended to Cyprus, which was then under British
colonial rule, said the Cyprus minister.
</P>
<P>
The Republic of Cyprus and the U.S. enjoy a long history of
close cooperation in law enforcement, said Bandler.
</P>
<P>
"This cooperation embraces the area of mutual assistance in
areas such as money laundering and drug enforcement and extends
to daily interactions between local police and security personnel
in embassies," he said.
</P>
<P>
The two documents will provide a framework for further
"cooperation in law enforcement matters" between the two
countries, said the Ambassador. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
