<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UNHCR Urges Africa to Consolidate Fragile Peace </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, September 14 (Xinhua) -- Visiting officials of the
United Nations High Commissioner for Refugees (UNHCR) Tuesday
urged African leaders to make efforts to consolidate fragile peace
on the continent so as to pave the way for the solution of refugee
problems.
</P>
<P>
Addressing a press conference here, UNHCR assistant high
commissioner Soren Jessen-Petersen said that peace settlement in
regional conflicts in Africa is of great importance to solve
refugee problems.
</P>
<P>
On the Democratic Republic of Congo and Sierra Leone,
Jessen-Peterson said, "we believe the big challenge for the
international community is now to seize opportunity to let fragile
peace settlement linger on. "
</P>
<P>
"Without political solutions, without resources to support
these solutions, we'll be moving from one bad operation to
another," Jessen- Petersen said.
</P>
<P>
The UNHCR official said he held talks with officials of the
Addis Ababa- based UN Economic Commission for Africa and the
Organization of African Unity, with all sides agree that African
countries should make use of peace settlement of conflicts to
solve refugee problems.
</P>
<P>
Albert-Alain Peters, UNHCR director for Africa bureau, also
appealed to African countries to create appropriate living
conditions for the returnees.
</P>
<P>
He said refugees can be active members of society. "They
should be allowed to work."
</P>
<P>
"If they are not working... they will certainly turn to other
activities, probably military activities which are not going to do
any good to the countries concerned, Peters said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
