<DOCNO> XIE19990915.0014 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thailand Approves Measures to Help Laos Overcome Crisis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, September 14 (Xinhua) -- The Thai cabinet Tuesday
approved measures to help Laos alleviate the impact of the
economic crisis by promoting imports from that country and
increasing investment there.
</P>
<P>
A Government House press release said the Thai cabinet approved
a new trade policy toward its northern neighbor at its weekly
meeting.
</P>
<P>
Under the new policy, the Finance Ministry is urged to reduce
import duty on 23 agricultural goods from Laos.
</P>
<P>
Import duty on some 39 other items of agricultural products and
raw materials from Laos will also be reduced as part of the
efforts to increase Laos' exports to Thailand.
</P>
<P>
The cabinet also asked the Commerce Ministry to undertake the
Association of Southeast Asian Nations (ASEAN) trade and
investment project under the economic framework with Cambodia,
Vietnam, Myanmar and Laos.
</P>
<P>
A Thai delegation will travel to the four countries to study
trade and investment opportunities, and the result of the study
will be used by Thai and foreign private sectors for helping make
decisions on investment in these countries.
</P>
<P>
The Federation of Thai Industries and Thai Chamber of Commerce
were also requested to encourage their members to invest in Laos.
</P>
<P>
The Transport and Communications Ministry of Thailand was also
urged to enforce the agreement on Thai-Lao Road transportation.
</P>
<P>
Thai businessmen were even encouraged to trade in kip, the Lao
currency, especially in border trade.
</P>
<P>
Separated from Laos only by the Mekong river, Thailand is the
largest trading partner of the landlocked country, taking more
than 80 percent of the latter's total foreign trade volume.
</P>
<P>
Since Laos' trade was greatly dependent on Thailand, it was
seriously affected by the financial crisis, which hit Thailand in
mid-1997.
</P>
<P>
The kip has devalued by about 90 percent to about 240 kips to
the baht, or about 9,120 kips to the U.S. dollar. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
