<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. African President Rejects Parliament Move </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, September 14 (Xinhua) -- South African President
Thabo Mbeki Tuesday rejected speculation that a decision to base
his office in Pretoria during parliamentary sessions signaled a
move for parliament from Cape Town.
</P>
<P>
"It would be quite incorrect to link the manner in which the
president has to operate as an implication of any sort for the
site of parliament," South African Press Association (SAPA) quoted
him as telling reporters in Pretoria.
</P>
<P>
"The only point being made is that because the president is not
expected to be sitting in parliament, obviously we will spend the
bulk of our time here (in Pretoria)."
</P>
<P>
Mbeki said any decision to move parliament would be taken by
the legislature itself.
</P>
<P>
Plans were being made to put the matter on parliament's agenda.
Also up for discussion was how the president should be required to
interact with parliament.
</P>
<P>
Mbeki said the decision to spend most of his time in Pretoria
did not mean a down-scaling of his Cape Town office.
</P>
<P>
Mbeki will still have to fly to Cape Town regularly for cabinet
meetings when parliament is in session because all cabinet
ministers are members of parliament.
</P>
<P>
On the ongoing public service wage dispute, he said the
government was eager for the matter to be resolved, but stressed
that public finances were stretched.
</P>
<P>
"Discussions will continue, but there are constraints," Mbeki
said. "We are not going to print money to meet all the demands
being made.
</P>
<P>
"I don't think we should address any particular item of
expenditure as if it was the only item of expenditure."
</P>
<P>
Mbeki expressed satisfaction with the performance of his
government in the first 100 days since it came into power.
</P>
<P>
"I am very happy. I think everybody is responding with the
sense of urgency that is required."
</P>
<P>
Mbeki was speaking after bestowing the Order of Good Hope on
outgoing Egyptian ambassador Moushira Khattab for her contribution
to promoting bilateral relations between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
Khattab, who is to take up the post of deputy foreign minister
in her country, expressed Egypt's confidence that South Africa
would go from strength to strength under Mbeki's leadership.
</P>
<P>
Mbeki also received credentials from Canadian high commissioner
Lucy Edwards and ambassador Alladin Villacorte from the
Philippines. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
