<DOCNO> XIE19990915.0019 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ethiopian Involvement Intensifies Fighting in S. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
He said a breakaway faction from the SNF under the support of
Ethiopian troops invaded on Monday Garbaharrey town, the regional
capital of Gedo in southern Somalia.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman blasted the Ethiopians for massacring civilians
in the town during their invasion, adding the whole town has been
destroyed by the Ethiopian's heavy artillery bombs.
</P>
<P>
He also accused the Ethiopians for detaining five clan
chieftains including Nabaddon Hussein Dualeh and Nabaddon Abdi
Hersih.
</P>
<P>
The military movements by Ethiopia or its allied factions have
been increasing, especially in Southern Somalia since last year
when Hussein Aidid brought in hundreds of Oromo Ethnic Ethiopians
for training and launching attacks against the regime of Meles
Zenawi of Addis Ababa, he said.
</P>
<P>
Ethiopian troops have been controlling several towns and
villages in Gedo, Bay and Bakol regions since last year, he said.
</P>
<P>
Apart from Garbaharrey town, Ethiopian forces were also seen in
the town of Dinsor of Bay region which has been the only way now
linking Mogadishu to Baidoa following its fall into the hands of
the Ethiopian backed RRA militiamen in June this year, he added.
</P>
<P>
The SNF breakaway forces attacked Garbaharrey town and chased
away their rival side loyal to General Omar Hajji Massaleh allied
with Aidid, according to spokesman for the SNF breakaway faction
Abdi Dahir Hassan, who contacted the journalists on the VHF radio
in Garbaharrey town.
</P>
<P>
He said the forces loyal to Ahmed Sheikh Buraleh have taken
control of the town after a fierce fighting which lasted for three
hours, adding that the town is now calm under their control.
</P>
<P>
At least 11 people were killed and more than 16 others from
both sides were wounded including civilians and women, local media
reported, adding that the heavy shelling and the exchange of the
gunfire for control of the town could well be heard in a distance
of more than 10 Kilometers away. Hundreds of people have fled the
town towards Bardera and the surrounding villages.  
</P>
</TEXT>
