<HEADLINE> Athens Quake Death Toll Climbs to 127 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, September 14 (Xinhua) -- The death toll from last
Tuesday's earthquake in northwestern Athens rose to 127 Tuesday,
with the Ricomex factory in Menidi being the only site at which
rescue work is still under way.
</P>
<P>
The earthquake registering 5.9 on the Richter scale occurred
last Tuesday afternoon in the Mount Parnitha region, some 20
kilometers northwest of Athens.
</P>
<P>
So far, more than 2,000 people have been injured and some
60,000 others left homeless in the earthquake, which is estimated
to cost Greece more than 200 billion drachams (about 666 million
U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
The Greek government has expressed its satisfaction with the
relief efforts and a total of 20,000 tents with a capacity of
120,000 people have been set up.
</P>
<P>
The tremor's aftereffects would have no impact on Greece's
course towards the European economic and monetary union (EMU), and
the European Union (EU) support would be significant and help
handle the problem, Greek government spokesman Dimitris Reppas
said Tuesday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
