<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Italy Suspends Aid Program to Zimbabwe </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, September 14 (Xinhua) - Italy suspended the 22 million
U.S. dollar commodity aid to Zimbabwe on Tuesday citing lack of
transparency in the awarding of tenders for projects under the
bilateral program.
</P>
<P>
The Italian embassy to Zimbabwe said in a statement "following
a legal action started in Italy, a careful review of all the
procedures followed for awarding the tender for the projects was
undertaken and brought to light several serious mistakes with
regard to guarantees and transparency."
</P>
<P>
The implementation of the agreement, which was signed in 1996,
had already started in the public sector investment projects and
was mainly funding the electrification of 250 rural schools and
250 rural clinics using solar power. Some of the money was used
to develop the private sector.
</P>
<P>
The embassy said efforts had been made since April to rescue
the projects by mending the legal mistakes but this did not
succeed.
</P>
<P>
"Unfortunately, every suggestion and warning has been ignored
and, therefore, in observance of its political and legal
responsibilities concerning the possible waste of public funds,
the government of Italy has been forced to suspend the aid," the
statement said.
</P>
<P>
This is the same aid under which the Tokwe Murkosi dam, the
largest inland water body for Zimbabwe, was being built. The
project has now been halted due to financial shortages caused by
the legal action in Italy. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990915.0022 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Special Rapporteur on Use of Mercenaries Visiting Cuba </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, September 14 (Xinhua) -- The U.N. special
rapporteur on the question of the use of mercenaries, Enrique
Bernales Ballkesteros, is visiting Cuba this week, U.N. spokesman
Fred Eckhard said here Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Eckhard said the visit was made at an invitation from the
government of that country.
</P>
<P>
During the mission, set to last from 12 to 18 September 1999,
the special rapporteur intends to collect first-hand information
to evaluate allegations of mercenaries' activities against Cuba.
</P>
<P>
In previous reports to the U.N. General Assembly and the
Commission on Human Rights, the special rapporteur drew attention
and reproduced communications received from the government of Cuba
in which reference was made to mercenary attacks on that country
"from the earliest days following the victory of the revolution.
</P>
<P>
During the visit, the special rapporteur intends to explore
more deeply the causes and effects of the existence of mercenary
practices and their increasing linkage with acts of terrorism.
</P>
<P>
The United Nations Commission on Human Rights created the post
of special rapporteur on the question of the use of mercenaries in
1987. Bernales Ballkesteros, a political scientist, a lawyer and
former Peruvian senator, has served as special rapporteur since
his appointment then. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
