<DOCNO> XIE19990915.0024 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. Africa to Seek Better Deal at IMF: Finance </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, September 14 (Xinhua) -- South Africa would
attend next week's annual meeting of the International Monetary
Fund (IMF) and the World Bank in Washington to try and secure a
better deal for small developing countries, Finance Minister
Trevor Manuel said on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Issues would include how to enhance the HIPC (highly indebted
poor countries) debt relief initiative, and gold sales, he told a
media briefing in Cape Town, according to South African Press
Association.
</P>
<P>
The annual meeting is scheduled for September 25 to 30.
</P>
<P>
Manuel said the gold issue was "somewhat more calm", as the IMF
sought to find an alternative to selling gold on the open market.
</P>
<P>
Of the 41 mostly African countries designated as HIPCs, 30
produce gold.
</P>
<P>
Gold has come under pressure from speculators ever since the
IMF announced it was planning to sell about 10 million ounces to
help relieve debt owed by the world's poorest countries.
</P>
<P>
An IMF document mistakenly made public last week said the
fund's governing committee would discuss a proposal to revalue 10
million ounces of its gold reserves to the metal's market price,
from its current book value of about 47 U.S. dollars an ounce.
</P>
<P>
This would allow the IMF to release about 1.1 billion U.S.
dollars to fund debt relief for poor countries.
</P>
<P>
Manuel said South Africa would want to see some sort of
commitment from the G7 group of industrialised nations.
</P>
<P>
"We need to develop a mechanism that takes account of the needs
of all countries, particularly gold producing, and a mechanism
that will be focused on financial support."
</P>
<P>
The IMF efforts to find an alternative had to be encouraged, he
stressed
</P>
<P>
On HIPC, Manuel said: "We must continue to bat for a
consciousness about the needs of small, poor countries."
</P>
<P>
A significant improvement in the HIPC initiative was necessary,
he said, adding that "if we can get a few more African countries
on to the list of beneficiaries now, then we'll be doing well."
</P>
<P>
Manuel said the countries that had to benefit were Zambia,
Tanzania and, hopefully, even Malawi.
</P>
<P>
"The G7 countries who committed themselves in Cologne, in
faith, to put money in the HIPC is all very good, but I don't
think we need faith alone.
</P>
<P>
"We need a few dollars in that HIPC fund and I think there
needs to be some pressure," Manuel said.
</P>
<P>
In the IMF's 1998/99 annual report, it again pleaded for the G7
 countries to find funds to support the HIPC debt relief
initiative. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990915.0025 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> France to Provide Mozambique Offshore Fishery </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MAPUTO, September 14 (Xinhua) -- French fleet will provide
offshore fishery information to Mozambican authorities from now
on, French Naval Commander of the Indian Ocean Patrice du Puy-
Montbrun said here Monday.
</P>
<P>
Following an etiquette visit of three French warships to Maputo
from September 10-13, Patrice said French warships will help
supervise the merchant ships travelling on Mozambique Ridge as a
response to the formal request of the Mozambican government for
strengthening military cooperation between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
The Noticias newspaper reported Tuesday that so far the naval
cooperation between Mozambique and France has been restricted to
exchange of experience and information, the French officer said,
while adding that " we will leave the door open for greater
cooperation".
</P>
<P>
A Mozambican officer speaking on condition of anonymity said
that although the Mozambican authorities has expressed that it
wishes to secure an agreement on military cooperation with France,
so far no agreements have been signed between the two sides in
this field.  
</P>
</TEXT>
