<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-14 18:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Barak Opposes Return of Palestinian Refugees </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, September 14 (Xinhua) -- As the Israeli-Palestinian
final status talks are underway, Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak
Tuesday reiterated that Israel would never allow the return of
Palestinian refugees.
</P>
<P>
Barak made the remarks in a cabinet meeting one day after
Israeli Foreign Minister David Levy and Abu Mazen, deputy to
Palestinian National Authority Chairman Yasser Arafat, formally
launched talks for a final peace settlement between the two sides.
</P>
<P>
The issue of Palestinian refugees, together with others lying
in the heart of the Israeli-Palestinian conflict such as the
Palestinian statehood and the status of Jerusalem, is to be
tackled in the talks.
</P>
<P>
Hundreds of thousands of Palestinians were forced to flee
their homes when the Jewish state was proclaimed in 1948.
</P>
<P>
Nowadays, more than 3 million refugees and their descendants
are scattered in the West Bank and the Gaza Strip as well as
neighboring Arab countries.
</P>
<P>
Israel opposes the return of the refugees for fear that it will
cause a major impact on the character of the Jewish state, which
has a population of 6 million.
</P>
<P>
Arafat said as recent as Sunday, however, that the Palestinian
refugees have the right to return to the West Bank and Gaza.
</P>
<P>
"Let me tell you honestly that there is no home for the
Palestinians except Palestine...The right of refugees to return
to their homeland is our conviction and one which we will never
compromise," he told an Arab League meeting in Cairo.
</P>
<P>
Despite the tremendous difficulty surrounding all the issues
in the final status talks, Israel and the Palestinians have set an
ambitious goal to reach a framework on the talks by February next
year and achieve a permanent peace treaty by September, one year
after the start of the talks.
</P>
<P>
But it seems that Barak is also unsure whether the two sides
can resolve all their disputes rooted in decades of conflict
within a year. In the cabinet meeting, he described three
scenarios for the result of the talks: a comprehensive peace, a
long-term interim agreement, or a total collapse.
</P>
<P>
There have been reports that Barak is seeking to postpone the
two thorniest issues - Jerusalem and refugees - till after the
one-year deadline for long-term discussion.
</P>
<P>
Cabinet Minister Haim Ramon told the Foreign Press Association
recently that these two issues could not be resolved in less than
five or ten years.
</P>
<P>
If the reported idea of Barak turned to a reality, then the
targeted peace accord next September would be an incomplete
permanent agreement. It would still have the nature of an interim
agreement.
</P>
<P>
Barak said in a radio interview earlier this week that if the
two sides did not agree on an outline by February, they might have
to forgo a final peace accord and instead - by mutual consent -
negotiate long-term interim agreements on most issues.
</P>
<P>
Palestinian officials have balked at Barak's suggestion, urging
him to seize the opportunity in order to reach a permanent peace
within a year.
</P>
<P>
In the cabinet meeting, Levy said Abu Mazen is positive on the
prospect of the peace talks and has showed a desire for a
permanent peace, Israel Radio reported. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990915.0029 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> News Analysis: World Peace Top on U.N. Agenda </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, September 14 (Xinhua) -- U.N. Secretary-General
Tuesday rang the Peace Bell at the New York-based United Nations
headquarters, marking the beginning of the International Year for
the Culture of Peace.
</P>
<P>
"Today, the ringing of the Peace Bell coincides with the
launch, by UNESCO (the United Nations Educational, Scientific and
Cultural Organization), of the International Year for Peace,"
Annan said at a brief ceremony to ring the Peace Bell at the U.N.
complex here.
</P>
<P>
"Why a Culture of Peace?" he said. "Because war, violence,
poverty and prejudice are the daily experience of millions upon
millions of people throughout our world."
</P>
<P>
The president of the Security Council, Arnold Peter van Walsum
of the Netherlands, told an audience representing various
countries at the ceremony, "In a large number of countries, for a
large number of people, peace is not the norm. War and destruction
are all these people have ever known."
</P>
<P>
"Peace for them is only a word," he said. "Their reality is
violence, injustice, violations of human rights. They have no idea
what peace feels, looks and sounds like."
</P>
<P>
For this year, peace has become even more precious after the
U.S.-led NATO sidelined the Security Council by waging 78-day air
strikes on Yugoslavia, a sovereign member of the U.N. family.
</P>
<P>
On November 20, 1997, the General Assembly adopted a
resolution, proclaiming the year 2000 as the International Year
for the Culture of Peace. The U.N. system as a whole has since
been preparing for its celebration, led by UNESCO.
</P>
<P>
The year 2000 has become an essential and necessary landmark
for all humanity, ushering in not only a new century, but also a
new millennium. Therefore, the international community, taking
stock of the achievements and failures of the past, must seize the
unique opportunity offered by the year 2000 to the work of
building the future for the whole mankind.
</P>
<P>
However, if the world, with the support from the United Nations
which has the primary responsibility for maintenance of the global
peace, wishes to build the future, the international community
must take immediate and concreted action, making peace and
non-violence part of daily life for all human beings.
</P>
<P>
UNESCO's constitution says, "Since wars begin in the minds of
men, it is in the minds of men that the defenses of peace must be
constructed."
</P>
<P>
UNESCO's Culture of Peace project aims to promote values,
attitudes and behaviors in people so that they will seek peaceful
solution to problems.
</P>
<P>
In fact, a culture of peace is a set of values, attitudes,
traditional and models of behavior and ways of life, based on such
policies as the action under the U.N. Charter, the full respect
for the principles of sovereignty, territorial integrity and
political independence of States and non-intervention in matters
which are essentially within the domestic jurisdiction of any
State, efforts to meet the developmental and environmental needs
of present and future generations.
</P>
<P>
Progress in the fuller development of a culture of peace comes
about through values, attitudes, modes of behavior and ways of
life conducive to the promotion of peace among individuals, groups
and nations.
</P>
<P>
To achieve the goal, it is very important to promote peaceful
settlement of conflicts, mutual respect and understanding and
international cooperation, and it is very important to comply with
international obligations under the U.N. Charter and international
law, and to enable people at all levels to develop skills of
dialogue, negotiation, consensus-building and peaceful resolution
of differences.
</P>
<P>
The Culture of Peace involves individuals, community leaders,
media, governments, and non-governmental organizations. In short,
people from different walks of life and people from different
countries can contribute to the promotion of peace and security in
the world as a whole.
</P>
<P>
Peace and development are the main theme of the current era, as
the two are the shared hopes and aspirations of mankind. In
reality, people may speak different languages for peace, but the
world must bear one thing in mind: the function of the United
Nations is irreplaceable, and the purpose of the United Nations
and the principles of international law are still the guidelines
for any action in the world to seek peace. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
