<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Rebel Tries to Press Talks Upon Angolan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUANDA, September 14 (Xinhua) -- Angolan rebel leader Jonas
Savimbi is trying to force the government to accept his political
exigences for negotiation through a series of terrorist activities
around the war-torn country.
</P>
<P>
The "banditry and extremist actions" conducted by the rebels
are aimed at pressing talks upon the government, said National
Assembly of Angola (ANA) Tuesday in a document.
</P>
<P>
Savimbi has threatened to create "spectacular" events in
Luanda, with the principal transport network, power and water
systems as their main targets, if the government refuses to
restart negotiation with him, according to the latest weekly
newspaper Angolense.
</P>
<P>
Rebels led by Savimbi have been put in a passive position in
recent months because the government has improved its capacity of
defense and began withdrawing some of the Angolan troops from the
Democratic Republic of the Congo (DRC), local analysts observed.
</P>
<P>
Due to the difficult situation, the rebel leader recently made
four interviews in less than three weeks with the British
Broadcasting Company (BBC), suggesting a restart of negotiation
with the government, the report said.
</P>
<P>
But Angolan government, which has lost faith in words of
Savimbi, refused to re-open negotiation with him. Angolan
President Jose Eduardo dos Santos has obtained in mid-August
support from the member countries of the Southern African
Development Community (SADC) for depriving Savimbi of the status
as a negotiator.
</P>
<P>
Secretary-General of the ruling People's Liberation Movement of
Angola Joao Lourenco said last week that Savimbi had fallen into
"affliction" and had to beg pardon, but he promised that the
government would not listen to his "supplications".
</P>
<P>
Early this month, the government troops recovered an important
fortress, Cuvango, in the south-central Huila Province; meanwhile,
assaults by the National Union for the Total Independence of
Angola (UNITA) on villages in the Bengo Province, neighboring the
capital city of Luanda, were frustrated.
</P>
<P>
The document said that the Angolan government has made great
efforts to end the conflict through pacific and democratic way,
citing the example of the elections in 1992, which showed the
government's "good faith" to seek a just and equilibrated
solution.
</P>
<P>
UNITA lost the 1992 elections to the incumbent Angolan
government, but Savimbi refused to accept the results of the
elections.
</P>
<P>
"Notwithstanding the arduous and unquestionable efforts made by
the Angolan government, the incessant diplomatic efforts and
mediations by the international community, Savimbi continues to
resort to armed forces through subversive actions," said the
parliament in the document.
</P>
<P>
In recent months, UNITA rebels scattered into small groups and
hid in rural areas. They have been trying to avoid face-to-face
confrontation with the government troops, which has been
reinforced by the return of the troops from DRC and the civilian
defence organized by regional governments.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, rebels launched a series of warlike actions against
civilians, including ambushments on civil vehicles on highways,
mining the principal roads with access to fields and assaulting
villages and small towns all around the country.
</P>
<P>
It is also reported that the ambushments on vehicles in the
province of Malanje has killed more than 30 and injured over 100
in the recent two months.
</P>
<P>
Although the Angolan President refused to negotiate with
Savimbi, he told the Angolan people that he will seek a solution
"as soon as possible" for ending the suffering of the people.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
