<HEADLINE> Bank of Cyprus Gains Good Profits </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, September 14 (Xinhua) -- The Bank of Cyprus (BoC)
Group Tuesday announced it gained after-tax profits of 22.5
million Cyprus pounds (45 million U.S. dollars) for the first half
of 1999, up by 50.3 percent compared to the same period last year.
</P>
<P>
Group Chairman Solon Triantafyllides told a press conference
that the Board of the Group, which is the island's largest
financial institution, has approved an interim dividend of 8.0
percent.
</P>
<P>
Triantafyllides attributed the increase to BoC's "very good
performance" in Cyprus and the good results of the Group's
associated companies operating in insurance and investment
sectors.
</P>
<P>
He said the Group has been working for BoC's listing on the
Athens Stock Exchange early next year.
</P>
<P>
He said the Group and the Greek authorities have reached an
agreement on the percentage of capital that has to be issued in
Greece prior to the BoC share trading on the Athens Stock Exchange.
</P>
<P>
The deal will be presented to the Extraordinary General Meeting
of the Group for approval on October 13, he noted.
</P>
<P>
With 16 branches in operation in Greece, BoC will open a
"substantial number of branches" in Greece in the next two to
three years. 
</P>
