<HEADLINE> Nigeria Reluctant to Shoulder Bulk of ECOMOG Troops </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, September 14 (Xinhua) -- Nigerian Minister of State for
Defense Dupe Adelaja expressed her country's reluctance to
shoulder the bulk of the West African peace-keeping force (ECOMOG)
and said pacts will be signed on quota for each members'
contributions.
</P>
<P>
Adelaja made these remarks in capital Abuja on Monday in
meeting with Togolese Defense Minister Tijani Assani, the local
newspaper Vanguard reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
She said that Nigeria and Togo would soon sign a defense pact
and an arrangement was being worked out to ensure that not only
Nigeria would continue to shoulder the responsibility of ECOMOG.
</P>
<P>
Nigeria is contributing 80 percent of the ECOMOG forces.
</P>
<P>
Adelaja explained that the pacts to be signed with Togo and
other West African countries were designed to ensure that "one
person's problem is the problem of the others and you cannot do
that except there is an agreement."
</P>
<P>
The Nigerian official noted that the pacts being proposed with
other countries in the sub-region would bring about a quota system
on the number of ECOMOG troops.
</P>
<P>
"If it is eventually signed, we can rely on one another if
there is crisis within the sub-region," she said.
</P>
<P>
At the moment, she added, there are ECOMOG troops, but it seems
as if Nigeria is the only one in charge.
</P>
<P>
Adelaja noted that "when we have this type of agreement, then
you can have proper contribution from other countries." 
</P>
