<HEADLINE> EU Offers Aid For Turkish Education Reform </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, September 14 (Xinhua) -- The European Commission said
Tuesday that it is allocating 100 million euros (105 million U.S.
dollars) for a project to assist Turkey under a European Union
(EU) program.
</P>
<P>
This is the biggest contribution by the European bloc so far in
its financial cooperation with Turkey, the EU's executive branch
said. The aim is to facilitate the extension of primary education
from five to eight years by means of sectoral aid to be provided
over a six-year period, it added.
</P>
<P>
The project will assist the Turkish Ministry of National
Education in the qualitative reform of initial and vocational
training, "ensuring a positive spin-off for the country as a
whole," the commission said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
"The reform is to be implemented in 12 of the most
disadvantaged provinces to achieve a quantitative and qualitative
improvement in education for girls and women in particular," it
said.
</P>
<P>
"Local multidisciplinary education centers will be opened for
sections of the population excluded from basic education --
children, young people and adults -- in cities with a high level
of immigration, mainly Istanbul," the European Commission said.
</P>
<P>
The EU's 15 foreign ministers met their Turkish counterpart,
Ismail Cem, Monday in Brussels to talk about comprehensive aid for
Turkey's economic reform and reconstruction after the earthquake
disaster, as well as prospects for Turkey's EU membership in the
future, warming up the tepid EU-Turkish ties to a high point
following an earthquake prompted thaw of the relations between
Turkey and Greece. 
</P>
</TEXT>
