<HEADLINE> Indonesia to Play Part in East Timor Peacekeeping: Alatas </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, September 14 (Xinhua) -- The U.N.-sanctioned
multinational force will cooperate with Indonesia in keeping peace
in East Timor, Foreign Minister Ali Alatas Tuesday said, ruling
out the imminent withdrawal of the Indonesian army.
</P>
<P>
The Indonesian troops "are not withdrawing yet, but there will
be cooperation between the multinational and the Indonesian
forces," the minister said, emerging from his talks with U.N.
Secretary-General Kofi Annan and Australian Foreign Minister
Alexander Downer Tuesday morning.
</P>
<P>
Australia is the most prepared contributor of troops to
restoring peace and security in East Timor. Alatas said he and
Downer talked about when their troops would go to East Timor, what
other countries would be among the first batch of the force and
the implications between a multinational force and a U.N.
peace-keeping one in terms of funding.
</P>
<P>
"But of course the command and the leadership on the ground
will be with the multinational force, with the Indonesian forces
probably playing an advisory or liaison role," he said.
</P>
<P>
"There is a timetable and we are going to withdraw in a matter
of weeks, let us keep the timetable, let us honor the
international agreement," he said, referring to the May 5
agreement between Indonesia, Portugal and the United Nations.
</P>
<P>
The pact provides for Indonesia to be responsible for law and
order in East Timor during the ballot on its future and its
transition to independence.
</P>
<P>
The August 30 referendum did see the majority of voters showing
preference to independence. In this case the U.N. peace-keeping
mission is mandated to enter into the territory only after the
transition period ends.
</P>
<P>
"We are facing a situation which was not of our making, which
was a very difficult and complicated one and we are trying to
overcome with the help of the United Nations... you can continue
to accuse us of many things, but if you don't accept the
situation, you cann't find the answer to the situation," Alatas
said.
</P>
<P>
He said Indonesia would like to see the international troops to
land on East Timor as soon as possible, but how soon would depend
on contributing countries and U.N. regulations.
</P>
<P>
The Security Council was working on a draft resolution forming
the basis for the multinational action.
</P>
<P>
Violence has taken place since the result of the U.N. brokered
ballot was announced on September 4, which ended Indonesia's rule
since 1976 after the withdrawal of former colonial ruler Portugal.
</P>
</TEXT>
