<HEADLINE> More People in Tanzania Facing Starvation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, September 14 (Xinhua)-- Over 20,000 residents in
 Tanzania's northwestern Kagera Region are facing acute food
shortage following a prolonged drought that lasted for four years
in a row.
</P>
<P>
Anatoli Amani, Chairman of the ruling Revolutionary Party of
Tanzania (CCM) branch in the region, told journalists in the
regional capital Tuesday that the situation is very pathetic as
some of the residents survive on a single meal per day.
</P>
<P>
Amani said he paid an eight-day visit to some parts of the
region recently, finding a large tract of banana plantation had
dried up.
</P>
<P>
The drought has also badly affected coffee farms, he added.
</P>
<P>
Karagwe district is one of the big producers of grain and
coffee in Tanzania but the drought has forced people to suffer
from hunger, he said.
</P>
<P>
The regional party leader appealed to individuals, parastatal
organizations and private companies to urgently transport food to
aid the drought affected areas.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, more than 600,000 people in north Tanzania's
Shinyanga Region are reportedly facing an acute food shortage
caused by a prolonged drought.
</P>
<P>
The Shinyanga Regional Commissioner, Tumainiel Kiwelu, said
that 2.53 million inhabitants there require 553,000 tons of grain
to live comfortably for one year. However, the available food
only amounts to 395,000 tons at present.
</P>
