<HEADLINE> Argentine Official Criticizes IMF Forecast </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUENAS AIRES, September 14 (Xinhua) -- Argentina's vice
secretary of finance, Miguel Kiguel, considered as "pessimistic"
the forecast by the International Monetary Fund (IMF) of an
economic growth of 1 percent for the country in the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
For some reason, the forecast by the IMF was discordant with
the favorable objective factors, such as a more favorable
international climate, said Kiguel in an interview published
Tuesday by the newspaper "El Cronista."
</P>
<P>
"The IMF is taking a very conservative stance" and "has little
respect" for the capacity of the gross domestic product (GDP) of
Argentina, said the official.
</P>
<P>
The GDP of the country would grow by 3.5 percent over the next
year, due to the provision of a higher dynamism in Brazil,
Paraguay and Uruguay, Argentina's partners in the Mercosur, he
said.
</P>
<P>
Kiguel also denied that the elections on October 24, in which
Carlos Menem will be replaced as president, would have adverse
repercussions on the economy.
</P>
<P>
The GDP of Argentina contracted by 4.9 percent in the second
quarter of this year, compared with the same period in 1998, due
to the recession which was worsened by the contraction of the
Brazilian economy, confirmed Kiguel.
</P>
<P>
On Monday, the Argentine government said it estimated its
budget deficit next year at 4.5 billion U.S. dollars, a target
below this year's likely shortfall. 
