<DOCNO> XIE19990915.0045 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-14 19:44 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Turco-Greek Rapprochement Out of Control: Turkish </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, September 14 (Xinhua) -- Turkish Foreign Minister
Ismail Cem said here on Tuesday that the rapprochement process
between Turkey and Greece following the quakes in the two Aegean
countries has gone out of his control.
</P>
<P>
Cem made the remarks at a press conference after returning from
a meeting of the European Union (EU) foreign ministers in
Brussels, Belgium.
</P>
<P>
"I did not want the rapprochement to proceed in front of
political clients. I wanted it to be silent and calm." Cem said.
</P>
<P>
He expressed concern that any adverse development in bilateral
relations could now lead to serious disappointment in relations
between the two states.
</P>
<P>
Cem said he and his Greek counterpart Yorgo Papandreou agreed
in June to mend fences and start low-level dialog on cooperation
in six years.
</P>
<P>
Turkey and Greece have immediately improved bilateral ties
after the two neighboring countries were hit by strong quakes
separately.
</P>
<P>
After a 7.4-magnitude earthquake hit western Turkey on August
17, Greece sent a strong rescue team to help Turkey extricate
survivors trapped in the ruins of collapsed buildings in western
Turkey.
</P>
<P>
Later, Turkey was the first country to send its 20-member
rescue team to help Greece rescue the Greeks trapped in the debris
after a 5.9-magnitude quake hit Athens on September 8.
</P>
<P>
"Now (following the earthquakes) mayors, football teams are
exchanging visits, newspapers in the two countries are running
headlines in Turkish and Greek...I lost ability to control it,"
said the minister.
</P>
<P>
"Of course this spirit of solidarity is positive. There is an
outbreak of friendship and expectations. I hope it will continue
in the same way. Otherwise it can become very unfortunate."
</P>
<P>
Turkey and Greece, both members of the North Atlantic Treaty
Organization (NATO), have long been at odds over the limits of
air space, sovereignty over some Aegean islands and the Cyprus
issue. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
