<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-14 19:50 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Present Climate for Turkey's Candidacy for EU </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, September 14 (Xinhua) -- Turkish Foreign Minister
Ismail Cem said here Tuesday that the present climate for
Turkey's candidacy for the European Union (EU) membership is
"very positive."
</P>
<P>
Cem made the remarks at a press conference after his return
from a meeting of EU foreign ministers in Brussels on Monday.
</P>
<P>
"A positive development is possible. but I do not want to talk
about big outcomes," Cem said in an apparent reference to the
widely-expected declaration of Turkey's candidacy at the EU summit
scheduled to be held in December in Helsinki, Finland.
</P>
<P>
He said "there is a better climate of understanding" in the
Brussels meeting, during which he was invited to make a speech on
Turkey's eagerness to join the European club.
</P>
<P>
On the reported opposition of Sweden and Denmark to Turkey's
candidacy, Cem said the two countries had not conveyed any such
position officially to Ankara, adding that he would visit Sweden
and Denmark in late November.
</P>
<P>
It is reported that Sweden opposes the Turkish candidacy,
citing its human rights record.
</P>
<P>
However, the Turkish foreign minister said "what we will
definitely oppose is any condition for our candidacy."
</P>
<P>
During the summit in Luxembourg in December 1997, the EU
decided to invite Poland, Hungary, the Czech Republic, Estonia,
Slovenia and Cyprus to start accession talks in early 1998.
</P>
<P>
Five other nations -- Bulgaria, Latvia, Lithuania, Romania and
Slovakia -- were put on a slower negotiating track by the
15-nation union. And Turkey, a 34-year applicant, was left
completely in the cold.
</P>
<P>
The result of the summit was disappointing for Turkey, but "it
was not an obsession for Turkey and we will not treat it as an
event that will have an impact on the course of Turkey," said Cem
at that time. 
</P>
</TEXT>
