<HEADLINE> Xinhua Mideast News Summary at 2000GMT, Tuesday </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY -- Saudi Prince Waleed Ibn Talal said on Tuesday he
was assured by Chairman of Walt Disney Co. Michael Eisner that the
entertainment giant will not hold an exhibition under the title of
"Jerusalem, Israel' Capital."
</P>
<P>
Prince Talal, one of the major investors in Disney Land
Company in France, said he had contacted Eisner and briefed him
with the Arab stand, the Kuwait News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Prince Talal said Eisner promised not to interfere in the
Jerusalem issue before the final status talks ended.
(BC-Saudi-Disney-Jerusalem)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- Israeli-Palestinan Joint Committee on Safe
Passage on Tuesday committed to strike a deal on the opening of
the "safe passage" linking the Gaza Strip and West Bank by the end
of this month.
</P>
<P>
In a meeting held in Tel Aviv Tuesday afternoon, the committee
discussed in detail about the opening of the safe passage linking
Gaza and Hebron, but members from the two sides are still at odds
over some relevant issues such as car registrations, Israel's
stoppage of suspects and security inspection by the Israeli
security forces, Israel Radio said. (BC-Israel-Safe Passage)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- As the Israeli-Palestinian final status talks are
underway, Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak Tuesday reiterated
that Israel would never allow the return of Palestinian refugees.
</P>
<P>
Barak made the remarks in a cabinet meeting one day after
Israeli Foreign Minister David Levy and Abu Mazen, deputy to
Palestinian National Authority Chairman Yasser Arafat, formally
launched talks for a final peace settlement between the two sides.
</P>
<P>
The issue of Palestinian refugees, together with others lying
in the heart of the Israeli-Palestinian conflict such as the
Palestinian statehood and the status of Jerusalem, is to be
tackled in the talks. (BC-Israel-Palestinians)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
BAGHDAD -- Iraqi Foreign Undersecretary Nazar Hamdoun on
Tuesday refuted a U.S. official's remarks that Iraq poses a threat
to its neighboring countries and Iraqi government should be
responsible for the sufferings of its people.
</P>
<P>
