<HEADLINE> Colombian Government Refuses Exchange of Prisoners </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SANTAFE DE BOGOTA, September 14 (Xinhua) -- Colombian Interior
Minister Nestor Martinez on Tuesday said the proposal of the
Revolutionary Armed Forces of Colombia (FARC) was not viable for
the exchange of the prisoners.
</P>
<P>
The FARC, the largest guerrilla group in Colombia, are
demanding that their proposal is subjected to a referendum, so as
to receive constitutional recognition.
</P>
<P>
Martinez told the press that the proposal for the exchange of
prisoners is unconstitutional.
</P>
<P>
the FARC are offering to release around 450 soldiers and
police, in exchange for 480 imprisoned guerrillas.
</P>
<P>
Colombian Attorney General Jaime Bernal wants the FARC to make
the proposal for the exchange of prisoners through dialogue with
the government.
</P>
<P>
The government and the FARC began peace talks on January 7, but
they have been suspended since mid-July, due to the refusal of the
FARC to accept an international commission of verification for the
distention zone. 
