<DOCNO> XIE19990915.0051 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> IFC Increases Investments in Emerging Markets in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 14 (Xinhua) -- The International Finance
Corporation (IFC) increased commitment of its own resources for
lending and investing in emerging markets to 2.8 billion U.S.
dollars in the 1999 fiscal year ending June 30 from the 2.7
billion dollars a year earlier, the IFC announced Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
In its 1999 annual report released Tuesday, the IFC said that
disbursements in FY99 were 2.1 billion dollars, similar to the
FY98 level.
</P>
<P>
The IFC said that it also mobilized 800 million dollars in
syndicated loans to projects in developing countries in FY99,
lower than the 2.4 billion dollars in FY98. IFC also disbursed 1.2
billion dollars on behalf of financial institutions participating
in its syndicated loans.
</P>
<P>
"The year-over-year decline in syndicated loans reflects the
difficult world financing environment which led many commercial
banks to cut back their exposure to developing countries," said
the IFC, part of the World Bank Group.
</P>
<P>
"IFC plays a key countercyclical role in times of uncertainty"
in emerging markets, said Peter Woicke, IFC Executive Vice
President and a managing director of the World Bank.
</P>
<P>
"In FY99, IFC's Asian strategy was directed at rehabilitating
and consolidating the financial and corporate sectors of those
economies hardest hit by the East Asian financial crisis," the
annual report said.
</P>
<P>
While aiding the crisis economies was a priority, IFC continued
to assist the transition economies, particularly China and
Vietnam, in developing their market systems, said IFC.
</P>
<P>
IFC earned 249 million dollars in fiscal year 1999, above the
246 million dollars earned in fiscal year 1998 but below the
record net income of 432 million dollars achieved in FY97. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990915.0052 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nigeria Reluctant to Shoulder Bulk of ECOMOG Troops </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, September 14 (Xinhua) -- Nigerian Minister of State for
Defense Dupe Adelaja expressed her country's reluctance to
shoulder the bulk of the West African peace-keeping force (ECOMOG)
and said pacts will be signed on quota for each members'
contributions.
</P>
<P>
Adelaja made these remarks in capital Abuja on Monday in
meeting with Togolese Defense Minister Tijani Assani, the local
newspaper Vanguard reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
She said that Nigeria and Togo would soon sign a defense pact
and an arrangement was being worked out to ensure that not only
Nigeria would continue to shoulder the responsibility of ECOMOG.
</P>
<P>
Nigeria is contributing 80 percent of the ECOMOG forces.
</P>
<P>
Adelaja explained that the pacts to be signed with Togo and
other West African countries were designed to ensure that "one
person's problem is the problem of the others and you cannot do
that except there is an agreement."
</P>
<P>
The Nigerian official noted that the pacts being proposed with
other countries in the sub-region would bring about a quota system
on the number of ECOMOG troops.
</P>
<P>
"If it is eventually signed, we can rely on one another if
there is crisis within the sub-region," she said.
</P>
<P>
At the moment, she added, there are ECOMOG troops, but it seems
as if Nigeria is the only one in charge.
</P>
<P>
Adelaja noted that "when we have this type of agreement, then
you can have proper contribution from other countries." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
