<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Putin Against State of Emergency in Russia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, September 14 (Xinhua) -- Prime Minister Vladimir Putin
said Tuesday that "no emergency situation should be invoked" in
Russia despite the recent spate of terrorist bombings and the war
in Daghestan.
</P>
<P>
"I believe that the current instrument of law is adequate, but
it should be properly used," Putin told journalists at the end of
a session of the State Duma, or lower house of parliament.
</P>
<P>
Top on the agenda in the session of the Duma was the recent
blasts that hit Moscow, the latest of which occurred Monday
morning, killing 118 residents in an eight-story apartment
building. Thirteen of the victims were children and 13 fragments
of human are yet to be identified.
</P>
<P>
"A struggle for the integrity of the Russian state is under
way," Putin said, adding that in such a struggle Russia has
"little choice, but need a positive result," the Interfax news
agency reported.
</P>
<P>
The blast Monday was the third to hit the capital since August
31, when a bomb went off in an underground shopping mall near the
Kremlin, killing one person and wounding dozens of others.
</P>
<P>
The second explosion happened just seconds to midnight
Wednesday, ripping apart a nine-story apartment building.
Ninety-four people were killed in that blast.
</P>
<P>
In Daghestan, a car bomb exploded in front of a five-story
military housing complex on September 4, killing 64 people.
</P>
<P>
Although authorities have not established the final causes of
the blasts, many believe they were staged by those with ties with
Islamic militants fighting federal troops in Daghestan, a southern
republic bordering the breakaway Chechnya.
</P>
<P>
Putin said the terrorist acts in Moscow and Daghestan "a
reaction of impotence and malice by the forces that received a
real befitting, adequate answer."
</P>
<P>
"It's time to stop talking about a state of emergency and
return the past positive practice of house committees," Putin
said.
</P>
<P>
He was apparently reacting to mounting rumors that the Kremlin
is contemplating emergency rule in the country so as to cancel the
upcoming parliamentary and presidential elections.
</P>
<P>
Almost all those likely to win those elections, including
powerful Moscow Mayor Yuri Luzhkov and former Prime Minister
Yevgeny Primakov, are considered not friendly with the Kremlin.
</P>
<P>
Security has been beefed up in the wake of the deadly blasts
and a large-scale anti-terrorist campaign involving interior
units will start in the country on Wednesday, Deputy Interior
Minister Igor Zubov said Tuesday in an interview on the ORT
television channel.
</P>
<P>
Total check of basements, attics and other premises in Moscow
houses and reinforced patrolling of the city streets will
continue, he said.
</P>
<P>
He said the recent terrorist attacks were masterminded in
Chechnya. The leadership in Chechnya has denied any connections
with the bombings.
</P>
<P>
During the Monday afternoon Duma session, Putin said Chechnya
had actually evolved into a "huge terrorist camp."
</P>
<P>
"If the Chechen authorities cannot control the situation and
are not asking the federal authorities for assistance, this means
that the situation suits them," he said.
</P>
<P>
"But this cannot suit us," Putin said. Therefore, a
comprehensive plan for settling the political situation in
Chechnya must be worked out, he added.
</P>
<P>
He said such a plan must envision, among other things, the
introduction of a "rigorous quarantine" regime all along the
administrative border with Chechnya. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990915.0056 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> (Urgent) Namibia's FM Elected as President of GA's </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, September 14 (Xinhua) -- Dr. Theo-Ben Gurirab,
Minister of Foreign Affairs of the Republic of Namibia, was
elected Tuesday afternoon as the President of the 54th Session of
the United Nations General Assembly(GA).
</P>
<P>
Dr. Theo-Ben Gurirab has been the Minister of Foreign Affairs
of Namibia since the country became independent in March 1990. He
is also a member of Parliament.
</P>
<P>
A member of the South West Africa People's Organization (SWAPO)
Central Committee and Politburo, Dr. Gurirab is regarded as one of
the founding fathers of the Republic.
</P>
<P>
Working to promote regional and subregional cooperation, he
represented Namibia, in 1995, on the bureau of the Organization of
African Unity (OAU) Council of Ministers.
</P>
<P>
In 1963, upon being awarded a United Nations Fellowship, he
proceeded to the United States to study. In 1964, he was appointed
one of SWAPO's Troika of Associate Representatives to the United
Nations and the Americas. In 1998, he received an award from the
World Association of former United Nations Internes and Fellows.
</P>
<P>
He was Born on January 23, 1939 in Usakos, Namibia. He is
married and has two sons.
</P>
<P>
The General Assembly, set up in 1945 under the United Nations
Charter, is the United Nations main deliberative organ and
provides a forum for multilateral discussion of the full range of
international issues covered by the Charter.
</P>
<P>
The Assembly comprises all Members of the United Nations and
meets in regular session each year from September to December, and
thereafter as required. 
</P>
</TEXT>
