<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> World Bank to Offer Sub-Sahara $3Bln in Fighting </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, September 14 (Xinhua) -- The world Bank has committed a
sum of three billion U.S. dollars in a strategic plan to fight the
HIV/AIDS pandemic in the sub-Saharan Africa.
</P>
<P>
The bank appreciates the efforts African countries are putting
in the fight against HIV/AIDS on the continent, its vice-president
for African region, Callisto Madavo said at the 11th International
Conference on AIDS and STDS (sexually transmitted diseases) in
Africa.
</P>
<P>
It has reportedly provided sub-Saharan Africa with 168 million
dollars to fight HIV/AIDS in the past.
</P>
<P>
In order to stimulate and support the implementation of the
strategy called the Intensifying Action Against HIV/AIDS in Africa
Responding to a Development Crisis, the bank has established a
multi-sectoral AIDS campaign team for Africa, which is based in
the office of the regional vice-presidents.
</P>
<P>
The high-level placement of the AIDS campaign team underscores
the World Bank's commitment to HIV/AIDS prevention and care and
will enable the team to maximize collaboration among all
development sectors.
</P>
<P>
The World Bank also expressed that it can and will play a
stronger role in responding to HIV/AIDS in Africa. 
</P>
</TEXT>
