<HEADLINE> Starving Rwandans Need 1,500 Tons of Food Relief </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, September 14 (Xinhua) -- The World Food Program (WFP),
 in conjunction with the Rwandan National Food Committee, is
planning to supply more than 1,500 tons of food to hunger-stricken
Rwandans, the Rwanda News Agency reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Coordinator of the committee, Innocent Rwakazina, said Tuesday
that northeastern Umutara and Kibungo, and southwestern Gikongoro
are the prefectures most hit by starvation.
</P>
<P>
"In Umutara, out of ten communes, eight are seriously stricken
by hunger," Rwakazina was quoted as saying. He said that his
committee will supply 550 tons of food to 7,000 families in the
prefecture.
</P>
<P>
In Kibungo prefecture, 8,500 families from five communes along
the banks of Kagera River will get 668 tons, said the food relief
official.
</P>
<P>
"The Umutara and Kibungo prefectures are known for their
aridity and scarce water resources," Rwakazina pointed out.
</P>
<P>
Unlike other regions in Rwanda, Umutara and Kibungo prefectures
have very few water resources and the underground water in those
areas is very shallow.
</P>
<P>
According to Bruno Mwanafunzi, Director of Water Resources in
the Rwandan Ministry of Public Works and Energy, the situation in
the northeastern region was exacerbated by an unusual drought that
hit the area during the prolonged dry season.
</P>
<P>
In the southwestern Gikongoro prefecture, 360 tones of food
will be given to 4,500 families in communes seriously affected by
hunger, Rwakazina said.
</P>
<P>
"Unlike the northeastern region, Gikongoro prefecture has got a
low food production due to very poor and old soils which are
acidic in nature," he added.
</P>
<P>
He indicated that in conjunction with the WFP, the Rwandan
National Food Committee will also provide 400 tons of cereals to
each prefecture where projects aimed at increasing food production
are implemented.
</P>
<P>
According to the food relief official, each family will get 50
kilograms of cereals, 25 kg of nutritious flour and 3.6 kg of
cooking oil. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990915.0066 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Coffee Prices Stable at Kenya's Nairobi Exchange </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Despite the price drop at the international markets, the
Nairobi exchange was steady, but there would be likely a supply
shortage of coffee in coming weeks, sources with the exchange
said.
</P>
<P>
According to the Nairobi Coffee Exchange, prices for T grade
coffee sold at 76 to 86 U.S. dollars per bag (50 kilograms)
Tuesday compared with 72 to 86 dollars last week while TT grade
at 85 to 94 dollars as against 72 to 86 dollars per bag in the
previous week.
</P>
<P>
Local press reported that in recent months, there had been
disputes between coffee farmers and their cooperative societies
leaders over the issues of society management and where their
coffee to be milled in the major coffee-growing area in the
country's Central Province.
</P>
<P>
As a result, their disputes had almost halted the harvesting of
coffee beans and processing at factories before delivered to the
coffee board.
</P>
<P>
Due to the scant supply, there will be no auction on September
28, but the auction will resume on October 5, the coffee exchange
said.
</P>
<P>
It is learned that to encourage coffee farmers to increase
production, the Coffee Board of Kenya has recently set aside 20
million shillings (some three million U.S. dollars) for provision
of coffee seedlings to farmers throughout the country.
</P>
<P>
Coffee is one of Kenya's major foreign exchange earners. The
coffee production in the east African country grew to a level of
140,000 tons in mid-1980s, but declined to only 40,000 tons in
1998. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
