<HEADLINE> S. Africa Develops New Anti-Crime Computer System </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, September 14 (Xinhua) -- Crime in South Africa
could be reduced by 30 percent in three years if a new computer
system lives up to its promises, state television reported
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The sophisticated investigating system will provide and link
information on criminals countrywide, reducing the amount of time
spent tracking them down, said the South African Broadcasting
Corporation (SABC) television.
</P>
<P>
MTN, a major cellular phone supplier, has contributed 1.5
million rand (250,000 U.S. dollars) to the development of the
system.
</P>
<P>
The system drew experiences of the South African police, the
Federal Bureau of Investigation of the United States and the
Scotland Yard of Britain, the television said.
</P>
<P>
The new system works on the theory that killers and rapists
work close to their home. Experts claim that in 97 out of 100
cases, the center of the circle of offenses is the criminal's
home.
</P>
<P>
With the help of other evidence such as profiles, the criminal
could be tracked down in minutes instead of months, according to
the tv report.
</P>
<P>
An Analysis finds that if delivered, the system could reduce
police work load by 40 percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
