<HEADLINE> U.N. Relocates Personnel in East Timor </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, September 14 (xinhua) -- The U.N. Mission in
East Timor (UNAMET) relocated its 120 staff and 1424 East Timorese
from its compound in the capital of Dili to Darwin, Australia
Monday night, U.N. spokesman Fred Eckhard said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The East Timorese had been forced to seek refuge at the
compound.
</P>
<P>
The United Nations saw the relocation necessary as the compound
was overcrowded and untenable with poor sanitary conditions, he
said.
</P>
<P>
U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan said the UNAMET has kept 12
international personnel as its core staff to cope with
humanitarian affairs.
</P>
<P>
He said the relocated people will take a rest in Darwin and
will return to East Timor once law and order are restored to allow
them to continue their work following the August 30 ballot, which
showed overwhelming preference to independence in East Timor.
</P>
<P>
Annan, who met Foreign Ministers of Indonesia, Portugal and
Australia here Tuesday, hoped that it should be possible to have
some elements of multinational force on the ground by the weekend
at the latest.
</P>
<P>
The Security Council was meeting Tuesday to discuss the details
of the U.N. authorized multinational force mandated to restore
peace and security in East Timor.
</P>
<P>
A draft resolution is expected to be adopted soon, forming the
framework of the multinational action. 
</P>
</TEXT>
