<HEADLINE> Portugal, Mali Sign Cooperation Agreements </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LISBON, September 14 (Xinhua) -- Portugal and Mali, who at
present preside over the Economic Community of Western African
States (CEDEAO), on Tuesday signed an agreement of cooperation
between the two countries and showed interest in strengthening
bilateral relations.
</P>
<P>
The agreement was signed in Lisbon, by the secretary of state
for Foreign Relations and Cooperation from Portugal, Luis Amado,
and the Foreign Minister for Mali, Modibo Sidibe.
</P>
<P>
In statements to the press, Luis Amado explained that the
dialogue between the two countries over the last two months, due
to the crisis in Guinea Bissau, created confidence and interest in
developing these relations.
</P>
<P>
According to the secretary of state, the Portuguese cooperation
with Africa, which is concentrated mainly in the African Countries
with Portuguese as the Official Language (PALOP), should be
diversified.
</P>
<P>
Modibo Sidibe said that the development of his country not only
needed bilateral cooperation, but also multilateral, especially
between the European Union and the CEDEAO.
</P>
<P>
Talking about Guinea Bissau, whose conflict was mediated by
CEDEAO, Sidibe said that it was necessary to continue the efforts,
so that the elections may be held, for the consolidation of all
the results gained so far. 
</P>
