<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dow Falls While Nasdaq Rising </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, September 14 (Xinhua) -- The Dow Jones industrial
average fell Tuesday as investors feared that the Federal Reserve
would raise interest rates to keep inflation from the hot U.S.
economy.
</P>
<P>
The blue chip index closed down 120.00 at 10,910.33 and the
Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 index fell 7.84 at 1,336.29. But the
technology heavy Nasdaq composite index rose 23.52 at 2,868.29.
</P>
<P>
The Dow and most indexes plunged after the Commerce Department
reported that U.S. retail sales surged 1.2 percent in August, the
biggest increase in six months. The report sparked fears among
investors that The Federal Reserve would raise rates for the third
time this year in an effort to fight inflation.
</P>
<P>
The Department also said in a separate report that the U.S.
trade deficit increased to the record high of 80.7 billion U.S.
dollars in the second quarter. The deficit increase pushed the
value of U.S. dollar lower to 105.25 against the Japanese yen,
adding to inflationary pressures.
</P>
<P>
The NYSE index fell 5.70 at 615.11 and the American Stock
Exchange index fell 3.02 at 801.48. The Russell 2000 index of
smaller companies fell 1.41 at 438.24.
</P>
<P>
Declining issues outnumbered advancers by a 5-to-2 margin on
the New York Stock Exchange, with 2,158 down, 868 up and 498
unchanged.
</P>
<P>
NYSE volume increased to 719.94 million shares from 652.22
million in the previous session. 
</P>
</TEXT>
