<DOCNO> XIE19990915.0076 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Security Council Meets on Kosovo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, September 14 (Xinhua) -- The U.N. Security
Council Tuesday began a closed late afternoon session to discuss
the latest situation in Kosovo, the Yugoslav province.
</P>
<P>
The meeting came after U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan issued
a statement through his spokesman, voicing his concern at the
worsening humanitarian situation in Yugoslavia due to a blighted
economy and other causes and calling upon donors to give a hand.
</P>
<P>
The statement said that in addition to half a million refugees
and internally displaced persons from previous Balkan conflicts,
an estimated 200,000 people had been displaced from Kosovo to
other parts of the Balkan country.
</P>
<P>
However, the statement failed to refer to NATO's 79-day
unilateral bombing of the sovereign and independent country, which
has dealt a severe blow to the economy of the nation.
</P>
<P>
There was a real threat of rising food price and dwindling drug
supply, coupled with plummeting household income due partly to a
dramatic increase in unemployment, the statement said.
</P>
<P>
Winter electricity supplies were projected to be 30 percent to
50 percent below requirements, threatening to deprive the urban
poor of heating, running water, health care and the capacity to
freeze and cook food.
</P>
<P>
In light of the "increasingly disturbing situation," Annan said
in the statement that he had asked the U.N. emergency relief
coordinator to lead efforts to mobilize resources to meet these
needs.
</P>
<P>
"The secretary-general strongly urges donors to give prompt and
generous support to this strictly humanitarian operation," the
statement said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990915.0077 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Italian Car Industry in Good Shape, Says Fiat Auto Chief </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, September 14 (Xinhua) -- Fiat Auto Chief Roberto Testore
denied Tuesday that the Italian car industry was in bad shape and
in need of new government incentives to boost it back to its 1998
level.
</P>
<P>
A recent report said that Italy recorded an 8 percent drop in
new car sales in August over the same month in 1998, compared to a
28 percent slump in the European Union.
</P>
<P>
According to Italian news agency Ansa, Testore, who was present
at Frankfurt's international car salon, said the Italian car
industry "is doing well," reporting that between 2.2 and 2.3
million new cars were expected to be sold by the end of 1999.
</P>
<P>
"Of course, the results are different from 1998, when there
were still incentives," he said, referring to the boom in car
sales last year, fueled by government incentives until July 1998
to trade in old lead-fueled cars for new environment-friendly
ones.
</P>
<P>
"In any case, we are still above what we consider the threshold
of 2 to 2.1 million car sales," Testore said.
</P>
<P>
"In the year 2000, however, we expect sales to be slightly down
to about 2.1 million cars," he said.
</P>
<P>
According to a report released Tuesday by the European
association of automakers, ACEA, new car sales in Italy fell 11.2
percent in August - traditionally a holiday month - compared to
July, against a 17.1 percent increase in the European Union.
</P>
<P>
But ACEA said that while the European Union registered 28
percent fewer new cars in August over the same month in 1998,
sales in Italy only dropped 8 percent.
</P>
<P>
Responding to a question on hopes that the government will
reintroduce car incentives, the Fiat official said these "could be
useful if they help reduce the number of older cars on the roads."
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
