<DOCNO> XIE19990915.0078 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chairpersons Elected for Six Main GA Committees </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, September 14 (Xinhua) -- The 54th General
Assembly (GA) session Tuesday elected chairpersons for its six
main committees in charge of such affairs as disarmament and
international security, and economy and finance.
</P>
<P>
The election outcome was elected shortly after the opening of
the 54th GA session on Tuesday afternoon, which elected Theo-Ben
Gurirab, Namibian foreign minister, the president of the new
session.
</P>
<P>
Raimundo Gonzalez was elected Chairman of the First Committee
of the 54th GA session, which is in charge of disarmament and
international security. He is director of Special Political
Affairs (Disarmament and International Security) in the Foreign
Ministry of Chile.
</P>
<P>
Born in 1939, Gonzalez was vice-chairman of the First Committee
during the 53rd GA session, which concluded Monday, and he is a
member of the U.N. Secretary-General's Advisory Board on
Disarmament Affairs.
</P>
<P>
Robe Olhays, the permanent representative fo Djibouti to the
United Nations, was elected chairman fo the Second Committee,
which is in charge of economic and financial affairs. Born in
April 1944, he has been the permanent representative to the United
Nations since 1988.
</P>
<P>
Vladimir Galuska, who served as the permanent representative of
the Czech Republic to the United Nations since April 1977, was
elected Chairman of the Third Committee, which is responsible for
social, cultural and humanitarian affairs.
</P>
<P>
Born in 1952, he served for three years as director of
Personnel in his country's Foreign Ministry in Prague, prior to
his United Nations appointment.
</P>
<P>
Sotirios Zackheos, permanent representative of Cyprus to the
United Nations, was elected Chairman of the Fourth Committee,
which is in charge of special political and decolonization
affairs.
</P>
<P>
Born in January 1950, he has previously chaired the Committee
on Relations with the Host Country.
</P>
<P>
Penny Wensley, the Australian permanent representative to the
United Nations, was elected chairperson of the Fifth Committee,
which is in charge of administrative and budgetary affairs.
</P>
<P>
She was the first woman to head the Fifth Committee in the
history of the General Assembly.
</P>
<P>
Prior to her current U.N. appointment, she, a career diplomat
since 1968, was head of the North Asia Division in the Department
of Foreign Affairs and Trade and Australian permanent
representative to the United Nations in Geneva from 1992 to 1995.
</P>
<P>
Phakiso Mochochoko, senior counsellor at Lesotho's Mission to
the United Nations, was elected chairman of the Sixth Committee,
which is in charge of legal affairs.
</P>
<P>
Born in September 1957, he was vice-chairman of the Sixth
Committee at the 53rd GA session.
</P>
<P>
The General Assembly is the main deliberative organ. It is
composed of representatives of all Member States, each of which
has one vote.
</P>
<P>
The General Assembly's regular session usually begins each year
in September. At the start of each regular session, the Assembly
elects a new President, 21 vice-Presidents and the Chairpersons of
the Assembly's six main committees, which hold discussions on
issues concerned after the GA's general debate. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990915.0079 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Explosion Renders Downtown Toronto Out of Power </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, September 14 (Xinhua) -- A transformer explosion
rendered the downtown core of Toronto out of power Tuesday
afternoon.
</P>
<P>
A Canadian press report from Toronto said that the accident
happened around 3 p.m. after routine maintenance at a key hydro
station.
</P>
<P>
The country's highest CN Tower was hit by the blackout, with
the elevators inside the tower of 553.33 meters coming to a sudden
stop. Backup generators were put into operation within minutes,
but no new visitors were admitted, according to the report.
</P>
<P>
The power interruption also affected several major broadcasters
including City-TV, which went off the air only to resume
broadcasting shortly after newscasters operated from its outside
parking lot.
</P>
<P>
Firefighters were called in to attend to the explosion induced
fire at the power station, where no casualties or injuries have
been reported.
</P>
<P>
The report quoted Toronto Hydro as saying it would likely be a
couple of hours before power could be restored to the area.
</P>
</TEXT>
