<DOCNO> XIE19990915.0080 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Greek PM Voices Shocked Over Deputy FM's Death </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, September 14 (Xinhua) -- Greek Prime Minister Costas
Simitis Wednesday night expressed his deep shock over the death of
the country's Alternate Foreign Minister Yiannos Kranidiotis.
</P>
<P>
Simitis praised Kranidiotis for his tireless in his duty and
sternly defending the interests of Greece.
</P>
<P>
Kranidiotis represented Greece with knowledge, skill and
determination, the premier said, adding that his sudden and unjust
loss created a large and irreplaceable vacuum.
</P>
<P>
Kranidiotis, who was born in Nicosia, Cyprus in 1947, died
later Wednesday in an accident when his plane plummeted from an
altitude of 23,000 feet to 6,000 feet just before landing in the
Bucharest international airport.
</P>
<P>
The plane, a falcon commuter jet, reportedly fell into an air
pocket and five other passengers, including Kranidiotis' son, were
killed and two other passengers seriously injured.
</P>
<P>
Kranidiotis, who could speak fluent English and French, became
Greece's deputy Foreign Minister in 1994.
</P>
<P>
In February this year, he assumed his last government post as
Alternate Foreign Minister in charge of European affairs. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
