<HEADLINE> Taliban Asks for UN Recognition </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, September 14 (Xinhua) -- Afghanistan's ruling
Taliban Tuesday asked the United Nations to recognize its
administration.
</P>
<P>
In a letter to U.N. Secretary General Kofi Annan, the Taliban's
number-two leader Mulla Mohammad Rabbani said he "regretted" that
the U.N. understanding of events in Afghanistan was "not based on
reality."
</P>
<P>
The United Nations has failed to "differentiate between the
true and legitimate representatives of this nation and the false
representatives," said the letter officially released here.
</P>
<P>
The Taliban leader claimed that they had protected the
country's integrity and "the United Nations, aware of this
reality, should therefore adopt a fair, just and honest decision
towards this nation."
</P>
<P>
The deposed government headed by Burhanuddin Rabbani is still
widely known as the legitimate ruler of Afghanistan and only
Pakistan, Saudi Arabia and the United Arab Emirates recognize the
Taliban's rule over the war-torn country.
</P>
<P>
Mulla Rabbani also rejected a recent U.N. report on human
rights in Afghanistan, saying the militia has committed no human
rights violations in the "95 percent" of the country it controls.
</P>
<P>
Radhika Coomaraswamy, the U.N. special rapporteur on violence
against women, last week toured Afghanistan and lashed out at the
Taliban for "widespread, systematic and officially sanctioned"
discrimination against women. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
