<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Argentine Cabinet Presents Budget for Year 2000 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUENOS AIRES, September 14 (Xinhua) -- The Argentine cabinet on
Tuesday presented a draft national budget for year 2000 to the
congress, which forecasts a 3.5 percent growth rate of gross
domestic product (GDP).
</P>
<P>
Prime Minister Jorge Rodriguez said in a statement that the
country's GDP may reach 297.543 billion U.S. dollars in 2000.
</P>
<P>
The budget forecasts a financial deficit of 5.311 billion
dollars or 17.8 percent of the GDP, with income totaling 42.864
billion dollars and global spending 48.175 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
It also estimates the current account deficit to be 13.11
billion dollars, and income from direct foreign investment and
financial capital to be 15.525 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
It increases resources for areas of health, education, social
loans to low income families, children and the disabled. 
</P>
</TEXT>
