<DOCNO> XIE19990915.0097 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australia Faces Funding Black Hole in Defense </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, September 15 (Xinhua) -- Australia's role in a
peacekeeping mission in East Timor will significantly upset the
country's budget, the Financial Review reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The paper quoted senior government sources as saying the cost
of the peacekeeping force of 4,500 soldiers could be as high as
325 million U.S. dollars while the estimated cost per refugee in
Australia was 1,950 U.S. dollars per person per month.
</P>
<P>
The Australian government promised to send 4,500 soldiers to
East Timor, composing the biggest part of a multinational
peacekeeping force which will be commanded by Australia's Major
General Peter Cosgrove.
</P>
<P>
So far 2,523 East Timor refugees have been evacuated to
Australia, with more expected, and they would take the additional
cost to at least 23.4 million U.S. dollars a year not including
airlift charges, the paper said.
</P>
<P>
In addition, Australia seemed to be pursuing a "leading role"
in the region. "We are responding to our moral and regional
responsibilities. We will face considerable challenges and
strains," Australian Treasurer Peter Costello said Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
Quoting government sources, the Financial Review said the
demands of Australia's "new strategic role in the region" would
create a funding freeze in education, health and other spending
ministries.
</P>
<P>
There is a looming funding black hole in defense over the next
decade, with the defense forces looking to upgrade or replace the
F-111s, the FA-18s and some of the older destroyers, the paper
estimated. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
