<HEADLINE> Irvine to Get Top Cat Treatment from Jaguar </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, September 14 (Xinhua) -- Formula One driver Eddie
Irvine will get top-cat treatment by Jaguar next season instead of
the track dogsbody role he had rejected at Ferrari.
</P>
<P>
Hopeful of winning this year's world championship, Irvine will
drive for Jaguar Racing in 2000 as one of the worst kept secrets
in the Formula One paddock was finally confirmed on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The promise came from Jackie Stewart whose young team was
renamed after one of the most glamorous of car marques following
their buy-out by Ford earlier this year.
</P>
<P>
Three-time champion Stewart believes Irvine will flourish next
season when he will be released from the four-year shackles he was
under at Ferrari who wanted him to remain as Michael Schumacher's
number two.
</P>
<P>
"I think Eddie has suffered considerably by being under the
leadership, if you could call it that, of Schumacher," said
Stewart, who will continue as chairman and chief executive of
Jaguar Racing.
</P>
<P>
"At Ferrari there was one man that they worked for and that was
Schumacher. If they had time for anything else that was Eddie
only second.
</P>
<P>
"He could not take that any more. He had to have a space of
his own and he has justified it and I think we have got a very,
very good man in the team.
</P>
<P>
"He is very fit, very strong-minded. To have been able to put
up with what he has had to put up with he had to have tremendous
stability in his mind.
</P>
<P>
"That is a great strength for a racing driver and I think he is
going to do very well for the Jaguar Racing team," he added.
</P>
<P>
Irvine, despite an apparent lack of support from Ferrari, is
still a serious contender for the drivers' crown with just three
races left after moving level with reigning champion Mika Hakkinen
in Italy last weekend. 
</P>
</TEXT>
