<DOCNO> XIE19990915.0102 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Argentine Official Criticizes IMF Forecast </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUENOS AIRES, September 14 (Xinhua) -- Argentina's Vice
Secretary of Finance Miguel Kiguel considered as "pessimistic" the
forecasts by the International Monetary Fund (IMF) of an economic
growth of 1 percent for the country in the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
For some reason, the forecast by the IMF is not in accord with
some favorable objective factors, such as a more favorable
international climate, said Kiguel in an interview published on
Tuesday by the newspaper "El Cronista."
</P>
<P>
"The IMF is taking a very conservative stance" and "has little
respect" for the capacity of the gross domestic product (GDP) of
Argentina, said the official.
</P>
<P>
Kiguel said that the GDP of the country would grow by 3.5
percent over the next year, due to the provisions of a stronger
impetus from Brazil, Paraguay and Uruguay, Argentina's partners in
the South American Common Market.
</P>
<P>
Kiguel also denied that the elections on October 24, in which
president Carlos Menem will be replaced, would have adverse
repercussions on the economy.
</P>
<P>
The GDP of Argentina contracted by 4.9 percent in the second
quarter of this year, compared with the same period in 1998, due
to the recession which was worsened by the contraction of the
Brazilian economy, confirmed Kiguel.
</P>
<P>
On Monday, The Argentine government said it estimated its
budget deficit next year at 4.5 billion dollars, a target below
this year's likely shortfall. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
