<DOCNO> XIE19990915.0107 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese School Teachers to Receive More Training </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 15 (Xinhua) -- The Ministry of Education is
to launch a nationwide retraining program for improving
professional skills of 10 million of primary and middle school
teachers.
</P>
<P>
Today's China Daily reported that the professional skills of
the Chinese primary and middle school teachers and nearly 1
million school masters are expected to be upgraded in the next
five years by implementation of the retraining program.
</P>
<P>
The central government will allocated 130 million yuan (16
million U.S. dollars) over the next two years to fund the
retaining project, according to the ministry's Teacher Training
Department.
</P>
<P>
Lu Fuyuan, vice-minister of Education, said all primary and
middle school teachers are expected to receive additional
professional training.
</P>
<P>
He made the remarks at a national conference on retraining
primary and middle school teachers and headmasters opened in
Shanghai yesterday.
</P>
<P>
The training is expected to encourage teachers to create more
efficient teaching methods and to help them develop respect for
their students' personalities and mentalities in the classrooms.
</P>
<P>
The retraining program will focus on computer-aided and other
modern teaching skills, Lu said.
</P>
<P>
Teachers and headmasters who are found unqualified after
receiving retraining will be dismissed from their posts.
</P>
<P>
China has 700,000 primary and middle schools which are attended
by 200 million students.
</P>
<P>
The ministry encourages regional educational departments to
introduce flexible training methods for teachers.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
