<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 0100 GMT, September 15 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS -- Kiribati, the Republic of Nauru and the
Kingdom of Tonga Tuesday afternoon were admitted to Membership of
the United Nations at the opening of the 54 session of the United
Nations General Assembly.
</P>
<P>
The admission of the three countries, announced by the newly
elected President of the General Assembly, Dr. Theo-Ben Gurirab of
Namibia, raised the total members from 185 to 188. (New Members-
UN)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS -- The U.N. Mission in East Timor (UNAMET)
relocated its 120 staff and 1,424 East Timorese from its compound
in the capital of Dili to Darwin, Australia Monday night, U.N.
spokesman Fred Eckhard said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The East Timorese had been forced to seek refuge at the
compound.
</P>
<P>
The United Nations saw the relocation necessary as the compound
was overcrowded and untenable with poor sanitary conditions, he
said. (UN-East Timor)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS -- The U.N.-sanctioned multi-national force will
cooperate with Indonesia in keeping peace in East Timor, said
Foreign Minister Ali Alatas Tuesday, ruling out the imminent
withdrawal of the Indonesian army.
</P>
<P>
The Indonesian troops "are not withdrawing yet, but there will
be cooperation between the multi-national and the Indonesian
forces", said the Minister, emerging from his talks with U.N.
Secretary-General Kofi Annan and Australian Foreign Minister
Alexander Downer Tuesday morning. (UN-East Timor-Indonesia)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS -- The U.N. Security Council Tuesday began a
closed late afternoon session to discuss the latest situation in
Kosovo, the Yugoslav province.
</P>
<P>
The meeting came after U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan issued
a statement through his spokesman, voicing his concern at the
worsening humanitarian situation in Yugoslavia due to a blighted
economy and other causes and calling upon donors to give a hand.
(UN-Kosovo)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
ISLAMABAD -- Afghanistan's ruling Taliban Tuesday asked the
United Nations to recognize its administration. In a letter to U.N.
Secretary General Kofi Annan, the Taliban's number-two leader
Mulla Mohammad Rabbani said he "regretted" that the U.N.
understanding of events in Afghanistan was "not based on reality."
(Pakistan-Afghan Taliban)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
BAGHDAD -- Iraqi Foreign Undersecretary Nazar Hamdoun on
Tuesday refuted a U.S. official's remarks that Iraq poses a threat
to its neighboring countries and Iraqi government should be
responsible for the sufferings of its people.
</P>
<P>
In a statement carried by the Iraqi News Agency, Hamdoun said
the remarks by U.S. Assistant Secretary of State Martin Indyk
reflected the U.S. disappointment over its failure to prevent Iraq
from chairing the just concluded Arab League (AL) foreign
ministers meeting. (Iraq-US)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- Israeli-Palestinan Joint Committee on Safe Passage
on Tuesday committed to strike a deal on the opening of the "safe
passage" linking the Gaza Strip and West Bank by the end of this
month.
</P>
<P>
In a meeting held in Tel Aviv Tuesday afternoon, the committee
discussed in detail about the opening of the safe passage linking
Gaza and Hebron, but members from the two sides are still at odds
over some relevant issues such as car registrations, Israel's
stoppage of suspects and security inspection by the Israeli
security forces, Israel Radio said. (Israel-Safe Passage)
</P>
</TEXT>
