<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Issel Reclaims Nuggets' Coaching Reins </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 15 (Xinhua) -- Dan Issel, who spent the
past 18 months trying to piece together a competitive roster as
general manager of the Denver Nuggets, on Tuesday signed a three-
year deal to serve as coach for the second time, replacing Mike D'
Antoni.
</P>
<P>
New billionaire owner Donald Sturm, who bought the team in late
July, offered Issel the coaching position. The Hall of Famer
admitted it was difficult to fire D'Antoni, whom he hired before
the lockout-shortened 1999 season, but pointed out the urgency of
rebuilding the Nuggets into the contender.
</P>
<P>
"If this wasn't day when I had to part company with a good
friend, it would be a happy day for me," Issel said. "I think the
reason I accepted is because we're trying to do what is best for
the Denver Nuggets.
</P>
<P>
"Being here for a shortened season didn't give Mike the biggest
opportunity, but we don't have a long opportunity to turn this
team around. We want to bring stability to the situation. We
have completely revamped the roster in the last year and a half,
we have some players who are going to have an impact."
</P>
<P>
The urgency to make the Nuggets -- who have won 25 games over
the last two seasons -- competitive grew with the team moving into
the new Pepis Center this season. Sturm led a group of local
investors who bought the Nuggets, the NHL's Colrado Avalanche and
the Pepsi Center -- which replaces McNichols Arena -- for 461
million U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
But Issel insisted Sturm did not force him into accepting the
coaching position, saying, "He was supportive, he gave me the
contract but left the final decision to me. With a two- or three-
year window to get the contract to respectability, we feel this is
the right choice."
</P>
<P>
Issel, 50, coached the Nuggets for two-plus seasons, compiling
a 96-102 record before resigning 34 games into the 1994-95
campaign.
</P>
<P>
Since Issel stepped down as coach midway through the 1994-95
season, the Nuggets have floundered. The franchise hit a low
point in the 1997-98 season, when Denver went 11-71 and nearly
matched the all-time record for NBA futility set by the
Philadelphia 76ers in 1972-73.
</P>
<P>
Issel is one of the four players whose numbers have been
retired by the Nuggets. His name became synonymous with the
franchise during his playing days from 1975-85. When Issel retired
in 1985, he left as Denver's all-time leading scorer and rebounder.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
