<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Initiates Safety Inspection for Its 50th Anniversary </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 15 (Xinhua) -- China is making great efforts
to ensure safety during the upcoming celebration of its 50th
founding anniversary, and has begun a week-long safety inspection
in Beijing.
</P>
<P>
"It is a serious political task to ensure the celebrations -- a
monumental event for Beijing and the whole country -- proceed
smoothly and safely," Shi Wanpeng, vice-minister of the State
Economic and Trade Commission (SETC), was quoted by Wednesday's
China Daily as saying.
</P>
<P>
The SETC, in cooperation with the ministries of construction
and railways, the Civil Aviation Administration of China and the
State Bureau of Quality and Technical Supervision, initiated the
inspection yesterday.
</P>
<P>
The inspection group will examine Beijing's main facilities in
civil aviation, chemical industry, subway system, power supply,
construction and metallurgical sectors to help remove any "hidden
dangers", Shi said.
</P>
<P>
To stem the rise of casualties in traffic, industrial, fire,
swimming, gas and food poisoning accidents, Beijing has
strengthened safety supervision on production, eliminated safety
loopholes, and ordered enterprises to implement State laws and
regulations on work safety to the letter, according to the Beijing
Bureau of Labor and Social Security.
</P>
<P>
Since Beijing will host grand parades, exhibitions, fireworks
displays and art performances, fire control is among the top
concerns for the municipal government.
</P>
<P>
The Beijing Fire Control Bureau will deploy more than 2,000
fire control policemen and 54 fire engines during the celebration,
the newspaper said.
</P>
<P>
"We should ensure that during the celebrations, there will be
no fires in the Tian'anmen Square, no fires in the celebration
park tours or large exhibition venues, and no big fires in the
whole city," director of the bureau Liu Ruixiang said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
