<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sixteen Asian Countries Discuss International Relations </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ALMA ATA, September 14 (Xinhua) -- Foreign ministers and deputy
foreign ministers from 16 Asian countries ended their meeting here
Tuesday after issuing a declaration on the basic principles of
international relations.
</P>
<P>
The declaration said to strengthen mutual trust and
coordination among them, countries should observe the recognized
basic norms of mutual respect for state sovereignty and
territorial integrity, no interference in each others' internal
affairs, solution of differences through peaceful means, no use of
force or threat of force, and promotion of economic and cultural
cooperation.
</P>
<P>
Adding that the general situation in Asia is healthy, it said
unstable factors still exist, noting the recent developments in
South Asia, Afghanistan and the southern region of Kirgystan
having caused great concern to the people.
</P>
<P>
Chinese Deputy Foreign Minister Wang Yingfan expressed at the
meeting that cooperation among the 16 countries will help maintain
the regional security and stability.
</P>
<P>
The meeting, initiated by Kazakh President Nursultan Nazarbayev
in 1992, has gained support from most countries in Asia. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
