<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Facts and Figures on China's Standing in the World </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Editor's note: The People's Republic of China celebrates its
50th founding anniversary this year and Xinhua will release 10
stories on key facts and figures on the nation's economic and
social development over the last half century. This is the first.
</P>
<P>
BEIJING, September 15 (Xinhua) -- The 50 years since the
founding of the People's Republic of China has seen remarkable
improvements in China's international status. The following facts
and figures indicate this:
</P>
<P>
China's GDP in 1998 was 7.955 trillion yuan, nearly 30 times
that of 1952 in real terms.
</P>
<P>
From 1952 to 1998, China's GDP increased at an annual rate of 7.
7 percent, compared to 3.3 percent for the world economy as a
whole.
</P>
<P>
According to World bank estimates, China's economy ranked
seventh in the world in 1997, after the United States, Japan,
Germany, France, Britain and Italy.
</P>
<P>
By the end of 1997, China led the world in grain, meat, cotton,
peanut, rapeseed, fruit, steel, coal, cement, fertilizer, an TV
production.
</P>
<P>
That same year, China's cotton cloth, chemical fiber, and
electricity output was second in the world, tea, soy bean, and
sugar cane production came third, sugar came fourth, and crude oil
was fifth.
</P>
<P>
In 1998, China's foreign trade was worth 323.9 billion U.S.
dollars, nearly 16 times the 1978 figure, and 11th in the world.
</P>
<P>
By the end of 1998, China's foreign reserves were worth 145
billion U.S. dollars, putting it in second place in the world for
the third consecutive year.
</P>
<P>
By the end of 1998, China had approved 324,000 overseas-funded
projects, worth 573.2 billion U.S. dollars of overseas investment,
and actual investment of 265.6 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
From 1993 to 1998, China ranked second in the world and first
among developing countries in attracting foreign investment for
six consecutive years.
</P>
<P>
In 1998, China had earnings worth 12.6 billion U.S. dollars
from 63.48 million overseas tourists, putting it in seventh place
in earnings in the world, after the United States, Italy, France,
Spain, Britain and Germany.
</P>
<P>
By the end of 1997, China had 1.67 million scientists and
engineers and 1.99 million doctors, the largest number for any
country in the world. Average life expectancy in China is 71 years,
compared to the world average of 64 years.
</P>
<P>
In 1998, food expenditures accounted for 53 and 45 percent of
rural and urban residents' total expenditure, respectively.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
