<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesia Senior Shuttlers Not Allowed to Leave </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PBSI executive director Karsono said that men's singles veteran
Hariyanto Arbi and men's doubles specialist Rexy Mainaky should
not leave the center because they were still in top form. "Both
players are still in the world's top rankings. We must not let
them go. They should be made to feel a part of the center,"
Karsono said.
</P>
<P>
Arbi, the 1993 world champion, has planned to move to Singapore,
and Mainaky has received an offer to coach England next month.
</P>
<P>
Both players expressed disappointment over some PBSI officials'
unfair treatment toward them. The officials urged both veterans
to leave the center as they had not shown any outstanding
performances recently.
</P>
<P>
But Arbi had a reversal of fortune by winning the Singapore
Open and Mainaky had the same by winning the Indonesia Open with
partner Ricky Subagja. The pair won the 1996 Olympic Games in
Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
Karsono said Arbi had told Arisanto, an official of the Central
Java branch of PBSI, that he had canceled his plan to move to
Singapore.
</P>
<P>
"Arbi has assured me that five Indonesian men's singles --
Hendrawan, Taufik Hidayat, Budi Santoso, Marlev Mainaky and Arbi
himself -- have a chance to bring home the Olympic gold medal," he
said.
</P>
<P>
"I think Mainaky still has a chance to retain his gold medal
with Subagja. Indonesia still needs them," he added.
</P>
<P>
Karsono expressed worry that both players' plan to move could
inspire other athletes to use the training center only as a
stepping stone to move to another country.
</P>
<P>
"If that happens in the future, we won't have top players
anymore because they will have moved on to other countries," he
said.
</P>
<P>
Karsono said he would meet the secretary-general, officials in
charge of athlete development and athletes to discuss and solve
the problem.
</P>
<P>
and, Arie Sudewo, chairman of the National Sports Council (KONI)
, said he would meet PBSI officials to discuss the issue. "I
think PBSI athlete development officials must intensify their
efforts to make shuttlers feel appreciated. It is regrettable if
those players want to move, but that's their right," he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
