<HEADLINE> U.S. Investment, Trade With Vietnam Down in 1999 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANOI, September 15 (Xinhua) -- Vietnam's trade with the United
States and U.S. investment in Vietnam both slipped in the first
eight months of 1999, said the latest issue of Vietnam Investment
Review.
</P>
<P>
Vietnam's export volume to the United States from the beginning
of the year to the end of August totaled just 250 million U.S.
dollars, according to Vietnam's customs statistics.
</P>
<P>
Several new products, namely cinnamon, handicrafts, tea, fruit
and vegetables, finally broke into the U.S. market but their value
totaled a paltry 5 million dollars.
</P>
<P>
At the same time export earnings to the United States from key
export goods such as crude oil, rice and coffee nose-dived.
</P>
<P>
In the first eight months of this year, rice volume was just
3.3 percent of last year's total and coffee exports plummeted 70
percent. And what is more, Vietnam exported no crude oil to the
United States in the eight months.
</P>
<P>
Last year, Vietnamese exports to the U.S. market were worth a
record 468.6 million dollars while, over the same period, U.S.
investors broke into the top 10 countries in terms of foreign
investment in Vietnam.
</P>
<P>
Throughout the first eight months of the year, just six
projects with an investment capital of 53 million dollars were
licensed for U.S. investors.
</P>
<P>
In sharp contrast, 16 projects worth 92.3 million dollars were
licensed last year while 16 projects worth 277 million dollars
were licensed in 1997.
</P>
<P>
Based on the latest trade statistics, Vietnam Investment Review
said, Vietnamese economists suggested that Vietnam would struggle
to reach last year's record trade haul. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
