<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Qi Xiuyu: A Helping Hand to Laid-offs (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DALIAN, September 15 (Xinhua) -- Editor's note: This year marks
the 50th anniversary of the founding of the People's Republic of
China. Xinhua News Agency is releasing about 50 stories on Chinese
men and women, young and old, illustrating the changes that have
taken place in China over the past half century. These people will
describe their own experiences and how they fit into the changes
in the motherland.
</P>
<P>
An employment agency in Dalian, northeast China's Liaoning
Province, headed by 45-year-old Qi Xiuyu, has helped over 10,000
laid-off workers get back on the job since it opened early this
year.
</P>
<P>
"I thought I had been in a dream when President Jiang Zemin
shook hands with me," said Qi, recalling her meeting several
months ago with the top Chinese leader, who congratulated her on
her extraordinary performance.
</P>
<P>
Qi had endeavored on her own to find suitable jobs for over 15,
000 unemployed before the service center was officially set up by
the Dalian Labor Bureau.
</P>
<P>
"Qi is just like an older sister, and she is really kind and
helpful," said 41-year-old Zhao Shulan with gratitude. Qi tried
dozens of times to find a job for Zhao.
</P>
<P>
"Great changes have taken place in the labor market. It was
rare for laid-off workers to go to the market when it was set up
in 1992, as most of them were used to being assigned jobs by the
government," Qi said.
</P>
<P>
Now, dozens of staff members in the agency assist an average
170 people daily, and sometimes as many as 300. Qi has to get up
at 6 a.m. every day to review the registration forms from the
previous day and arrange interviews for the applicants.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990915.0133 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australians Help Design New City Section in Southwestern Chinese Municipality </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHONGQING, September 15 (Xinhua) -- An Australian company has
joined Chongqing, a metropolis in southwest China, to design its
northern section, an area called Jiangbei.
</P>
<P>
A contract recently signed between the Asia-Pacific Designing
Group (APDG) and the municipal government of Chongqing gives the
Australians three months to submit initial designs for the modern
spot, which is expected to be the center of the city in the 21st
century.
</P>
<P>
According to the government plan, Jiangbei will be the
administrative, cultural, information and traffic heart of
Chongqing.
</P>
<P>
Last year, the municipal government published its open tender
on the Internet and it soon received dozens of bidders. The
Australian firm won the bidding in almost one year.
</P>
<P>
Construction of Jiangbei should take 15-20 years to complete at
the cost of some 100 billion yuan (12 billion US dollars). The
city government hopes the new town will be comparable to the
Pudong New Area in Shanghai, the largest economic powerhouse in
China.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990915.0134 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Qi Xiuyu: A Helping Hand to Laid-offs (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
In spite of the heavy workload, Qi is really proud of her job.
Whenever she hears the words like "Thanks a lot, Qi," from the
applicants, she feels truly rewarded. In order to find a most
suitable job for everyone who registers with the agency, she needs
to get a clear idea of what the applicant really wants by using
well-honed interviewing skills, she said.
</P>
<P>
But situations don't always work out. Some laid-off workers
blame Qi instead of themselves for not finding a suitable job.
Once a man even cursed her when he did not pass the job interview.
"I don't blame them, because I know that they are distressed and
in a bad mood when they don't get the job," Qi said.
</P>
<P>
About 3,000 unemployed applied for over 4,600 job vacancies
last month. But often many don't get hired, as some aren't
qualified and others don't want to do some of the humbler
occupations, such as sanitation worker.
</P>
<P>
Qi explained that some people will have to have more training,
while others ought to think in more practical terms.
</P>
<P>
"I try to find as many job opportunities as possible by various
means. And sometimes I do not even have time for lunch," she said.
"I can't let them down when they turn to me for help."
</P>
<P>
Qi never shows off the service awards she has received. "I am
just a common person, and what I have done is just to try my best
to help people in difficulty."
</P>
<P>
Qi, born in a worker's family with seven kids, has been a
village doctor, a worker in a leather factory, and an accountant.
Her apartment is filled with plants and books, which, she said,
help ease her mind after a stressful day at work. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
