<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sri Lanka to Set Up Committee to Monitor Fund Use </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, September 15 (Xinhua) -- Sri Lanka has decided to
appoint a committee with wide powers to examine whether funds made
available through the budget and foreign loans and grants are used
without waste and corruption, the official Daily News reported
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The government has made this decision because about half of the
funds allocated for national development under the previous
governments from 1977 to 1994 had drained away through waste and
corruption, the paper said.
</P>
<P>
The committee, to be appointed by President Chandrika
Kumaratunga, will examine whether funds allocated for national
development have been properly used and whether estimates are in
order and completed works are up to the expected standard and
conform to the plans, a cabinet minister was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
The minister said the president made a nationwide public appeal
a few weeks ago for informing her directly if any form of
corruption or irregularities have taken place in the course of
development programs that are being implemented.
</P>
<P>
Persons found guilty by the committee, whether they are
politicians or officials who have defrauded funds allocated for
national development, will be punished, the minister added.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
