<DOCNO> XIE19990915.0139 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Environmental Protection Vital to China's Sustainable Development ( 2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
A report released by the World Health Organization (WHO) last
year showed that among the ten most heavily polluted cities in the
world, seven are in China.
</P>
<P>
Aware of the ever-increasing dangers of environmental pollution,
people in China ranging from top party leaders to ordinary
individuals have begun taking serious steps to save nature.
</P>
<P>
Just weeks after the catastrophic flooding along the Yangtze
and Songhua rivers last year, the State Council, the Chinese
cabinet, banned the logging of virgin forests in many areas,
locked away logging tools and vehicles and even destroyed roads
accessing the forested regions. A million loggers were turned into
a nationwide force to plant trees.
</P>
<P>
In the past two years, China allocated 10 billion yuan (1.2
billion US dollars) to combat the pollution along Huaihe River and
several billion yuan to clean up Taihu Lake in east China.
</P>
<P>
China has long been engaged in prevention and control of soil
erosion. The annual Tree Planting Festival, initiated at the
recommendation of the late leader Deng Xiaoping, and the massive
"Northern Afforestation Project," which has been underway for 21
consecutive years, have created a green belt across the full width
of China's arid northern territory, bringing enormous benefits to
150 million people in the region.
</P>
<P>
China has also worked ceaselessly for city environmental
protection. Now 70 percent of the motor vehicles in big cities
meet the emissions standards stipulated in the laws and
regulations. The use of leaded gasoline is now prohibited in more
than 20 cities in the country, and a nationwide ban will take
effect on January 1, 2000.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
