<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Museum of Stone Tablets Reopens </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
XI'AN, September 15 (Xinhua) -- A museum containing a vast
array of stone tablets and carvings has reopened in this capital
city of northwest China's Shaanxi Province after a 10-month
renovation.
</P>
<P>
The remodeled design, covering an area of more than 900 square
meters, includes 97 exhibits, 19 of which were shown to visitors
for the first time.
</P>
<P>
Among the exhibits are seven state-listed art treasures, such
as a stone horse carved in relief which was placed in the tomb of
Li Shimin, Emperor Taizong of the Tang Dynasty (618-907 a.d.), and
a jade carving of Lao Zi, founder of the Taoism in China, during
the Spring and Autumn and Warning States period (770 b.c.-221 b.c.)
.
</P>
<P>
"This is the largest collection of high-grade indoor stone
carvings so far found in China. Many exhibits hold an important
position in the China's sculpture history," said a Chinese expert.
</P>
<P>
The original facility, built in the early 1960s, has received
more than 10 million visitors over the past 30 years.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
