<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ignorance of Y2K Problem Revealed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Only 63 percent of those polled in a recent survey conducted by
the Horizon Market Research Corp. in 11 major cities could provide
a clear definition of the dangerous bug.
</P>
<P>
More than 4,500 residents from Beijing, Shanghai, Guangzhou,
Chengdu and other cities took part in the survey.
</P>
<P>
About 8.4 percent of those polled said they had some rough idea
of the cause and potentially harmful effects of the problem, but
could not specify.
</P>
<P>
Other people came up with surprising explanations for the Y2K
problem that ranged from worms, viruses and fossils to corrupt
officials.
</P>
<P>
People with access to computers were better informed about the
millennium bug, the survey found. Out of all personal computer
owners who participated in the survey, more than 86 percent could
give a clear account of the problem as well as safety precaution
measures, displaying much higher than average Y2K knowledge.
</P>
<P>
Residents in the more developed southeastern coasts tend to
show greater interest in and understanding of the Y2K problem than
those in the inland cities, according to the survey. More than 77
percent of the respondents in Guangzhou could identify the cause
of the millennium bug, but the figure dropped to below 60 percent
in Zhengzhou of Henan Province and Wuhan of Hubei Province.
</P>
<P>
The millennium bug, or the Year 2000 (Y2K) Problem threatens to
cause computer program failures and system breakdown from the
first day of next year when computer chips will not be able to
differentiate between the year 2000 with 1900.
</P>
<P>
Unlike the indifference of many residents towards the Y2K
problem, State departments are gearing up efforts to take safety
precautions.
</P>
<P>
To date, thorough checks have been carried out on computing
systems in key sectors including banking, securities, civil
aviation and power sectors, as well as the global system for
mobile communications networks to ensure that all the systems will
be Y2K-compliant. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
