<BODY>
<HEADLINE> World's 1st Petroglyph Museum Built In China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HOHHOT, September 15 (Xinhua)-- A museum filled with
petroglyphs, or stone pictures, carved by local ethnic herdsmen
will open on October 1 at Baotou, in north China's Inner Mongolia
Autonomous Region.
</P>
<P>
More than 80 petroglyphs are on display, depicting vividly the
life of local ethnic herding people living in different periods in
Chinese history. The museum is said to be the first of its kind in
the world.
</P>
<P>
Local experts said the herdsmen made the carvings as a way of
recording their lives and the activities of animals.
</P>
<P>
Some 30,000 stone pictures have been discovered in the
autonomous region. In recent years human activities and natural
wear and tear have endangered the pictures, Mayor Niu Yuru said.
</P>
<P>
Petroglyphs have been spotted extensively in northern,
northwestern and southwestern parts of China, especially in Inner
Mongolia.
</P>
<P>
The museum is part of the local government's effort to protect
the rare cultural relics, the mayor said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
