<HEADLINE> One More Power Plant Goes Into Operation in Myanmar </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YANGON, September 15 (Xinhua) -- Ahlone Combined Cycle Power
Plant of the state-run Myanmar Electric Power Enterprise (MEPE)
was commissioned in the western Ahlone township of the capital
Tuesday, official newspaper The New Light of Myanmar reported
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The power plant with a capacity of 54 megawatts uses recycled
waste from three nearby 33-megawatt gas-fired turbines of the
Ahlone power station to generate 350 million kilowatt-hours of
electricity annually.
</P>
<P>
The plant is one of the two combined-cycle power plants
installed with the cooperation of the Marubeni Corporation of
Japan under a contract reached between the MEPE and the Japanese
company in March 1997.
</P>
<P>
The plant was installed at a cost of 27.71 million U.S. dollars
plus 649.77 million kyats (2.16 million dollars) and was completed
in July this year, three months ahead of schedule.
</P>
<P>
The other plant, the Hlawga plant in Mingaladon township in the
capital started operation in May this year.
</P>
<P>
Myanmar Minister of Electric Power Major-General Tin Htut said
while inaugurating the Ahlone plant that the country's power
consumption at present is 750 megawatts, up 127 percent from
1988's 330 megawatts.
</P>
<P>
He said plans are under way to implement more power projects in
view of the rising power demand in the country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
