<HEADLINE> Thailand Launches Campaign to Promote Brown Rice </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, September 15 (Xinhua) -- The Public Health Ministry of
Thailand has launched a campaign urging health officials to
consume brown rice to set an example for the general public, The
Nation reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Deputy Health Minister Kamronna Lamphun was quoted as saying
brown rice had been consumed by Thais for many generations but was
later ignored as the country developed.
</P>
<P>
He said brown rice, with its nutritional richness, would
promote a healthy diet while at the same time saving energy.
</P>
<P>
Unlike white rice, which must be polished three times, brown
rice is polished just once to take off the husk.
</P>
<P>
Chatree Sumethavanit, deputy secretary-general of the ministry,
was also quoted as saying the ministry had given brown rice to
patients in some hospitals it controls.
</P>
<P>
He said the lifestyle of high consumption of fat, protein and
sugar with less fiber had put people at the risk of such illnesses
as diabetes, high blood pressure, heart disease and cancer.
</P>
<P>
Brown rice contains a higher level of vitamins and minerals
than white rice, thus not only promoting efficient functioning of
the body but also helping prevent diseases such as colon cancer
and high blood pressure, Chatree said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
