<BODY>
<HEADLINE> ADB Predicts 5-Percent GDP Growth for Sri Lanka </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, September 15 (Xinhua) -- The Asian Development Bank
(ADB) has predicted a 5-percent gross domestic product (GDP)
growth for Sri Lanka in 1999 against 5.3 percent in 1998.
</P>
<P>
The ADB said in its latest report "Asian Development Outlook"
that Sri Lanka's GDP growth was about 3.8 percent in real terms
during the first half of this year, against 5.3 percent in the
whole of 1998, due to slow growth in all sectors except mining and
quarrying.
</P>
<P>
However, Sri Lanka's GDP growth will pick up to 5 percent this
year because the private- and public-sector initiatives are likely
to be realized in the second half.
</P>
<P>
Sri Lanka's central bank has forecast that GDP will grow by
about 4 percent in 1999 against 4.7 percent in 1998.
</P>
<P>
The ADB said Sri Lanka has made concerted efforts for
developing the local debt market by introducing longer-term
marketable instruments including bond issues.
</P>
<P>
Revenue performance during the first half of 1999 improved,
particularly income tax, national security levy and excise duties,
the report said.
</P>
<P>
Revenue is expected to recover to around 17.7 percent of GDP in
1999 from 17.3 percent the previous year.
</P>
<P>
The better management of public expenditure is expected to
contain the expenditure at 18 percent of GDP. The monitoring and
control of defense expenditure has also been strengthened.
</P>
<P>
The report added that an overall balance of payment surplus of
90 million U.S. dollars is expected due to foreign long-term
private and official capital inflows. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
