<HEADLINE> Thai Juvenile Court Sees Surge of Drug Cases </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, September 15 (Xinhua) -- More than 38,400 young people
in Thailand were found guilty of drug charges and sent to
correctional institutes by the Central Juvenile and Family Court
last year, The Bangkok Post reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Most of the youngsters came from communities and families
involved in drugs and were tempted by friends to try and finally
became drug addicts, the newspaper quoted Chief Justice Sompol
Sattayapithan as saying.
</P>
<P>
Those who became involved in the drug trade were mostly pushed
into it by their parents who knew the Central Juvenile and Family
Court rarely sentenced young people to jail, the chief justice
said.
</P>
<P>
In Thailand, addicted young people were usually sent to serve
time at rehabilitation centers and those found guilty of dealing
in drugs went to observation and protection centers.
</P>
<P>
Most of these young people resumed using or dealing in drugs
upon returning to the same old environment which was conducive to
illegal activities, Sompol said.
</P>
<P>
Last year, a total of 38,472 youngsters, 35,181 boys and 3,291
girls, were found guilty of drug charges, mostly involving
methamphetamines.
</P>
<P>
Sompol said the Central Juvenile and Family Court could not
find new places, jobs or schools for youngsters released from
observation centers because of limited funds.
</P>
<P>
In the case of repeat offenders, the court had no policy to
increase penalties because, according to the chief justice, this
was not the way to solve the problem. 
</P>
</TEXT>
