<HEADLINE> China, U.S. Officials Hail Jiang-Clinton Summit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 14 (Xinhua) -- Chinese Ambassador to the
United States Li Zhaoxing Tuesday spoke highly of the meeting
between Chinese President Jiang Zemin and his U.S. counterpart
Bill Clinton in Auckland, New Zealand, on September 11.
</P>
<P>
The meeting is "positive, constructive, useful and very
significant," Li told a conference here on U.S.-China Relations on
the Eve of the 21st Century, sponsored by the Center for Strategic
and International Studies.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese ambassador expressed his hope that after the summit,
the two countries would overcome their setbacks and difficulties
and bring their important relationship back to a normal and sound
track.
</P>
<P>
Li said after Lee Teng-hui's "state-to-state" fallacy, the
relationship between China and the U.S. faced "the most dangerous
challenge."
</P>
<P>
He described it as a "positive thing" that just on the
following day after Lee pronounced this fallacy, Clinton had a
telephone call with Jiang, during which he reaffirmed America's
policy of recognizing only one China and the U.S. commitment to
the principles enshrined in the three joint communiques between
China and the U.S..
</P>
<P>
"We believe and hope that America will honor its commitment.
And on such principled basis our relationship can be assured of
having a sound and smooth-going development and continuous
improvement," he added.
</P>
<P>
Speaking on the same occasion, Democratic Senator Max Baucus
described the summit as "successful and responsible" and "an
important step towards substantive dialogs on issues of importance
to both sides."
</P>
<P>
"No unrealistic promises were made and (there is) no hyperbole
of the nature of the relationship," said Baucus.
</P>
<P>
David Dreier, a Republican Representative of House from
California, also said it is a "positive sign" for improvement of
America-China relations.
</P>
<P>
Dreier hoped that the two countries would soon strike a deal on
China's accession to the World Trade Organization after the
successful meeting between the two leaders.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Susan Shirk, U.S. deputy assistant secretary of
state on East Asian and Pacific affairs, said the meeting between
the two presidents has established a foundation for renewed
progress in the bilateral relationship.
</P>
<P>
"Both sides were determined to get back on track and make
progress," she said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
