<HEADLINE> Thai Consumer Confidence Low Despite Recovery Forecast </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, September 15 (Xinhua) -- Despite forecast of an
economic recovery by various agencies, Thai consumers are still
reluctant to spend their money, a report from the Center for
Economic and Business Forecasting of the Thai Chamber of Commerce
University said.
</P>
<P>
According to the report, which is available Wednesday, the
consumer confidence index measured by the forecasting center stood
at 67.4 points in August, down from 70.3 points in July.
</P>
<P>
The report said that while economic figures, particularly in
the manufacturing sector, indicated a gradual recovery, the income
levels remained static.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the index for employment prospects was down to 58.6
points from 61.2 and the index measuring the expected income in
the future stood at 78.1 compared with 83.2 a month earlier.
</P>
<P>
The index has a full scale of 200 points, providing a snapshot
view of the economy.
</P>
<P>
Declining indicators, which measured the consumers' confidence
in the country's economy, reflect uncertainty about economic
recovery, center director Thanavath Phonvichai said in the report.
</P>
<P>
He attributed the drop in the consumer confidence index mainly
to a sharp rise in oil prices coupled with the weakened baht.
</P>
<P>
Local worries about the stability of the financial sector also
dampened the sentiment, he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
