<DOCNO> XIE19990915.0157 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Politicians Express Support for One-China Policy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 14 (Xinhua) -- Former U.S. President
George Bush and other prominent figures Tuesday expressed their
support for the one-China policy, urging the authorities in Taiwan
not to attempt to change the formula.
</P>
<P>
In a meeting with Chinese Ambassador Li Zhaoxing to the United
States, Bush said he would continue to support the one-China
policy and the principles adopted in the three joint Sino-U.S.
communiques, which China believes enshrine guiding principles for
Sino-U.S. relations.
</P>
<P>
Bush made the remarks at a time when the situation across the
Taiwan Straits grew tense after Taiwan's Lee Tenghui pronounced
the "special state-to-state relations" between Taiwan and the
Chinese mainland.
</P>
<P>
Also on Tuesday, Zbigniew Brzezinski, former presidential
national security advisor, told a conference on Sino-U.S.
relations at the Center for Strategic and International Studies (
CSIS) that the "two states" statement has its "political and geo-
political meaning."
</P>
<P>
"That formula is nothing less than an attempt to legitimate the
permanent division of China, to create a situation in which the
formula of one-China masking the reality of the existing division
while retaining formally the notion of single state is changed
into a formula in which there are separate states," he said.
</P>
<P>
"For the Chinese, to accept this formula would be to acquiesce
in the division of China," Brzezinski noted. "I do not believe
that we have the right to demand that."
</P>
<P>
He also criticized the demand by a group of U.S. politicians to
request the U.S. to "defend Taiwan." "It is an assault on the
formula that has maintained the stability of the American-Chinese
relations for more than a quarter of century."
</P>
<P>
"It goes beyond the Taiwan Relations Act formulated by Congress
on a bipartisan basis," Brzezinski added. "The Taiwan Act does not
constitute an automatic, unconditional commitment to defend Taiwan
no matter what the Taiwanese themselves decided to do."
</P>
<P>
Brzezinski also believes that the U.S. administration should
make it clear to the authorities in Taiwan that "sudden and
objectively provocative initiatives are not viewed with favor by
the United States."
</P>
<P>
Also speaking at the CSIS meeting, Senator Max Baucus called
for no change of the relationship across the straits, which has
served the interests of Taiwan, the Chinese mainland and the
United States for 25 years.
</P>
<P>
The one-China policy has served the People's Republic of China,
including Taiwan, the United States and the world very well for
over a quarter of a century, he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990915.0158 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> CPPCC Vice-Chairman on Reunification of Motherland (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 15 (Xinhua) -- Zhang Kehui, Taiwan-born Vice-
Chairman of the National Committee of the Chinese People's
Political Consultative Conference (CPPCC) today urged that cross-
Straits negotiations begin as soon as possible.
</P>
<P>
Zhang, also chairman of the Central Committee of the Taiwan
Democratic Self-government League said, "I love Taiwan, I love
inland areas and I will love more a powerful and reunified
motherland."
</P>
<P>
The 71-year-old told Xinhua that he hoped the Taiwan
authorities would miss no opportunity to respond to President
Jiang Zemin's call for talks at an early date.
</P>
<P>
He said he will continue to lead the Taiwan Democratic Self-
government League in pushing forward cross-Straits exchanges and
the early realization of direct exchanges of mail delivery, trade
and shipping services.
</P>
<P>
Zhang was born in Changhua, Taiwan, and left in 1948 to study
at the Xiamen University in east China'sm Fujian Province.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
