<HEADLINE> CPPCC Vice-Chairman on Reunification of Motherland (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Thirty-one years later, he was re-united with his parents and
other family members in Tokyo, Japan. His overjoyed mother
prepared dumplings made of glutinous rice wrapped in bamboo, all
ingredients from Taiwan.
</P>
<P>
In 1988 Zhang's younger brothers and sisters accompanied their
parents on a trip to inland areas.
</P>
<P>
Taiwan authorities did not allow him to return to Taiwan when
his mother died in 1992 because of his "special identity." However,
he was permitted to go to Taiwan for his father's funeral in 1993
after the Taiwan authorities succumbed to a strongly negative
public reaction.
</P>
<P>
Zhang joined the army after graduation from university, and
after the founding of New China in 1949, he was promoted from a
grassroots official in Fujian to vice-chairman of the CPPCC
National Committee.
</P>
<P>
He believes that the biggest tragedy for the Chinese nation is
the separation of Taiwan and inland areas. "The tragedy should be
ended in our generation," he said. 
