<HEADLINE> Australian Aircraft Ready for Food Drops to E.Timor </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, September 15 (Xinhua) -- Australian aircraft are
ready to begin food drops to starving refugees in East Timor but
final details have yet to be resolved.
</P>
<P>
"At this stage we don't know when they are going to happen," a
government source said on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
"There are a few issues still to be decided, including flight
approvals from Indonesia," he said.
</P>
<P>
"We are doing everything we can to prepare for the drops as
soon as possible and as safely as possible," he added.
</P>
<P>
The source said security was an obvious concern for the
flights, as was the mountainous terrain and the risk that food may
not reach those in need.
</P>
<P>
It was hoped that the food drops could start Thursday following
Indonesia's in-principle permission for drops in the mountains of
East Timor, where tens of thousands of displaced people have taken
refuge, some reportedly surviving on roots and leaves.
</P>
<P>
The Australian government aid coordination group AusAID has
stockpiled tons of food and medical supplies in a 1,500
square-meter warehouse leased near Darwin airport in northern
Australia.
</P>
<P>
Prime Minister John Howard said Tuesday discussions were
proceeding between the government and AusAID on how the drops
could be conducted.
</P>
<P>
Further talks are also continuing between the United Nations
and Indonesian officials to determine flight clearances. 
</P>
