<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Security Council Authorizes Force for East Timor </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, September 15 (Xinhua) -- The U.N. Security
Council early Wednesday morning unanimously adopted a resolution
authorizing the establishment of a multi-national force to restore
peace and security in East Timor.
</P>
<P>
Citing Chapter VII of the U.N. Charter which allows the use of
force, the council "determined that the present situation in East
Timor constitutes a threat to peace and security", according to
the resolution.
</P>
<P>
The council welcomes the expressed commitment of Indonesia to
cooperate with the multinational force in all aspects of the
implementation of its mandate and looks forward to close
coordination between the force and Indonesia.
</P>
<P>
The force under a unified command structure is mandated also to
protect and support the U.N. Mission in East Timor (UNAMET) in
carrying out its tasks following the August 30 referendum which
showed preference of East Timor's independence over its special
autonomy within Indonesia.
</P>
<P>
The council agrees that the force should collectively be
deployed in East Timor until replaced as soon as possible by a U.N.
peace-keeping operation. Its expenses will be borne by the
participating states.
</P>
<P>
The resolution was endorsed after two days of intensified
consultations of the 15 Security Council members on the details of
the plan.
</P>
<P>
U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan who met with Foreign
Ministers of Indonesia, Portugal and Australia Tuesday, said he
hopes that an advance contingent could be on the ground in East
Timor by the weekend "at the latest".
</P>
<P>
Since the result of East Timor ballot was announced on
September 4, violence has taken place in the former Portuguese
colony which was integrated by Indonesia in 1976.
</P>
<P>
Australian Foreign Minister Alexander Downer wrote to Annan
Tuesday that Australia would accept the leadership of the
multinational force, as requested by Annan and it is prepared to "
make a substantial contribution" to the force. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
