<HEADLINE> China's First Large-Scale Hydropower Station Left Behind </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANGZHOU, September 15 (Xinhua) -- Though squeezed out of China
's top 50 power stations, the Xin'anjiang Hydropower Station, the
country's first large-scale power plant built by Chinese, is still
the pride of the local people.
</P>
<P>
"As the first landmark in hydropower development in New China,
it has played and is still playing a major role in fueling the
local economy," said Yu Zhiqun, the station's director.
</P>
<P>
The station was built in the 1950s, when the country suffered a
severe shortage of electricity, on the Xin'an River in the western
part of Zhejiang Province in east China.
</P>
<P>
Over the past few decades, the station, with 662,500 kilowatts
in installed capacity, has generated 60.2 billion kwh of
electricity and impounded 146 flood peaks, while acting as an
example for hydropower development, station management, and
resettlement of people in reservoir areas.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, it formed a huge reservoir with 1,078 islands, which
is part of a golden tourist route linking Hangzhou, provincial
capital of Zhejiang, and Mount Huangshan in neighboring Anhui
Province.
</P>
<P>
The reservoir, now called Qiandao Lake, hosts millions of
domestic and overseas tourists annually.
</P>
<P>
An upgrading project was launched in October 1997 to
computerize the power station's equipment and raise its installed
capacity to 810,000 kw by the year 2004.
</P>
<P>
However, it will be left further behind anyway, as a series of
new power stations are being built including the Ertan Hydro-
electric Power Station, which will have six generating units each
with a capacity of 550,000 kw, and the mammoth Three Gorges
hydropower project which will have a total installed capacity of
20.9 million kw and a projected yearly production of more than 100
billion kwh of electricity.
</P>
<P>
"But we'll always be proud of the Xin'anjiang Hydropower
Station because it has laid a foundation for New China's power
industry," Yu said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
