<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Exhibition of Golden Age of Chinese Archaeology Opens in U.S. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 14 (Xinhua) -- The Golden Age of Chinese
Archaeology, a landmark exhibition of the most important
archeological discoveries of China in the last 50 years, opened at
the National Gallery of Art in Washington Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
Present at the opening ceremony were over 500 people, including
Chinese Ambassador to the United States Li Zhaoxing, Director
General of State Administration of Cultural Heritage of China
Zhang Wenbin, U.S. Secretary of Education Richard Riley, high-
ranking officials of the U.S. Department of State and Department
of Treasury as well as some U.S. Congressmen.
</P>
<P>
The exhibition will provide people with a unique opportunity to
see masterpieces dating from 5000 B.C. to the 10th century A.D. (
the Neolithic through the feudal Song dynasty).
</P>
<P>
Over 230 pieces of works on show were excavated from various
archaeological sites since the founding of the People's Republic
of China in 1949, including almost 100 objects unearthed in the
1980s and 1990s alone. Many were found in tombs and were probably
created for use during the lifetime of the deceased as well as for
the afterlife. Representing the earliest and best of each category,
many have never been exhibited before in the United States or
outside China.
</P>
<P>
The Golden Age of Chinese Archaeology is a sequel to the
exhibition of Chinese archaeological finds at the National Gallery
of Art in 1974. The current exhibition, which covers a great range
of ancient Chinese cultures, shows that Chinese civilization and
art did not originate at a specific time or place, as previously
believed, but developed from the interaction and assimilation
among various cultures that flourished concurrently all over China.
</P>
<P>
At the dinner to mark the opening of the exhibition, Chinese
Ambassador Li said the exhibition will promote the understanding
between the peoples of China and the United States and enhance the
friendship of the two countries.
</P>
<P>
Robert Smith, president and trustee of the National Gallery of
Art, said that the discipline of archaeology reveals to the
American people the history and the spirit of a people. "The
exquisite works we have seen tonight bear witness to the very
ancient and brilliant civilization of China, and enlarge greatly
our understanding of both the history and the spirit of the
Chinese people."
</P>
<P>
The fact that these beautiful objects have all been found,
preserved and studied since the founding of the People's Republic
of China in 1949 is a remarkable achievement, justifying the title
"The Golden Age of Chinese Archaeology," and marking this great
exhibition a most fitting celebration of the cultural heritage of
the People's Republic of China, Smith said.
</P>
<P>
The exhibition, which will end on January 2, 2000, was jointly
sponsored by the State Administration of Cultural Heritage of
China, the National Gallery of Art and the Nelson-Atkins Museum of
Art in Kansas City of the United States.
</P>
<P>
After its showing at the National Gallery of Art, the
exhibition will be on display in Houston from February 13 through
May 7, 2000, and in San Francisco from June 17 through September
11, 2000. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990915.0173 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-15 07:14 </DATE_TIME>
