<DOCNO> XIE19990915.0174 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Booming Postal Sector Amid China's Economic Growth (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 15 (Xinhua) -- China's rapid economic
growth has upgraded the country's postal facilities to a level
that now matches any country in the world, said Thomas Leavey,
general director of the International Bureau of the Universal
Postal Union (UPU).
</P>
<P>
China's postal sector has grown at an average rate of nearly
nine percent in recent years, far above the world average of three
percent.
</P>
<P>
Xia Lixin of the State Post Bureau (SPB) said this sector has
never before been more challenged.
</P>
<P>
One veteran postman, Gong Benyu, has been in the postal service
for 26 years in the city of Linjiang in northeast China's Jilin
Province and has walked 220,000 kilometers delivering letters.
</P>
<P>
However, with telephones and other modern telecommunications
facilities now widely used, traditional mail service is undergoing
a sharp decline these days. In 1998, ordinary mail service
accounted for only ten percent of the total postal earnings in
China.
</P>
<P>
As Xia put it, the ever-increasing demands of customers can
only be met by innovations in the postal service.
</P>
<P>
China's Express Mail Service (EMS) reported earnings of 20,000
yuan when first introduced in 1980. This figure rose swiftly to
exceed 3.1 billion yuan in 1998, equal to that of ordinary mail
service.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990915.0175 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Booming Postal Sector Amid China's Economic Growth (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Ma Ye, a man from Qinghai Province in the northwest who is
doing business in Beijing, told Xinhua that it took more than one
month for a parcel to travel from Qinghai to Beijing a couple of
dozen years ago.
</P>
<P>
Now, it only takes one day to deliver his sample commodities
from Guangzhou to Beijing via EMS, and the journey from Lhasa to
Beijing takes three days. "It is worthwhile to pay the fee," he
said, "it saves me so much time, which is dearer to me."
</P>
<P>
At present, the postal savings service, philately, EMS, and
newspaper and periodical distribution account for 86 percent of
China's postal earnings.
</P>
<P>
In addition, postal bureaus in major cities have been linked to
the Internet, which will bring faster and more efficient services
to customers.
</P>
<P>
Some tens of billions of yuan are being poured into developing
a modern postal service network across the country each year.
</P>
<P>
China's capital Beijing now provides around-the-clock services
for customers via Internet, and self-service post offices,
according to Xia Lixin.
</P>
<P>
"The promising economic growth has brought about huge potential
in China's postal market," said Leavey, adding that it will become
the world's largest market in the next century.
</P>
<P>
The UPU made China the host country for its 22nd Congress, and
has selected the country to chair the Council of Administration (
CA) of the UPU for the next five-year term, thanks to China's
important status in the international community, he said.
</P>
<P>
Leavey also expects a more important role for China in
international postal service as the country becomes stronger in
terms of its economy and international standing. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
