<HEADLINE> Kenya Assures Commitment to Investors </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, September 15 (Xinhua) -- Kenya is committed to give
investors a safe and secure environment to make initial
investments and continue ploughing back profits for expansion,
Kenyan Minister of Finance Chris Okemo has said.
</P>
<P>
Because of the need to maintain an open and pragmatic approach
to investors, Kenya joined the Multilateral Investments Guarantee
Agency, the People daily newspaper Wednesday quoted the minister
as saying.
</P>
<P>
Okemo made the remarks during a recent signing of an agreement
here on the promotion and protection of investments between Kenya,
Britain and Northern Ireland.
</P>
<P>
He noted that to support investment, his government is taking
major reforms to restructure the economy and reduce involvement
of the public sector in those activities and services which the
private sector can provide better.
</P>
<P>
"We are now focusing on improved governance including reforms
in the procurement process, accounting and financial management
among other measures," the minister said, adding that in so doing
Kenya may call upon its development partners for both technical
and financial support.
</P>
<P>
Foreign direct investment in the next millennium would be the
driving force for high and sustainable growth in the country,
which must be complemented by local savings, the minister added.
</P>
