<HEADLINE> Netanyahu May Face Bribery Probe </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, September 15 (Xinhua) -- Israeli police are opening
an investigation of former Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu on
suspicions that he received bribes and misused public funds,
Israel's media reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
A senior police source told Israel News Agency (Itim) Tuesday
night that both Netanyahu and his wife Sara will have to be
interrogated to hear their explanations regarding the charges.
</P>
<P>
The case broke Tuesday when local Hebrew paper Yediot Aharonot
ran a promotion of its own investigation into Netanyahu's dealings.
</P>
<P>
According to the daily, Netanyahu received various domestic
maintenance and home renovation services from Avner Amedi, a
58-year-old Jerusalem businessman who owns a maintenance company.
</P>
<P>
The report said that Amedi's company supplied Netanyahus with
a variety of services during his term as prime minister, but Amedi
neither requested nor received any payment for the services, which
carried out not only at the prime minister's office, but at the
couple's home and their official residence.
</P>
<P>
According to the story, when Netanyahu lost the May election,
Amedi presented the Prime Minister's Office a bill for 440,000
Shekels (about 100,000 U.S. dollars). The Treasury authorized
payment to him only 12,000 U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
The report said Netanyahu claimed he never asked Amedi to carry
out work for him.
</P>
<P>
Police arrested Amedi on Tuesday on suspicion of having bribed
Netanyahu and the Tel Aviv Magistrate Court remanded him for two
days. 
</P>
</TEXT>
