<HEADLINE> Australia Identifies More Land for Plantations </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, September 15 (Xinhua) -- Australia has more than 19
million hectares of land waiting to play host to plantations and
farm forestry, the country's chief commodities forecaster
Wednesday said in a report.
</P>
<P>
The Australian Bureau of Agriculture and Resource Economics
(ABARE) has identified parts of Western Australia, Tasmania and
the Green Triangle region of South Australia and Victoria as
suitable for plantations.
</P>
<P>
"The total land suitable for plantation development in all the
regions covered in this study is estimated at just over 19 million
hectares," the ABARE said.
</P>
<P>
Developing plantations could provide thousands more jobs
throughout Australia, the bureau said in the report on the Forest
Plantations on Cleared Agricultural Land in Australia.
</P>
<P>
ABARE acting executive director Vivek Tulpule said the report
showed the significant economic potential of plantations and farm
forestry.
</P>
<P>
He said the aim of the study was to raise the profile of
plantations by providing data to governments, industry and
landowners interested in developing plantations.
</P>
<P>
Australia already has 1.2 million hectares of plantations.
</P>
