<BODY>
<HEADLINE> One Million-Year-Old Elephant Fossil Found in East China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JINAN, September 15 (Xinhua) -- Chinese archeologists have
found the fossilized remains of a mammoth elephant dating back one
million years at the bottom of a river in Zhucheng City of
Shandong Province, east China.
</P>
<P>
The elephant's tusk is about 3.3 meters, according to the
archeologists.
</P>
<P>
They estimate that the elephant lived during the period between
2.6 million and one million years ago.
</P>
<P>
The giant creature belongs to a class of ancient elephant that
appeared on earth three million years ago, and disappeared 10,000
years ago. The fossils of such elephants were first discovered in
India.
</P>
<P>
The new discovery is expected to provide valuable material for
the study of the ancient climate and the evolution of animals in
the area.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990915.0193 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-15 07:58 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Egypt to Host MENA Meeting If Peace Prevails: FM </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, September 15 (Xinhua) -- Egypt is ready to host an
international conference next year to discuss Middle East economic
cooperation, the country's foreign minister has said in remarks
published on the Egyptian Gazette newspaper Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
"There will be a possibility for Egypt to host the conference
next year after the revival of the Palestinian, Syrian and
Lebanese peace tracks," Amr Moussa told reporters Tuesday on the
fringes of an economic meeting in Cairo.
</P>
<P>
Moussa was referring to the Middle East and North Africa (MENA)
Economic Conference aimed at boosting Arab-Israeli cooperation.
The annual conference kicked off in 1994 in Morocco. It was not
held in 1998 and 1999 due to the deadlock in the Middle East peace
process triggered by the hardline policy of former Israeli Prime
Minister Benjamin Netanyahu.
</P>
<P>
Moussa, meanwhile, conditioned the conference on progress of
the Arab-Israeli peace talks. "If there is no peace (in the Middle
East) there will be no (MENA) conference," he said.
</P>
<P>
"That's why Egypt was not interested in hosting or attending
the conference over the past three years," the foreign minister
was quoted as saying by the English-language newspaper.
</P>
<P>
Egypt alongside a number of Arab countries boycotted the 1997
session in the Qatari capital of Doha to protest the intransigence
of Netanyahu.
</P>
<P>
After the new Israeli Prime Minister, Ehud Barak, took office
in early July, optimism prevails for the peace process. Israel has
begun carrying out the revised Wye peace accord signed early this
month. The Palestinians and Israel started the final status talks
on Monday to discuss thorny issues including Jerusalem,
Palestinian statehood and the refugee issue.
</P>
<P>
The peace talks between Syria and Israel have been stalled for
more than three years due to disputes over the Golan Heights
captured by Israel from Syria in the 1967 Arab-Israeli War. The
two sides have expressed readiness to resume talks. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990915.0194 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Vietnam Explores Markets in Middle East, Africa </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANOI, September 15 (Xinhua) -- Vietnam has reported progress
in its efforts to explore markets in the Middle East and Africa.
</P>
<P>
Vietnam's Ministry of Trade expects the country's 1999 exports
to the Middle East and Africa to soar to 500 million U.S. dollars
from some 350 million dollars last year, the business newspaper
The Saigon Times Daily said on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Chief of the Southwest Asia and Africa Department of Vietnam's
Ministry of Trade Vu Thi Them said Vietnam could achieve this
target due to increasing food and engine shipments to the Middle
East.
</P>
<P>
Vietnam's exports to Africa were usually through aid programs,
she said. The 1999 export sales to this market would probably be
at most a meager 30 million dollars.
</P>
<P>
The Vietnamese government recently permitted the Ministry of
Trade to open representative offices in Dubai of the United Arab
Emirates and South Africa to promote trade.
</P>
<P>
The ministry is also planning to ask the government for
permission to open representative offices in Senegal and Algeria.
</P>
<P>
She said the ministry is finalizing the required procedures to
enable the two offices to commence operation early next year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990915.0195 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Adapt or Perish, Gulf Family Businesses Told </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ABU DHABI, September 15 (Xinhua) -- Family businesses in the
Gulf have been advised to adapt to the changes that will be
brought about by the World Trade Organization (WTO) regulations,
or else face severe competition because of the soon-to-emerge new
global economic order.
</P>
<P>
"If you are adaptive, you will survive. If not, Gulf businesses
will not be able to stand on their feet," Mishal Hamed Kanoo,
deputy chairman of the Dubai-based Kanoo Group, was quoted by the
Gulf News daily as saying on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
"Forget the idea that the government will protect you," Kanoo
said. He added that Gulf businesses should not take it for granted
that foreign companies would sign cooperative contracts with them
in their favor.
</P>
<P>
Gulf businesses must "think of a partnership where both parties
benefit," he said.
</P>
<P>
Kanoo estimated that in the United Arab Emirates (UAE), between
75 to 85 percent of economy is controlled by family enterprises,
which are protected by the government.
</P>
<P>
Besides reducing dependence on protection from government, as
ways to adapt to WTO regulations, Kanoo suggested the ushering in
of top-level management practices.
</P>
<P>
"Get the best management techniques and also pay for it. In
addition, change the way you run your business," he said.
</P>
<P>
He pointed out that Gulf businesses should learn to add value
to their economies rather than gain from the system.
</P>
<P>
Except Oman and Saudi Arabia, all the Gulf Cooperation Council
states, namely the UAE, Kuwait, Qatar and Bahrain, are members of
the WTO, with family enterprises likely to control business worth
over 300 billion U.S. dollars, Kanno said.
</P>
<P>
Family businesses are the main generators of gross domestic
product (GDP) in most Gulf economies and also the main providers
of employment," he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990915.0196 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australian PM Welcomes Security Council Resolution </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, September 15 (Xinhua) -- Australian Prime Minister
John Howard Wednesday welcomed the United Nations Security Council
authorization of an multinational force in East Timor.
</P>
<P>
"It is an historic resolution, it is a major hurdle cleared,"
he told reporters here.
</P>
<P>
"Australia has accepted leadership of the multinational force,"
he said. "The speed with which the Security Council has acted is
very impressive."
</P>
<P>
The Security Council Wednesday authorized an multinational
force to move into East Timor to restore peace and security.
</P>
<P>
Howard said Australia wanted to see the multinational force in
East Timor as soon as possible.
</P>
<P>
He expected cooperation between the multinational force and the
Indonesian military as Australia took the leadership role.
</P>
<P>
He also believed that "there will be ... a very significant
element of ASEAN (Association of Southeast Asian Nations)
participation."
</P>
<P>
Australia did not intend to have joint exercises with
contributing nations such as the United States before deployment
into East Timor, he said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, he hoped the food drops to East Timor would commence
as early as Thursday.
</P>
<P>
"We're keen to make food drops: It remains our hope that we can
make them in the next day or two depending upon the sort of
assurances and clearances we get," he said.
</P>
<P>
Howard said he would travel to northern Australian city of
Darwin to see off the Australian troops whenever they leave for
East Timor.
</P>
<P>
Opposition Leader Kim Beazley would also be asked to
participate in the farewell, he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
