<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Insurance Market In Better Order (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 15 (Xinhua) -- China has seen much better
order in its insurance agent market, thanks to a six-month
rectification campaign, the China Insurance Regulatory Commission
(CIRC) said here today.
</P>
<P>
CIRC chairman Ma Yongwei told a meeting here that the watchdog
commission implemented a review of all part-time agents' licenses,
71,000 of which were applied for, but only 59,000 were granted
renewals.
</P>
<P>
The CIRC carried out a full investigation into the illegal
activities of overseas insurance intermediaries and their
representatives in China.
</P>
<P>
According to its estimate, these firms earned more than 400
million yuan (about 48.3 million U.S. dollars) from illegal
businesses in 1998.
</P>
<P>
Two overseas firms, the Sedgwick Insurance &AMP; Risk Management
Consultants (China) Ltd. and the Jardine Insurance Brokers Limited
paid a high price for their illegal activities.
</P>
<P>
Sedgwick was closed for three months, while Jardine's Beijing
representative office was closed permanently.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990915.0199 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Swaziland's Parliament Rejects Proposed Health </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, September 15 (Xinhua) -- In a major setback for
AIDS control in Swaziland, the House of Assembly has thrown out
the proposed Public Health Bill on the pretext that further
consultation is needed, Business Day newspaper reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The legislation was 10 years in the making and resulted from
extensive consultation with doctors, nurses, hospital
administrators and even traditional healers, the paper said.
</P>
<P>
Privately, some members of parliament admitted they were
personally put off by the bill's proposal that the immediate
families of AIDS sufferers be notified that they have contracted
the fatal disease.
</P>
<P>
Health and Social Welfare Minister Phetsile Dlamini said
because AIDS patients did not divulge their condition to anyone,
sexual partners are put at risk and families waste money seeking
treatment for the undisclosed malady.
</P>
<P>
In rejecting the legislation, members of parliament appeared to
be displaying a national phobia of acknowledging the AIDS disease,
the paper said.
</P>
<P>
Though a study by the United Nations estimates one-third of
Swazis are infected with the HIV virus that leads to AIDS, the
Health Ministry put the figure at 22.5 percent and only less than
a dozen people have publicly admitted their condition. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990915.0200 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Insurance Market In Better Order (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
During the rectification campaign, more than 800 people were
punished for rule violations, and eight will be prosecuted.
</P>
<P>
A number of other companies were also penalized for breaking
regulatory rules.
</P>
<P>
All the individual agents were ordered to sign new agency
contracts with their insurance firms.
</P>
<P>
The watchdog commission also unified the prices of all
intermediate businesses.
</P>
<P>
According to Ma Yongwei, the campaign has resulted in a
remarkable decrease in illegal activities and a major improvement
in the insurance market.
</P>
<P>
However, he warned that the rectification of the market will be
a long and painstaking job and that measures must be taken to
prevent a recurrence of illegal activities after the campaign.
</P>
<P>
He disclosed that in the next stage, the commission will
investigate the 70,000-odd rural insurance agents, who will also
be re-registered.
</P>
<P>
The chairman disclosed that they are working on a package of
new measures to promote the development of insurance in China,
including the intermediary sector.
</P>
<P>
Noting that China's insurance intermediary sector is still
underdeveloped and cannot satisfy market needs, Ma said the CIRC
will grant licenses to a number of specialized intermediary
organizations.
</P>
<P>
The establishment of specialized intermediaries will help
optimize the distribution of resources, improve the efficiency of
the insurance market, and serve the insured better, he added.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
