<DOCNO> XIE19990915.0213 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Longest Expressway Operational </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NANNING, September 15 (Xinhua) -- A 650-km-long expressway in
south China's Guangxi Zhuang Autonomous Region opened to traffic
today, running from the famous tourist city of Guilin to the port
city of Beihai.
</P>
<P>
With a total investment of 10.6 billion yuan, the expressway,
the longest in the country, crosses eight cities and l0 counties
and has four to six two-way lanes with a width of 15-21 meters,
and speed limits of 80-120 kmh.
</P>
<P>
The Guilin-Beihai expressway was started in 1993, and is 300 km
longer than the Shenyang-Dalian Expressway in Liaoning Province,
and the Jinan-Qingdao Expressway in Shandong Province.
</P>
<P>
Huang Zhendong, the Minister of Communications, said that this
expressway will help both social and economic development in the
heavily populated region.
</P>
<P>
The Guilin-Liuzhou section of the expressway was completed in
May last year, and it can handle 4,000 to 5,000 vehicles per day.
Every year, this section takes about 600,000 passengers to tourism
sites and economic zones in Guangxi.
</P>
<P>
The expressway will cut the trip from Guilin to Beihai to 6
hours, and is expected to increase the region's GDP by 4 billion
yuan annually, Huang said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
