<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesian Military Accepts Australia Leadership in Peacekeeping Force to E.Timor </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, September 15 (Xinhua) -- Indonesia's National Defense
Forces (TNI) said Wednesday it can accept Australia leading the
multinational force to East Timor if it is the decision of the
U.N. Security Council.
</P>
<P>
"If God is willing, TNI and all the Indonesian people will
accept the (U.N.) decision because Indonesia should put themselves
as part of the international community," TNI spokesman Maj. Gen.
Sudrajat said here.
</P>
<P>
In New York, the U.N. Security Council Wednesday morning
unanimously adopted a resolution authorizing the establishment of
a multinational force to restore peace and security in East Timor.
</P>
<P>
The force under a unified command structure is mandated to
protect and support the U.N. Assistance Mission in East Timor
(UNAMET) in carrying out its tasks after the August 30 direct
ballot which showed preference of East Timor's independence over
its special autonomy within Indonesia.
</P>
<P>
U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan said he hopes that an advance
contingent could be on the ground in East Timor by the weekend "at
the latest."
</P>
<P>
Welcoming the decision, Australian Prime Minister John Howard
Wednesday said his country has accepted leadership of the
multinational force.
</P>
<P>
Since the result of the East Timor ballot was announced on
September 4, violence has taken place in the former Portuguese
colony which was integrated by Indonesia in 1976.
</P>
<P>
Commander of the Information Task Force of the East Timor
Military Emergency Region Lt. Col. Willem Wednesday said the
condition in East Timor, particularly in Dili, the capital, now
was much better and safer compared to that before the martial law
was declared on September 7.
</P>
<P>
However, the Antara News Agency Wednesday reported from Dili
that gunfire was still being heard, particularly at night, and
arson still occurred. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990915.0217 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 21 Tamil Rebels Killed in Northern Sri Lanka </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, September 15 (Xinhua) -- At least 21 Tamil rebels
were killed Tuesday in separate clashes in the Northern Province
of Sri Lanka, a military spokesman here said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman said government troops conducted a limited
operation with the objective of destroying identified terrorist
positions Tuesday morning in general area Paranthan.
</P>
<P>
During the confrontation, two armor tanks were slightly damaged
due to rebel mortar fire. According to reports of the troops, at
least 11 Tamil rebels were killed and more than 30 others were
seriously injured in this operation, the spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
On the same day in east of Kandavalai, the spokesman said
troops observed a group of rebels and a double cab moving from
north to south and directed artillery fire. The troops confirmed
that four rebels were killed and the double cab was destroyed by
artillery fire.
</P>
<P>
Government troops operating ahead of defenses confronted a
group of Tamil rebels, killing five rebel cadres around 5:00 p.m.
Tuesday in general area Oddusuddan, said the spokesman, adding
that Tuesday afternoon in south of Pallamadu, troops operating
ahead of defenses killed one rebel.
</P>
<P>
The Tamil rebels have been fighting a war against the
government for a separate Tamil state in the north and south of
the island country since 1983. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
