<DOCNO> XIE19990915.0218 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Wade Upsets Jackson at Tokyo Athletics Meeting </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, September 15 (Xinhua) -- Larry Wade rounded up an injury-
plagued season on a high note here Wednesday as he stole spotlight
from the heavily favored world champion Colin Jackson from Britain
to claim victory in the men's 110 meters hurdles at the season-
ending Tokyo athletics international meeting.
</P>
<P>
The 24-year-old American Wade clocked a winning time of 13.50
seconds, upsetting world record holder Jackson, who came home in
13.55 seconds. Japan's Satoru Tanigawa was third in 13.95 and
Asian Games champion Chen Yanhao of China fourth in 14.01.
</P>
<P>
Wade missed out on a place in the world championships as he
suffered cramp in the national trials and was forced to withdraw
from the high-profile event.
</P>
<P>
Driss Maazouzi of France won the men's 1,500m in three minutes
46.54 seconds to beat Japan's Kazuyoshi Tokumoto and Alistair
Stevenson of Australia.
</P>
<P>
Japan's Kazuhiko Yamazaki defeated American Joey Woody to win
the 400m hurdles in 48.98.
</P>
<P>
Takahisa Yoshida of Japan cleared 2.24 meters to win the men's
high jump title. Lee Jin-Taek of South Korea, sixth in the world
championships in Seville, matched that height but had to settle
for second place for taking more attempts.
</P>
<P>
Japan-based Kenyan James Wainaina clocked 13:56.88 to lead a 1-
2 Kenyan sweep with Kagika Laban in the men's 5,000m.
</P>
<P>
American Kelly Suttle jumped 4.20 meters for an easy win in the
women's pole vault after world record holder Emmer George of
Australia withdrew. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
