</P>
<P>
-- Algerians will vote massively on Thursday on the "civil
concord" law proposed by the government to end seven years of
violence. The law will provide total or partial amnesty for all
the Islamists who have not committed crimes of blood and rape.
</P>
<P>
-- Six months after the en masse resignation of the former
European Commission on March 15, the European Parliament is ready
Thursday to endorse the new executive of the European Union. Most
of the Euro-deputies are expected to vote for the new team of
Ramano Prodi.
</P>
<P>
Le Monde:
</P>
<P>
-- The British are talking about the most extensive documents
ever revealed from the archives of the KGB on the activities of
penetration in Western Europe during the Cold War. A book has been
published in London and will be published in Paris making a
synthesis of the documents brought to the West by a former KGB
agent, Vassili Mitrokhin, who defected in 1992. According to the
996-page book, the KGB had widely recruited French journalists and
members of the entourage of President Francois Mitterrand.
</P>
