<HEADLINE> Zimbabwean Attorney-General to Appeal Against </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, September 15 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwean Attorney-General's
Office intends to appeal to the Supreme Court against the
effective six-month jail term imposed on the three Americans
which it said had trivialized the seriousness of the crime.
</P>
<P>
The daily Herald reported on Wednesday that the three Americans
were arrested on March 7 this year at the Harare International
Airport and convicted for illegal possession of weapons and
attempting to take them on board an aircraft.
</P>
<P>
The Attorney-General Patrick Chinamasa said in a statement on
Tuesday the sentence handed down by High Court judge Justice Adam
on Monday " induces a sense of shock and outrage in the minds of
all right-thinking people".
</P>
<P>
He said the three Americans -- Garry Blanchard, Joseph
Pettijohn and John Dixon -- were convicted of offences which were
treated as serious by all civilized countries worldwide, including
the United States, which was in the forefront of fighting
terrorism and gun running.
</P>
<P>
"By imposing sentences which do not match the seriousness of
the offences, Judge Adam has in effect trivialized crimes of
unlawful possession of arms and has seriously erred in doing so,"
he said.
</P>
<P>
He said, "Mere unlawful transiting of firearms through the
territory of Zimbabwe is in itself a serious and gross violation
of the sovereign and security interests of Zimbabwe." 
</P>
</TEXT>
