<DOCNO> XIE19990915.0228 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-15 09:40 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israel Discovers Y2K Bug Solution </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, September 15 (Xinhua) -- An Israeli computer
amateur has found a solution to the Year 2000 computer problem
(Y2K) that is applicable to all databases, a local newspaper
reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The Sapir 2000 program, developed by Ben-Etzion Yaron, head of
Manpower and Payroll Department in Hebrew University, compresses
four digits for the years in the 21st century into two symbols by
using special algorithms, so the code for any year in the 21st
century will not be the same as the year 100 years ago.
</P>
<P>
The program makes it possible to analyze computer programs
written in COBOL, the programmers of which used two digits for
years in the 20th century instead of four needed to differentiate
between them and those in the 21st century because of the
limitation of space.
</P>
<P>
The programmers thought the programs, which were written in
the 1970s and 80s, would be abandoned by the end of the century.
</P>
<P>
Chaos will be expected worldwide if the bug is not fixed by
next January. So far, the world has invested billions of dollars
to solve the problem.
</P>
<P>
Yaron's invention can even identify errors in other programs
that have been already revamped to get rid of the Y2K bug and make
corrections. The Y2K bugs it can not cope with are those in
computer components embedded in equipment, for instance, medical
devices, the Jerusalem Post said.
</P>
<P>
It is estimated that the time needed by Sapir 2000 to fix the
Y2K bug is 15 percent to 20 percent of the time other solutions
need, the paper said.
</P>
<P>
Yaron has applied for patents for his new program in the United
States. The product will be initially marketed and distributed in
Israel and, if all goes well, will be sold worldwide, mainly via
the Internet. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990915.0229 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Try On-line Pagers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 15 (Xinhua)-- Chinese people now can read e-
mail wherever they are and whenever they like with their pagers
rather than with expensive palmtop computers.
</P>
<P>
 With a technique called "on-line pager," paging stations can
transform e-mail into wireless signals that can be received by
pagers, and users can enjoy this service by applying to paging
stations for e-mail boxes.
</P>
<P>
 On-line pagers, originally developed in the United States,
were introduced to China by Internet service providers and paging
stations a few years ago.
</P>
<P>
 Cyber Netology Corp., a Chinese Internet service provider in
Beijing, launched a two-way grovel e-mail paging system (ESP)
based on this technique and fit for Chinese paging stations.
</P>
<P>
 On-line paging also will meet the needs of overseas Chinese
and their folks at home, said Yan Baomin, executive vice president
of Cyber Netology Corp.
</P>
<P>
 "Chinese students abroad, for example, are used to e-mail,
however, their parents at home may not have the access to Internet,
" he added. "On-line pagers offer Chinese an easier way to use the
Internet, since pagers are much more popular here."
</P>
<P>
 On-line paging brings a new opportunity for the development
of Chinese paging stations, which have been competing with mobile
telephone services, said Yan.
</P>
<P>
 Statistics show that the country has 1,763 paging stations
now, with pager users totaling 72.68 million.
</P>
<P>
 According to Yan, 50 paging stations in 21 Chinese cities
including Beijing, Shanghai, Xi'an, and Harbin, offer on-line
paging service, and China Unicom, the country's telecommunications
giant, also adopted ESP in July. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
