<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, September 15 (Xinhua) -- Ethiopian government
representatives are due to meet officials of the International
Monetary Fund (IMF) in Washington on September 23 to discuss
granting credit to Ethiopia, the Reporter newspaper said
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The report quoted experts as saying that Ethiopia has met IMF's
 requirements on economic reform, adding if the IMF criterion is
only economical, the IMF is expected to release the promised aid
package.
</P>
<P>
However, the unidentified experts said if the IMF may come up
with a political criterion as it did before under a pressure from
the United States, it may not grant Ethiopia the loan.
</P>
<P>
A press release by the IMF board of directors on August 17 said
that Ethiopia has shown a seven percent economic growth so far
this year despite the short of rainfall, a decline in the price of
coffee on international markets and the country's conflict with
Eritrea.
</P>
<P>
Ethiopia is the third largest coffee producer in Africa. It has
been at war with Eritrea over border dispute since May last year.
</P>
