<HEADLINE> Chinese Police Round Up Over 100,000 Escaped Criminal Suspects </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 15 (Xinhua) -- The Ministry of Public
Security announced here today that police departments across in
the country have rounded up over 100,000 escaped criminal suspects
in the latest nationwide campaign which began on July 1.
</P>
<P>
An official with the ministry said they include over 10,000
people who surrendered to police under great pressure.
</P>
<P>
He said the campaign has been playing a positive role in
ensuring social stability and safety during celebrations for the
upcoming 50th anniversary of the People's Republic and the return
of Macao.
</P>
<P>
To ensure a smooth campaign, the ministry has established an
information network to provide detailed information about suspects,
directly to police units at various levels.
</P>
<P>
More than 80,000 criminal suspects now captured were in the
nationwide fugitive network's files, the official said.
</P>
<P>
He added that the ministry offers rewards to policemen
capturing escapees on the ministry's most-wanted list, as well as
to citizens who provide tips or help round up the escapees during
the campaign.
</P>
<P>
The public security bureau of Shenzhen in south China awarded
10,000 yuan on April 18 to two ordinary citizens who helped
capture a fugitive homicide suspect.
</P>
<P>
"This was the first time a public security bureau gave such a
large reward to citizens who voluntarily helped catch a major
fugitive since the beginning of the ongoing nationwide campaign
against fugitives," the officer stressed.  
</P>
</TEXT>
