<HEADLINE> ASEAN Transport Ministers Meet in Vietnam </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANOI, September 15 (Xinhua) -- The fifth ASEAN transport
ministers (ATM) meeting opened here Wednesday, discussing further
development plans for transport cooperation among ASEAN member
countries.
</P>
<P>
The transport ministers and senior officials from all 10 ASEAN
countries and the ASEAN Secretariat are taking part in the two-day
meeting, which is the first of its kind hosted by Vietnam.
</P>
<P>
During Wednesday's meeting, the ASEAN ministers adopted the
ASEAN Transport Cooperation Framework Plan and the ASEAN Plan of
Action in Transport for the 1999-2004 period, as the cooperation
vehicle to hasten the implementation of the transport action
agenda of the Hanoi Plan of Action and the ASEAN Vision 2020.
</P>
<P>
The ministers in the afternoon signed the ASEAN Ministerial
Understanding on the Development of the ASEAN Highway Network
Project which, a Joint Press Statement of the Meeting said, will
pave the way for the stage or phased development of priority road
projects and provide the necessary infrastructural backbone for
increased opportunities in intra-regional trade, investment and
tourism in the ASEAN region.
</P>
<P>
The ASEAN transport ministers also signed two implementing
protocols. They are the Protocol on Types and Quantity of Road
Vehicles and the Protocol on Technical Requirement of Vehicles.
</P>
<P>
In consonance with the ASEAN leaders' directive to
operationalize the Framework Agreement by the year 2000, The
ministers agreed to set the timetable to have the ASEAN Framework
Agreement on the Facilitation of Goods in Transit operationalized
by December 31, 2000.
</P>
<P>
The meeting decided that the Sixth ASEAN Transport Ministers
Meeting will be held in Brunei Darussalam in September 2000.
</P>
<P>
The Fifth ASEAN Transport Ministers Meeting is scheduled to be
closed on Thursday, preceded by the Eighth ASEAN Senior Transport
Officials Meeting held here on September 13-14.
</P>
<P>
ASEAN groups Brunei, Cambodia, Indonesia, Laos, Malaysia,
Myanmar, the Philippines, Singapore, Thailand and Vietnam.
</P>
</TEXT>
