<HEADLINE> Model of Japanese Tank Found in NE China City </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHENYANG, September 15 (Xinhua) -- A museum in the city of
Fushun in Liaoning Province, northeast China, announced today that
it has discovered a model of a Japanese tank built in 1932, when
Japan occupied northeast China.
</P>
<P>
The model tank, 21.2 cm long, 9.5 cm wide, and 10.9 cm high, is
believed to have been a souvenir to mark the first anniversary of
the "Sept. 18 Incident," the beginning of a four-month-long
aggressive action by Japanese troops to occupy the entire
northeast of China.
</P>
<P>
Chinese characters carved on the model indicate that it was
made to mark the incident by the "South Manchu Railway Company"
run by the Japanese aggressors. 
</P>
</TEXT>
