<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Interview: Living "One Country, Two Systems" Great Experience (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, September 15 (Xinhua) -- "My family always consider
Hong Kong our home, and we have lived here very comfortably," said
Frank Martin, president of the American Chamber of Commerce (
AmCham) in Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
Martin is one of the 40,000 or so Americans with a long-
established and prominent presence in Hong Kong, who make Hong
Kong their "home away from home".
</P>
<P>
From an American's perspective, Hong Kong's return to the
mainland has been very positive, and politically, little change
has occurred so far in Hong Kong, he said.
</P>
<P>
"Living 'One Country, Two Systems' is really great experience,"
Martin told Xinhua in an exclusive interview just two weeks before
October 1, China's National Day, when a variety of activities will
be held throughout the country to celebrate the 50th anniversary
of the founding of New China.
</P>
<P>
"I have already received dozens of invitations to different
kinds of receptions, meetings and gatherings in Hong Kong," Martin
said.
</P>
<P>
"To me, the most impressive events that have taken place in the
country in the past half century were Nixon's visit to China in
early 1970s and Deng Xiaoping's decision to establish the open-up
policy in 1978," Martin said.
</P>
<P>
"It was these and the subsequent events that led to closer Sino-
U.S. relations and resulted in more foreign investment in China
and more trade with China, which in turn promoted a spectacular
economic growth and improved the standard of living for millions
of people," he said.
</P>
<P>
"During my first visit to China in 1980, I, as a guest of the
Bank of China, toured several places. I was amused that I could
not use my normal passport," he recalled.
</P>
<P>
"But dramatic changes have occurred in China since then," he
said, adding that China's fast economic growth has established the
country as an important economic force in the world.
</P>
<P>
Martin travels between Hong Kong and China's mainland at least
six times each year. "Every time I could find something new to me,
" he said.
</P>
<P>
In China, he met many Chinese leaders, including Premier Zhu
Rongji and Vice-Premier Li Lanqing, and many others.
</P>
<P>
He described the Chinese leaders as "extraordinarily capable".
"They have done the most difficult job in the world," he said. He
expressed the belief that the Chinese leaders are able to lead the
Chinese people to overcome any difficulties and obstacles in the
way in the future and to lead an even stronger country into the
new millennium.
</P>
<P>
"China so far remains an attractive location for foreign
investment, especially for the investment from the United States,"
he said, mentioning that 75 percent of AmCham member companies now
have operations in China which is about 20 percent more than five
years ago.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990915.0240 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Interview: Living "One Country, Two Systems" Great Experience (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Among the member companies that do not have a presence in China,
43 percent intend to make an investment in the market over the
next three years and 78 percent of the companies that already have
operations in China claim they will increase their investment in
the next three years, he explained.
</P>
<P>
"So I am very anxious about the resumption of negotiations over
the WTO," Martin said. "I believe that the resumption of Sino-U.S.
talks on China's entry to the WTO will be good both to China and
to the United States. It is not just an issue about imports and
exports, but also about the foreign investment."
</P>
<P>
He expressed his strong support for China's entry into the
World Trade Organization. "To facilitate this process, Congress
should pass legislation that will enable the United States to
extend permanent normal trade relations status once China
negotiates a commercially acceptable accession protocol," he
stated.
</P>
<P>
Martin, 58, was appointed president of the AmCham in Hong Kong
in December 1990. He and his wife Noriko have been residents in
Hong Kong since 1976.
</P>
<P>
Martin is very proud of his two children who received 13 years'
education in Hong Kong, from kindergarten to high school. Now, the
Martins are permanent residents of the Hong Kong Special
Administrative Region.
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong is so attractive to the outside world because it is
not only an international business and finance hub, but also a
multiple-lingual and multiple-cultural metropolis, he said.
</P>
<P>
Mentioning the economic crisis, Martin said it had great
impacts on the economy and foreign investment in Hong Kong and
China's mainland. It takes time for the economies of Hong Kong,
China's mainland and the rest of Asia to recover or to improve, he
added.
</P>
<P>
"I don't think it will rebound, but it is a very gradual
process," he explained. However, a recent survey conducted among
members of the AmCham shows that everyone is satisfied with the
handover since it happened.
</P>
<P>
He is an active participant in local community service and has
served on board of numerous non-profit organization, including
Hong Kong International School Board of Management and Hong Kong
Inland Revenue Review Board.
</P>
<P>
Martin said more than 190 U.S. companies have regional
headquarters in Hong Kong, while 285 others have regional offices.
That represents about 20 percent of all international companies
with a regional office or headquarters in Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
The AmCham in Hong Kong is the biggest outside of America and
represents the business interests of more than 1,000 companies and
2,600 members.
</P>
<P>
"American businesses are confident in the long-term prospects
of Hong Kong and have decided to continue their investment here,"
he said. 
</P>
