<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Becomes World's Building Materials Giant </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 15 (Xinhua) -- China has become one of the
world's largest building materials producers after 50 years of
development, with annual outputs of cement, sheet glass, ceramic
tiles, and sanitary wares ranking first in the world.
</P>
<P>
According to the State Administration of Buildings Material
Industry, China produced 530 million tons of cement in 1998, and
has been the world's largest cement producer for 13 years running.
The country produced only 660,000 tons in 1949 when New China was
founded, ranking 26th in the world at that time.
</P>
<P>
The total output value of China's building materials sector
reached 347 billion yuan in 1998, ranking fifth among the country'
s various industrial sectors.
</P>
<P>
China's building materials sector registered an average annual
growth rate of 13.1 percent between 1952 and 1997, 1.5 percentage
points higher than that of the nation's industrial sector.
</P>
<P>
There now are 61,000 building materials enterprises in China,
with total assets topping 533.1 billion yuan.
</P>
<P>
With the founding of New China, especially after the country
adopted the reform and opening-up policy, the building materials
sector maintained a favorable growth momentum.
</P>
<P>
China's building materials enterprises were mostly publicly or
collectively owned before 1978, and since then Sino-foreign joint
ventures, solely foreign-funded ventures and private enterprises
have developed rapidly. Some of them are even engaged in trans-
regional, trans-regional and inter-trade operations.
</P>
<P>
To date the 4,500-strong foreign-funded building materials
enterprises in the country have used a total foreign investment of
seven billion U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
China's building materials industry has developed ties more
than 130 countries and regions in the fields of trade, labor
service, contracted construction projects, and technology services.
</P>
<P>
Official statistics show that the country's import and export
value of building materials totaled 2.04 billion U.S. dollars in
the first half of this year, including 1.2 billion U.S. dollars of
exports. The total foreign trade value of the industry grew at an
average annual rate of 18 percent between 1979 and 1997.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
