<HEADLINE> S. African Men Held in Angola Released </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, September 15 (Xinhua) -- Hugs, kisses and tears
marked the return to South Africa of four men who were detained in
an Angolan jail for 20 months, The Star newspaper reported
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Family and friends of the four, who gathered at Lanseria
Airport in Johannesburg, could not contain their joy when they saw
the men emerging from the private plane that brought them back
from Angola late Tuesday night, said the paper.
</P>
<P>
Marnix van der Eecken, 48, Gert Allen, 49, Marthines Steyn, 26,
and Rudie Swanepoel, 20, were detained in Angola on January 20
last year, after their supply flight carrying building materials
to northern Angola was forced to land by the Angolan Air Force.
</P>
<P>
The four were detained for five months after their arrest under
a blanket provision of the State Security Act, namely that they
had endangered the security of the Angolan State by entering the
country without a visa.
</P>
<P>
At some stage they were accused of bringing arms into Angola,
probably for the benefit of rebel National union for Total
Independence of Angola.
</P>
<P>
After being found guilty, Van der Eecken and Steyn were each
sentenced to eight years' imprisonment while Allen and Swanepoel
were each sentenced to two years' imprisonment.
</P>
<P>
The men were acquitted on September 3 after an appeal and were
accommodated locally before returning home on Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
The men, all dressed casually and looking neat, said they had
been well looked after in recent weeks -- a far cry to the early
days of their detention. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
