<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Rain Falls in China Rally After Shakedown </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HUAIROU, Beijing, September 15 (Xinhua) -- Drivers may find the
China Rally rougher than they thought as a mild rain fell on the
course following the shakedown in the Wednesday's morning in the
northeast county in Beijing.
</P>
<P>
The China Rally, the 11th stage of the World Rallying
Championships, will set off on Friday morning, with just less than
40 hours left for the organisers to examine the road and conduct
repair if necessary.
</P>
<P>
All the top racers in the rally claimed a rough road condition
in the three-day race during the morning's shakedown.
</P>
<P>
"The stage is very rough," said Mitsubishi's Tommi Makinen,
leader of the drivers competition. "And the road is very narrow."
</P>
<P>
"The road is so rough that we can find stones everywhere," said
Toyota's racer Didier Auriol, who is trailing Makinen by 10 points
at second on the drivers standings. "It's very easy to pull away
on every corner."
</P>
<P>
"Some stages are quiet nice, but some are rough and twisty. It'
s very difficult to do with the car," Auriol added.
</P>
<P>
Approximate 250-meter road in the first-day leg had been
damaged by flooding about a week before, and some repair was
conducted to make the road passable. 
</P>
</TEXT>
