<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nigeria Donates Rice, Medicines to S. Leone </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, September 15 (Xinhua) -- The Nigerian government has
donated 5, 000 bags of rice and some consignment of medicines to
former combatants of the rebel Revolutionary United Front (RUF)
and the Armed Forces Revolutionary Council (AFRC) in Sierra Leone.
</P>
<P>
Nigeria's Acting High Commissioner in Sierra leone Tony
Chikezie announced the donation during a coordinating meeting on
the take-off of the disarmament exercise under the Lome peace
agreement signed in July, according to a Nigerian Tribune report
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The paper quoted the envoy as saying that the consignment is
expected to arrive in Freetown, capital of Sierra Leone, this
week, adding that the gesture is a further demonstration of
Nigeria's sincere interest in the peace process in Sierra Leone.
</P>
<P>
Chikezie expressed the hope that the items would assist the
rank and file of the disarming combatants as they demonstrated
their commitments to the peace process in the west African
country.
</P>
<P>
The RUF/AFRC delegation leader S.Y. Rogers was quoted as saying
that his movement no longer considered the West African
peace-keeping force of ECOMOG as an antagonistic force, rather it
accepted its roles in providing security to ensure the success of
the peace process.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the Nigerian government has halted the withdrawal of
 its troops from strife-torn Sierra leone to ensure ECOMOG troops
to initiate the process of disarmament, demobilization and
reintegration of rebel soldiers in line with the Lome peace
agreement.
</P>
<P>
A statement from ECOMOG headquarters in Sierra Leone said that
the AFRC loyalists had promised to ensure a halt to all hostage
taking or ceasefire violation along the highways in Freetown.
</P>
<P>
Troops loyal to the AFRC led by Major Johnny Paul Koromah had
in July posed an obstacle on the peace process by seizing ECOMOG
soldiers, United Nations staff and aid workers. 
</P>
</TEXT>
