<HEADLINE> Young Judokas Stand up in Chinese City Games </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YAN'AN, SHAANXI, China, Setpember 15 (Xinhua) -- The judo
competitions in the fourth Chinese City Games were concluded here
on Wednesday with a promosing prospect of a string of young
athletes.
</P>
<P>
National champion Li Shufang was beaten by budding star Yang
Shujun in the women's 63kg class with clear upperhands, while 15-
year-old Wang Haixia also dethroned another national champion Qing
Dongya in the women's 70kg category.
</P>
<P>
"Those are the good players with great potentials, produced in
the City Games, which was being conceived as the cradle for the
youngesters under the age of 20," said assistant judge Xia
Shuangxi.
</P>
<P>
"The men players have also impressed me the most with their
active participation as the majority of the winners triumphed in
ippon," said Xia.
</P>
<P>
"The players' active attitude was mainly due to the fact that
the Chinese Judo Association issued new rules to punish those
passive participants by reducing the time period from 20 seconds
to five seconds," explained the official.
</P>
<P>
Besides, the traditional judo powers were prevented from
dominating in the four-day national competitions as Shenyang of
Liaoning province only claimed four out of the 16 gold medals at
stake, and Inner Mongolia failed to reap a single gold.
</P>
<P>
"However, our players still need to improve their basic
techniques, with the ones on the floor in particular, as most of
them resorted to quick victories, seldom the case in the world
arena," said the assistant judge.
</P>
<P>
Furthermore, against the full-fledged development of the
smaller classes, "those heavy players in both the men's and women'
s competitions are clearly lack of skills and strength",
requesting further researches from the concerned authorities, said
the official. 
</P>
</TEXT>
