<HEADLINE> Japan to Provide Anti-flood Aid to Philippines </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, September 15 (Xinhua) -- Philippine President Joseph
Estrada said Wednesday that the Japanese government has approved
assistance for a 4-billion-peso (100-million-U.S.-dollar) dike
project that will protect Metro Manila from floods.
</P>
<P>
The president said in a radio program that Japanese Prime
Minister Keizo Obuchi informed him of the approval of the Japanese
aid during their meeting in the 7th Asia-Pacific Economic
Cooperation leaders' informal summit in New Zealand.
</P>
<P>
Estrada said he received reports on the plight of thousands of
Metro Manila residents, particularly students and workers, caused
by flooding last Friday and Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The president also said he does not intend to replace Gregorio
Vigilar as the public works secretary, who had been severely
criticized in the wake of the floods that submerged the low-lying
areas of Metro Manila and the nearby provinces.
</P>
<P>
"Secretary Vigilar has performed well," he said. "The
inundation was not due to his fault."
</P>
<P>
The Metro Manila inundation, in the president's view, was
caused mainly by clogging of the drainage system due to the
implementation of various infrastructure projects.
</P>
<P>
Estrada said his administration, which is now in its second
year, has been tackling the decades-old problem of flooding in
Metro Manila.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, presidential spokesman Jerry Barican said Estrada
had instructed Secretary Vigilar to coordinate with the Metro
Manila Development Authority to make sure that flooding in the
metropolis is under control. 
</P>
</TEXT>
