<HEADLINE> Nigeria Plans on Pay Rise for Public Servants </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, September 15 (Xinhua) -- The Nigerian Government is to
consider raising wages for the public servants as a step towards
tackling corruption,

the Vanguard, a major Nigerian newspaper reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
President Olusegun Obasanjo made the government's intention in
a message sent through his aid Tuesday to the opening of a seminar
on the Anti-Corruption Bill organized by the Nigeria Labor
Congress (NLC) in Lagos.
</P>
<P>
Obasanjo said in the message that "corruption has become a
necessity to certain categories of workers in our country who
cannot be expected to survive and provide the basic necessities of
life for their dependants on the wages and salaries which they are
currently paid".
</P>
<P>
The president also identified corruption as one of the factors
hindering the much-desired foreign investment in Nigeria.
</P>
<P>
"Without such investment, we will find it difficult to reduce
significantly the present level of unemployment in our country. It
is therefore in the collective interest of our work force that no
effort be spared in the war against corruption," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
