<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Exhibition on Chinese History Staged in Hong Kong </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, September 15 (Xinhua) -- A large scale exhibition
featuring Chinese people's endeavors for national strength and
prosperity in the past century was staged in Hong Kong Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Entitled "Rise of Modern China: A Century of Self-Determination,
" the nine-section exhibition displays more than 200 historical
photographs, most of which have never been shown in Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
It also highlights 180 significant historical objects,
including the microscopic lens used by Dr. Sun Yat-sen, forerunner
of Chinese revolution, when he was a medical student, the banner
used by the Beijing University students during the May 4th
Movement in 1919, and the loudspeaker used by the late Chinese
leader Mao Zedong to proclaim the founding of the People's
Republic of China at Tian'anmen.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the opening ceremony, Ronald Leung Ding-bong,
chairman of the Provisional Urban Council (PUC), said the Council
pursued an active program of promoting Chinese history and culture.
</P>
<P>
"The exhibition has been timed to tie in with the 50th
anniversary of the founding of the People's Republic of China," he
said. "Now that Hong Kong has returned to our motherland for over
two years, it is important that the people of Hong Kong, the
younger generation in particular, should acquire better knowledge
and understanding of the transformation that China had undergone
in the last hundred years."
</P>
<P>
Leung said: "Hong Kong played a part in many of the events
which took place in China in the last hundred years."
</P>
<P>
"All the historical events demonstrate that Hong Kong is an
inalienable part of China's historical development. To understand
Hong Kong we must place it in the context of Chinese history," he
added.
</P>
<P>
Jointly presented by the Provisional Urban Council and the
National Museum of Modern Chinese History, the exhibition will run
through November 21 at the Special Exhibition Gallery of the Hong
Kong Museum of History.
</P>
<P>
Officiating at the opening ceremony were Tung Chee Hwa, chief
executive of the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region (HKSAR);
Jiang Enzhu, director of Xinhua News Agency Hong Kong Branch; Sun
Jiazheng, minister of culture of the People's Republic of China;
and Ma Yuzhen, commissioner of the Ministry of Foreign Affairs of
the People's Republic of China in the HKSAR. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
