<HEADLINE> Ugandan Command to Review  Kisangani Clashes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
KAMPALA, September 15 (Xinhua) --The High Command of Uganda
People's Defense Forces (UPDF) will meet on Wednesday to review
the report of investigation into the fierce clashes between the
troops of Uganda and Rwanda in Kisangani, the third largest city
in the Democratic Republic of the Congo (DRC).
</P>
<P>
The report presented at the weekend by Army Commander Jeje
Odongo was initially dismissed as shallow and compromised, the New
Vision newspaper said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
President Yoweri Museveni told reporters Tuesday evening that
the report did not cover certain areas it was supposed to cover.
</P>
<P>
The report attributed the clashes to the lack of a joint
military and civilian leadership, and respective support of rival
factions of the main rebel group by the two countries. It added
both sides were preparing for an attack, however, the UPDF High
Command denied that the Ugandan troops ever prepared for an
attack.
</P>
<P>
A break-down in communication between the Ugandan and Rwandan
troops was blamed for the start of the clashes, said the report,
which also blamed the two sides for breaking the loose ceasefire
agreement signed on August 15.
</P>
<P>
The four-day clashes,from August 14-17, claimed 38 Ugandan
soldiers. Some sources put the casualty at hundreds. 
</P>
</TEXT>
