<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Angola Sells Foreign Currency to Save Exchange </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUANDA, September 15 (Xinhua) -- Angolan National Bank (BKA)
has undertaken "an important intervention" in the exchange market
to help its fast-devaluating national currency readjusted kwanza.
</P>
<P>
This is the first intervention in the exchange market since
June 3 when the country started the system of floating rate,
official newspaper Jornal de Angola reported here Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The paper quoted BNA as saying that the national bank sold
Tuesday a massive volume of foreign currency with an aim to save
the poor exchange rate of readjusted kwanza.
</P>
<P>
Since the start of the floating rate in June, the readjusted
kwanza has devaluated by a large margin, with 7.2 million
readjusted kwanzas equivalent to one U.S. dollar on Wednesday,
worth only one tenth of its value on June 2 when it was officially
priced at 1:710,000 in exchange for U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
The national currency devaluated by 24% in two days since
Monday when the exchange rate in readjusted kwanza against U.S.
dollar was 1:5,800,000 (one dollar for 5,800,000 readjusted
kwanzas).
</P>
<P>
"BNA put a big part of the financial means, which are necessary
for covering the demand for foreign currency in the market, at the
disposal of commercial banks," the report said.
</P>
<P>
The paper also quoted BNA as saying that the bank will take
other measures to "maintain the control over the evolution of the
exchange rate".
</P>
<P>
The Angolan government gave up on June 3 the fixed rate of
exchange, in a bid to curb inflation and strike the illegal
currency exchange market. But the impasse in the battle-field and
the deteriorating economic situation prevented the policy from
working, according to the paper.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
