<HEADLINE> Organizers of Moscow Blasts Hide in Chechnya: PM </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, September 15 (Xinhua) -- Prime Minister Vladimir Putin
said here Wednesday that the organizers of the explosions of
residential buildings in Moscow that killed more than 200 people
were hiding in Chechnya, a breakaway Russian republic.
</P>
<P>
"It's absolutely clear that the terrorists are hiding in the
Chechen territory and are being supported by extremist forces in
Chechnya," Putin told journalists after meeting with visiting
Irish Prime Minister Bertie Ahern.
</P>
<P>
"We intend to ask the republic's leadership to hand over the
criminals," he said.
</P>
<P>
"Several people who prepared the terrorist acts were detained
and their role is being determined," he said. "A search was
announced for a number of individuals whom we consider contractors,
" he said.
</P>
<P>
Ahern arrived here Tuesday on a three-day official visit. The
two countries signed two agreements on their cooperation in
fighting crime and drug trafficking Wednesday, the Itar-Tass news
agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Putin said law enforcement bodies and police located a storage
of several tons of explosives, which might have been used in
future terrorist attacks.
</P>
<P>
Sweep checks of markets and premises continue in Moscow, and
control over non-residents of the city was stepped up, the
Interfax news agency quoted Putin as saying.
</P>
<P>
In addition, "a series of prevention measures unnoticeable for
the general public are being implemented," he said.
</P>
<P>
Moscow was rocked by three explosions since August 31, when a
bomb went off in an underground shopping mall near the Kremlin,
killing one person and injuring dozens of others.
</P>
<P>
The second explosion happened just seconds to midnight
Wednesday, ripping apart a nine-storey apartment building in
southeast Moscow. Ninety-four people were killed in that blast.
</P>
<P>
The latest blast occurred Monday morning, killing 118 residents
in an eight-storey apartment building. Thirteen of the victims
were children and 13 fragments of human are yet to be identified.
</P>
<P>
In Daghestan, a car bomb exploded in front of a five-storey
military housing complex on September 4, killing 64 people.
</P>
<P>
On Wednesday afternoon, a man telephoned the Itar-Tass news
agency, saying that a so-called Daghestan Liberation Army staged
the blasts in retaliation against Russian assaults on Islamic
rebels in Daghestan and Chechnya. 
</P>
</TEXT>
