<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> "Underground Treasure House" Found in Northwest China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
XI'AN, September 15 (Xinhua) -- Chinese archeologists have
found a large "underground treasure house" some 20 kilometers
north of the ancient city of Xi'an, capital of northwest China's
Shaanxi Province.
</P>
<P>
Excavation efforts in the past decade showed that the large
underground treasure house is actually the cemetery of Liu Qi, the
fourth emperor of the Western Han Dynasty (206 B.C.-24), which has
four gates.
</P>
<P>
In 1990 when a highway leading to the Xianyang International
Airport was being built, a group of archeologists accidentally
found hundreds of colored pottery figurines in the southern part
of the Liu Qi cemetery.
</P>
<P>
Continued excavation efforts led to the discovery of 90 burying
pits within the emperor's cemetery,
</P>
<P>
In the eastern side of the cemetery are 28 burying pits
containing colored terra-cotta infantrymen, cavalrymen, chariots,
horses, weapons, sheep, dogs pigs, and articles for daily use.
</P>
<P>
The 21 pits in both northern and western sides of the cemetery
contain large numbers of various weapons, chariots and daily
necessities. Excavations will continue to determine what is in the
20 pits in the southern side of the cemetery.
</P>
<P>
Among the more than 1,000 50-60-cm high beautifully-shaped
pottery figurines unearthed from these pits are the earliest
valiant and brave cavalry women found in China, according to
archeologists.
</P>
<P>
To date, more than 10,000 various attendant tombs have been
found in a 3.5-square-kilometer attendant cemetery at the eastern
part of the Liu Qi cemetery, the largest that has been found among
the tombs of the emperors of the Western Han Dynasty, said a
Chinese archeologist.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990915.0295 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-15 </DATE_TIME>
