<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Situation Worsens in Southern Somalia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOGADISHU, September 15 (Xinhua) -- The stability in southern
Somalia is further worsening as the armed confrontations between
the warring sides supporting Hussein Mohamed Aidid and those of
the Ethiopian backed factions are escalating and drawing close to
the capital.
</P>
<P>
At least five people were killed and more than eight others
wounded in the fighting between the militiamen of the Rahanwein
Resistance Army (RRA) accompanied by the Digil Salvation Army
(DSA) on one side and Aidid's forces on the other in Aw-Koreh
village, about 5 Kilometers southwest of the lucrative airport of
Ballidogleh Tuesday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
According to the VHF radios in the area, more than seven battle
wagons and nearly 100 heavily armed infantry militiamen from
Aidid's side were involved in the clashes, while the RRA and DSA
fighters posed stiff resistance against the attack led by the
commander of Ballidogleh airport, Abdukarim Farabadan.
</P>
<P>
The reason for the attack is not stated officially. However,
according to independent sources, the militiamen of Aidid
stationed at Ballidogleh airport, 90 kilometers south of the
capital, have launched the attack. The sources said the attack was
prompted after the RRA and DSA fighters started establishing a new
strong militia base at Aw-Koreh village.
</P>
<P>
The new base is seen as a serious threat to the operations of
the only tarmac airport run by Hussein Aidid's militiamen.
According to the sources, the attack has later on spread to
several other villages in the area.
</P>
<P>
Malaq Mohamed Jobanoh Yarow, one of the traditional leaders in
the area, fled to Mogadishu and met the journalists Wednesday,
accusing Aidid's forces led by the commander of Ballidogleh
airport for committing crimes of killing, torturing, abducting,
raping and displacing people in Lower Shabelle region.
</P>
<P>
Mohamed Ali Aden Qalinleh, spokesman for RRA, has claimed that
his men have killed 11 militiamen and wounded 15 others from the
side of Aidid during the confrontation and seized two battle
wagons.
</P>
<P>
This confrontation is said to be an extension of the war for
control of Qoryoley town between the two sides. Hussein Aidid's
militiamen still remain in control of Qoryoley town, and the two
sides are now in defensive positions outside the town.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, encouraging reports from the southern port town of
Kismaio, 500 kilometers south of the capital, indicate that sweep
operations in disarming the outlawed militiamen is continuing by
the Jubba Valley Alliance forces, who captured the town from
General Morgan early June this year. According to officials from
the alliance, the plan is meant to create a peaceful environment
for both the commercial and humanitarian activities throughout the
region.
</P>
<P>
However, at least four people were killed Tuesday in the center
of the town during a disarmament operation by the alliance forces.
Eyewitnesses in the town said the exchange of fire started when
about 150 policemen mandated for the disarmament operation tried
to collect weapons from a food store.  
</P>
</TEXT>
