<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Montreal School Board Under Language "Criminal" Charge </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, September 15 (Xinhua) -- An English-language school
board in Montreal has been under what the local television calls "
criminal" charge for failing to put bilingual messages on all its
answering machines.
</P>
<P>
The French-language agency in Quebec Tuesday ordered the board
of 65 schools to fix up machines for both languages, as required
under the Charter of the French Language adopted in 1977.
</P>
<P>
The agency said all recorded messages must be in both French
and English for anyone who wants to reach a teacher or a school
janitor, local media reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The French recording of a school does not have to be
predominant but it must be at least equivalent to the English one,
the agency was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
Language disputes occasionally occur between the French and
English speaking communities in Quebec, where 82 percent of its 7.
28 million population communicate in French.
</P>
<P>
Many schools of the board are still using the same single-
language recording since long before 1977.
</P>
<P>
Institutions serving an English-majority population are
required to have bilingual signs or internal communications under
the charter in Quebec.
</P>
<P>
Recently, a language policewoman was reportedly driven out of
an English speaking community while trying to photo a shop without
bilingual signs. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
