<HEADLINE> Chinese Defense Minister Reiterates China's Stand on South China Sea Issue </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 15 (Xinhua) -- Defense Minister Chi Haotian
said today that China insists on using consultations and friendly
dialogue based on equality to settle all issues that have been
left over from the past, including the South China Sea issue.
</P>
<P>
The remark came in a meeting with Eduardo Santos, the head of
the Philippine Navy.
</P>
<P>
Chi said that the South China Sea has been China's territory
from ancient times and that China has had indisputable sovereignty
over the Nansha Islands and their adjacent sea areas. The Chinese
government will hold dialogues with all countries concerned under
the principle of putting aside disputes and co-developing the area,
he added.
</P>
<P>
China and the Philippines are friendly neighbors, Chi said, and
the two devote themselves to friendship and cooperative ties and
that is in the interest of the people of both countries and helps
the peace and stability of the Asia-Pacific region.
</P>
<P>
He said that the meeting between Chinese President Jiang Zemin
and Philippine President Estrada before the informal meeting of
leaders of the Asia-Pacific Economic Cooperation (APEC) forum in
Auckland has given impetus to the growth of bilateral relations.
</P>
<P>
Santos agreed that the two countries should avoid conflicts and
maintain peace in the South China Sea area in favor of co-
development of the area and said that he is positive about the
growth of bilateral military relations. 
</P>
</TEXT>
