</P>
<P>
-- With Colombia's Government buckling under the pressure of
guerrilla attacks, a thriving drug trade and the worst economy in
decades, the Clinton Administration is putting together a major
new effort to prop up the country's democracy that will include
hundreds of millions of dollars in economic and military aid.
</P>
<P>
-- New York State is opening a new legal front in its fight
against pollution drifting from coal-burning power plants in
upwind states with an announcement on Tuesday that it intends to
sue 17 power plants to force them to clean up.
</P>
<P>
The Wall Street journal:
</P>
<P>
-- August retail sales in the United States rose 1.2% from July
and 9.1% from a year ago. A survey of small-business confidence
shows 16% of companies raised prices while 13% lowered them. At
the meantime, the current-account deficit for the April-June
period widened to 80.7 billion U.S. dollars, driving the broadest
gauge of the trade deficit to another record.
</P>
<P>
-- Russian police and soldiers tightened security in Moscow as
the death toll climbed to 118 from Monday's bomb attack on an
apartment building. Prime Minister Vladimir Putin accused Chechen
terrorists of responsibility for the explosion. 
