<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. House Passes Bill to Curb Finance Campaign </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 15 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. House of
Representatives passed a bill late Tuesday night to curb the
influence of money in political campaigns.
</P>
<P>
The bill, which was approved on a 252-177 vote, moves to the
Senate with an uncertain fate while Republican opponents are
threatening to obstruct it with a filibuster as they did last year.
</P>
<P>
The House passed the bill on a similar 252-179 vote last year.
</P>
<P>
The bill would ban soft money donations from corporations,
labor unions and individuals, which go to political parties rather
than individual candidates and are always used by parties to
bolster candidates.
</P>
<P>
Unlike hard money donations, soft money donations are unlimited
in size and are unregulated by the federal government.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the bill would impose limits on certain types of
political advertising.
</P>
<P>
Supporters said the bill is crucial to restore public
confidence in the political process while opponents complained it
restricts the constitutional rights of free speech.
</P>
<P>
The House Republican leadership backed efforts to derail the
measure or rework it, and concluded the bill could leave
Republican candidates vulnerable to attacks by the labor. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990915.0305 </DOCNO>
