<HEADLINE> Eritrea Rejects Ethiopia's Territorial Claims </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, September 15 (Xinhua) -- Eritrea rejected Wednesday
Ethiopia's demand for disputed territory by saying that its
demand "is a contradiction and violation" of the fundamental
tenets of the Framework Agreement set by the Organization of
African Unity (OAU).
</P>
<P>
Responding to a statement issued by Ethiopia Tuesday, Eritrean
 Presidential advisor Yemane Gebremeskel said "the implication is
clear that Ethiopia wants to legitimize Eritrean territory it has
incorporated in its illegal map, thus circumventing demarcation."
</P>
<P>
Ethiopian stated on Tuesday that the Ethiopian government could
 not agree to the peace package "unless it receives firm
guarantees that its territories will be returned".
</P>
<P>
Yemane said in a news release available here Wednesday that
Ethiopia's assertion "is certainly not compatible the major tenet
of the Framework Agreement and all subsequent documents" of the
OAU.
</P>
<P>
Eritrea and Ethiopia are accusing each other of having no
sincerity for peace settlement over their year-long border
conflict. 
