<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> More Canadian Teenage Students Use Drugs: Survey </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The Health Canada survey found 44 percent of boys and 41
percent of girls in Grade 10 used the two kinds of drugs three or
more times last year, the Globe and Mail newspaper reported.
</P>
<P>
The newspaper said it is an "alarm" increase since 1994, when
30 percent of boys and 27 percent of girls were reported to be
drug users.
</P>
<P>
The survey will be officially released next month in a report
of Trends in the Health of Canadian Youth as part of a World
Health Organization project.
</P>
<P>
The survey has also registered a large number of students
smoking, getting "really drunk" and cutting class.
</P>
<P>
At least twice in their lives, 43 percent of 15-year-old
Canadian boys and 42 percent of girls have been "really drunk,"
while more than 90 percent have tried alcohol.
</P>
<P>
Skipping class has emerged as another major problem in Canadian
schools, where 22 percent of boys had skipped three or more
classes by Grade 10 and 20 percent of girl students skipped at
least three, the survey said.
</P>
<P>
The newspaper urged public attention to the "disturbing
behavior that affects school performance for students between
Grade 6 and Grade 10." 
</P>
</TEXT>
