<HEADLINE> S. Africa to Go Ahead With Massive Arms Purchase </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, September 15 (Xinhua) -- The South African
government would go ahead with its controversial massive
arms-for-investment deal, South African Press Association (SAPA)
reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
There is no basis for allegations that ruling African National
Congress (ANC) parliamentarians have received kickbacks from rival
bidders aimed at influencing the arms acquisition process, Defense
Minister Patrick Lekota was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
He was reacting to Pan Africanist Congress parliamentarian
Patricia de Lille's announcement in the house last week that she
had received a document purportedly from disgruntled ANC
parliamentarians implicating several senior ANC members in
corruption.
</P>
<P>
De Lille had called for a commission of inquiry to investigate
into the controversial deal.
</P>
<P>
Lekota criticized De Lille for not making the source of the
document public, despite requests from various government
quarters.
</P>
<P>
He said he had approached Anglican Archbishop of Cape Town
Njongonkulu Ndungane to prevail on De Lille to make the names
public.
</P>
<P>
Lekota accused De Lille of wanting to raise her profile "at the
expense of using the SANDF (South African National Defense Force)
as a football".
</P>
<P>
The deal, which is worth 24 billion rands (4 billion U.S.
dollars), includes submarines, corvettes, maritime patrol
helicopters, light utility helicopters, fighter trainer planes and
fighter jets.
</P>
<P>
Companies from Sweden, Britain, Germany and Italy were named as
 preferred suppliers of the equipment last November. 
</P>
</TEXT>
