<HEADLINE> Zhu Rongji on Reform of State-Owned Enterprises (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHIJIAZHUANG, September 15 (Xinhua) -- Chinese Premier Zhu
Rongji has said that there needs to be a greater effort in
restructuring State-owned enterprises and promoting grain
marketing reform.
</P>
<P>
Zhu made the remark when he made a study tour of north China's
Hebei Province September 12 to 15.
</P>
<P>
He said that, over the past several months, the restructuring
of State-owned enterprises has gone well and that the enterprises
have had marked improvements in returns, and a large number of
them are out of or getting out of the economic mess.
</P>
<P>
This indicates that there has been a favorable turn in the
restructuring and development of State-owned enterprises, he said,
and this has increased people's confidence in the management and
it shows that the Party's restructuring policies are correct and
that the macro-economic measures since last year have been
successful.
</P>
<P>
However, he said, there is still a formidable task in solving
the State-owned enterprise problems and promoting the healthy
development of all enterprises.
</P>
<P>
President Jiang Zemin recently presided over a series of
meetings on this issue.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990915.0317 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zhu Rongji on Reform of State-owned Enterprises (3) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
However, he added, people should be conscious of the fact that
the reforms have gone somewhat unevenly and that there are still
contradictions and problems to be solved, and he pointed out that,
in some places, the government policy of purchasing as much grain
as farmers want to sell has not been fully implemented, while in
other places, government-run grain enterprises offer much lower
prices to farmers.
</P>
<P>
Purchasing as much grain as farmers want to sell is significant,
he emphasized, because it is only in this way that farmers'
interests can be protected when supply exceeds demand.
</P>
<P>
The State's policy on grain marketing reform needs to be
implemented, he went on to stress, especially the policy of buying
as much as farmers want to sell, and it needs to be done for
farmers' sake and for the development of the economy, even if the
State has to provide more subsidies.
</P>
<P>
The premier also said that the restructuring of agriculture and
grain production needs to be speeded up, he concluded. 
</P>
