<HEADLINE> China's Railways Gearing Up For 21st Century (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 15 (Xinhua) -- Editor's note: This year
marks the 50th anniversary of the founding of the People's
Republic of China. China's economic successes over the past five
decades have attracted the attention of the world. Xinhua began
issuing stories on the country's economy on August 17. This is the
23rd.
</P>
<P>
There are 66,000 km. of Chinese railway lines and the figure is
expected to grow to more than 70,000 km. in just a few years,
according to Minister of Railways Fu Zhihuan.
</P>
<P>
The country now ranks first in Asia in total length of railway
lines, but, when that figure is divided by the number of people in
Chgina, it is 5 centimeters, the length of a cigarette, Fu told
Xinhua.
</P>
<P>
In addition to that, the railway system is somewhat
unreasonable, because most railways are in coastal areas in the
East, so the Southwest will be given priority in new construction,
he explains.
</P>
<P>
That region includes Sichuan, Yunnan, and Guizhou provinces,
the Guangxi Zhuang and Tibet autonomous regions, and the municipal
area of Chongqing, or 26 percent of China's land. It is rich in
minerals, forests, and hydro-electric power resources.
</P>
</TEXT>
