<HEADLINE> China's Railways Gearing Up For 21st Century (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Ten more railway lines are being built and work started this
year on four more in the region and analysts predict that by 2002,
the rail transport capacity in southern China will double.
</P>
<P>
Fu also said that, in addition to the new railway lines, the
entire railway sector needs to be restructured to allow it to
compete with airlines and roads. From 1988 to 1998, the number of
domestic air passengers increased 196 percent and road travel went
up 75 percent. Railways, however, had 20 percent negative growth.
</P>
<P>
The first thing to do is to increase the speed of trains. The
technological renovation drives of 1997 and 1998 brought the
average speed of passenger trains up from 80 km. per hour to 140-
160 kmph on experimental lines.
</P>
<P>
Many major trains that depart at dusk and arrive at dawn are
now using trunk lines.
</P>
<P>
China also expects to start work in 2000 on the 1,300-km.
Beijing-Shanghai high-speed line for trains that run at a maximum
speed of 250 kmph.
</P>
