<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Poll: Palestinians Oppose Jerusalem as Israeli </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, September 15 (Xinhua) -- The overwhelming majority
of the Palestinians oppose any solution in the final status talks
which would recognize Jerusalem as the "unified capital" of Israel.
</P>
<P>
The opinion was expressed by 93.7 percent of the Palestinians
in a poll conducted by the Jerusalem-based Jerusalem Media and
Communication Center (JMCC) prior to last month's signing of the
Sharm El Sheikh memo, a revised version of the Wye interim accord.
</P>
<P>
The poll, conducted among 1,200 Palestinians in the West Bank
and Gaza Strip, said the majority of the Palestinians believe that
Jerusalem would constitute the final obstacle to the signing of
a lasting Palestinian-Israeli peace treaty.
</P>
<P>
Some 48.9 percent of those surveyed said Jerusalem must be the
capital of Palestine while 6.7 percent said the city should become
an international city and 5.1 percent said it should remain
unified as the capitals of two states.
</P>
<P>
The poll showed 44.5 percent of the Palestinians thought the
"attention and care on Jerusalem" taken by the Palestinian
National Authority (PNA) was "not enough," while 33.3 percent
believed the PNA gave "due attention and care" to the city.
</P>
<P>
The new deal signed by Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat and
Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak in Egypt stipulates that the two
sides should reach a framework of the final-status talks by next
February and a comprehensive lasting peace treaty by September,
2000.
</P>
<P>
Besides the status of Jerusalem, other thorny issues the two
sides have to face in future talks include the nature and borders
of the Palestinian entity, the fate of over 3 million Palestinian
refugees and the future of the Jewish settlement in the West Bank
and Gaza Strip.
</P>
<P>
Regarding the performance of the PNA, 58.9 percent of the
Palestinians said "good" or "very good" while 34.3 percent said
"bad," the poll said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990915.0328 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> European Parliament Endorses New EU Commission </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, September 15 (Xinhua) -- The European Parliament
Wednesday formally endorsed the new European Commission led by
Romano Prodi, according to reports from Strasbourg, where the
parliament is located.
</P>
<P>
The European Parliament deputies voted 404 in favor, 153
against and 37 abstaining to give investiture to the new executive
body of the European Union (EU), which will serve from January 22,
2000 to January 22, 2005.
</P>
<P>
This result helped the EU out of an institutional crisis
beginning six months ago when the outgoing EU commission led by
Jacques Santer resigned en masse because of charges of
administrative irregularities.
</P>
<P>
Prodi and his 19 commissioners will be sworn in at the European
Court of Justice in Luxembourg Friday and will hold their first
formal session in Brussels later that day.
</P>
<P>
A majority of Euro-deputies, including the Christian-Democrats
and their right wing allies, Socialists, Liberals and Greens,
voted in favor, while neo-Communists, Eurosceptics and extreme-
right groups voted against.
</P>
<P>
Some deputies from the British Conservative Party and the
German Christian Democrats had tried to persuade Prodi to replace
the commissioner Philippe Busquin, who is in charge of research,
from the Belgian Socialist Party, alleging he should be
responsible for the food contamination scandals.
</P>
<P>
Prodi rejected their demand but promised to make "profound and
severe examinations." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
