<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Consumer Prices Rise 0.3 Percent in August </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 15 (Xinhua) -- U.S. consumer prices rose
0.3 percent in August as energy costs surged for a second
consecutive month, the Labor Department reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
In both August and July, energy was the big force pushing
prices upward. For August, two-thirds of the total price increase
was attributed to a 2.7 percent jump in energy costs. Food costs
edged up a small 0.2 percent, the report said.
</P>
<P>
If excluding the volatile energy and food categories, prices
were up just 0.1 percent in August.
</P>
<P>
This performance of the "core" rate of inflation was even
better than economists' expectations and will provide ammunition
for those arguing there is no need for the Federal Reserve to
boost interest rates for a third time.
</P>
<P>
So far this year, consumer prices have been rising at an annual
rate of 2.6 percent, compared with a gain of just 1.6 percent for
all of 1998. However, all of the increase reflects higher energy
costs, which have rebounded this year after a steep plunge in 1998
that reflected slumping global demand in the wake of steep
recessions in many nations hit by a global currency crisis.
</P>
<P>
The August's 2.7 percent jump in energy costs was even bigger
than July's 2.1 percent increase. Gasoline prices advanced 5.6
percent last month and are up 25.1 percent at an annual rate so
far this year.
</P>
<P>
The 0.2 percent rise in food prices in August matched the
modest July increase. Clothing prices fell by 0.3 percent, the
fourth consecutive drop.
</P>
<P>
Airline fares fell by 2.7 percent in August after having posted
a sharp 6.5 percent increase in July. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990915.0333 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Governor of Bank of Italy Calls For Labor Flexibility </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, September 15 (Xinhua) -- The Italian central bank's
Governor Antonio Fazio said Wednesday that Italy could achieve
solid growth if the labor market was made more flexible, taxes
were reduced and the public administration was streamlined.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the inauguration of a new branch of Bank of Italy,
the central bank, on the outskirts of Rome, Fazio agreed with
analysts that the economy appeared to be picking up again.
</P>
<P>
But he said swift and decisive action was needed to make sure
the recovery gained strength and led to sturdy and constant growth
in coming years.
</P>
<P>
"In Europe and Italy the signs of recovery seen in recent
months are being confirmed," he said. "In order to set off
sustained growth favoring a stable increase in employment, we must
act in a prompt and coordinated way."
</P>
<P>
Firstly, the central banker said, the government needed to
demonstrate with concrete actions that it intended to create the
right conditions for businesses to invest.
</P>
<P>
Secondly, Fazio said, a new wage policy was necessary in order
to allow a more flexible use of labor and capital and a closer
correlation between salaries, output and company profits.
</P>
<P>
Lastly, there was still a mound of red-tape standing in the way
of business initiative, he said.
</P>
<P>
What was needed was "a radical streamlining of rules and
procedures, allowing a relationship between citizens, companies
and public bodies which is conducive to economic activity," he
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990915.0334 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> German Exposition Welcoming Chinese Visitors </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 15 (Xinhua) -- German Ambassador to China
Christian Ueberschaeer said here today he hopes more Chinese can
join the approximately 40 million people expected at EXPO 2000,
which is being held in the city of Hanover from June 1 to October
31 next year.
</P>
<P>
At the German embassy this afternoon, Ueberschaeer said that
this is the first time for Germany to hold the international
exposition and that it is the best time for China to display its
culture, economy, and society since the two Germanys were reunited
ten years ago.
</P>
<P>
The exposition has a theme of "Mankind-Nature-Technology". It
will display new ideas about humanity, the environment, health,
knowledge, information, jobs, transportation, and energy. It has
already attracted some 193 countries and organizations.
</P>
<P>
Germany's CAISSA GmbH has been appointed official agent for
tickets and tourism affairs in China and Lufthansa plans to add a
number of flights.  
</P>
</TEXT>
