<HEADLINE> S'pore to Develop ICT Industry as Key Growth Sector </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, September 15 (Xinhua) -- A senior Singapore official
has said his country will make the Information and Communications
Technology (ICT) as the key driver in its Digital Economy and
develop the industry as the key growth sector in Singapore's
economy and society with an aim to transform the city-state into a
"dynamic and vibrant ICT capital."
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the Chief Information Officer Forum Dinner Held by
the Business Week, Singapore Minister of State for Communications
&AMP; Information Technology and Trade &AMP; Industry Lim Swee Say said
ICT will be the "key driver in the Digital Economy and Information
Society of the future."
</P>
<P>
"We want to develop the ICT sector as the key growth sector in
Singapore's economy," Lim said.
</P>
<P>
Lim said that as a result of its three-phased sustained efforts
over a 20-year period, Singapore has become one of the most
computerized nations in the world.
</P>
<P>
He said Singapore began laying foundation in ICT in 1981 and
progressed through three "developmental stages" -- from the
National Computerization Program of 1981 to 1985, through the
National Information Technology Plan of 1986 to 1990 and to the
1992-launched IT2000 Masterplan under which Singapore promoted the
export of IT products and services.
</P>
<P>
Lim said Singapore's vision in IT2000 is to transform Singapore
into an "Intelligent Island."
</P>
<P>
The three objectives contained in the ICT21 Master Plan are to
develop the ICT industry as the key growth sector in Singapore's
economy, to actively exploit ICT in every major sector of the
economy and to use ICT to enhance the quality of life and standard
of living of Singaporeans in an Information Society.
</P>
<P>
Quoting a finding in a study on Singapore's digital economy
conducted by the National University of Singapore, Lim said
Singapore's digital economy generated about 90 billion Singapore
dollars (54 billion U.S. dollars) in revenue in 1996 and this
encompassed areas like IT goods manufacturing, IT services, IT
wholesale and retail, Telecommunications, media, content services,
business services and research.
</P>
<P>
The average annual growth rate of the digital economy between
1986 and 1996 was 19 percent and the contribution of the digital
economy to Singapore's GDP was estimated at 16 percent in 1996, a
steady rise from 11 percent in 1986, he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
