<HEADLINE> Australian Parliamentary Leader Praises Tibet's Development </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LHASA, September 15 (Xinhua) -- Garry Nehl, the deputy speaker
of the House of Representatives of Australia's Federal Parliament,
said here today that he was surprised at the great changes in the
Tibet Autonomous Region of China.
</P>
<P>
Garry made the remarks during a meeting with Li Liguo, the
deputy secretary of the Communist Party of China's Tibet
Autonomous Region Committee.
</P>
<P>
This is Garry's second visit to Tibet since 1992. He said he
was deeply impressed by the new buildings, schools, hospitals, and
shops he saw over the past four days.
</P>
<P>
Li said that the number of schools in the region went from 3,
000 to over 4,200 in the past seven years, and that 81.3 percent
of school-age children are attending school.
</P>
<P>
Life expectancy of Tibetans also went from 35 years 40 years
ago to 65 years today because of the improved health care, Li said.
However, people in the region lack iodine and suffer from diseases
caused by iodine deficiencies, so aid from the Australia and the
rest of the international community is welcome. 
</P>
</TEXT>
