<HEADLINE> Incendiary Device Explodes in N.Ireland </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, September 15 (Xinhua) -- An incendiary device exploded
in the doorway of a furniture shop in Northern Ireland Wednesday,
causing no injures.
</P>
<P>
Police said the blast occurred at 11:25 a.m. (1025 GMT) in
Ballycastle, County Antrim. Two other devices have also been
found.
</P>
<P>
The man who owns the Xplorus store, Frank McCahan, said he had
no idea why his premises was targeted and believed the device was
pushed through the letter box.
</P>
<P>
He said the main concern was for people living in an upstairs
flat.
</P>
<P>
He said there was no one in the shop when the fire started, but
other shop owners spotted smoke coming out of the doorway.
</P>
<P>
They called the fire brigade who managed to put the flames out,
and there was only smoke damage to the property.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, police said another device was found outside a shop
in Ann Street in the town.
</P>
<P>
A third incendiary was later discovered at a Credit Union
premises in Castle Street in nearby Ballymoney. It was removed
into the street.
</P>
<P>
No warnings were given about any of the devices, according to
the Royal Ulster Constabulary.
</P>
<P>
The police have asked all shopkeepers in both towns to check
their premises.
</P>
<P>
Northern Ireland First Minister David Trimble said it was too
early to know who was responsible and he was not going to jump to
conclusions.
</P>
<P>
"Obviously there is concern about any attack, any development
of that nature is not going to encourage confidence in the (peace)
process," he said.
</P>
<P>
He said it reinforced his party's concern "about whether the
paramilitaries are really committed to progress and really
committed to implementing the agreement in the way we would like
to." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
