<DOCNO> XIE19990915.0339 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Manila Gives More Incentives to Multinational Firms </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, September 15 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine Senate
Wednesday passed a bill which seeks to give additional incentives
to multinational companies and create a sound economic climate in
the country.
</P>
<P>
The bill, providing tax exemption for regional headquarters
(RHQ) and regional operating headquarters (ROHQ) of multinational
companies, is one of the 25 priority measures certified urgent by
the Philippine government.
</P>
<P>
An RHQ is defined as a foreign business whose purpose is to act
as an administrative branch of a multinational company engaged in
international trade.
</P>
<P>
Meantime, ROHQs, which are allowed to engage in
income-generating activities such as general administration and
planning, business coordination and development, training and
other qualifying services, are required a minimum paid-in capital
of 200,000 U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
Ramon Magsaysay, chair of the Senate committee on trade and
commerce, said in his sponsorship speech that the RHQ is a foreign
investor's way of "testing the waters" to find out if a specific
country is a viable investment site.
</P>
<P>
"The presence of regional headquarters sends a signal that the
base country is stable and competitive, with a corps of quality
workforce and facilities," he added.
</P>
<P>
According to the bill, exempt from tax and customs duties is
the importation by RHQs and ROHQs of equipment and materials not
available locally for conferences and training.
</P>
<P>
Under the bill, they may also import motor vehicles but these
will be subjected to duties and taxes, Magsaysay explained.
</P>
<P>
The bill also extends the validity of multiple entry special
visas granted to foreign personnel to three years.
</P>
<P>
At present, the Philippines is host to 610 RHQs. Hong Kong has
2,100, Malaysia close to 1,000 and Singapore 2,500. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
